[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Dear Chess friend,   Before delving into chess details inside the course, I would like to write a few words about my upcoming course that you are going to witness. All my life as a chess player I hated the opening ceremonies – I could not wait for my game to begin! – so I will try to be brief and to the point.   Being a professional chess player, I usually had to smile seeing titles such as “ Winning with the Attacking 1.b4” or “Crushing the Najdorf” etc. Yes, maybe this does increase sales, but it has nothing to do with the objective evaluation – and it is maybe even misleading the “reader” to a certain point.   I guess “ MVL” would love to know, finally, why his beloved Najdorf is refuted, and not by Carlsen, Caruana or Giri in their secret files, but by a book that costs 25 Euros and can be ordered online!  In my work, I tried to stay objective, even if the course is made from the side of the black pieces.   Most of the time, during chess events, I had the feeling that I have no chances of getting an advantage with White...and being worse in all my lines with Black! This is a typical situation for almost all serious players, and this is the way the human brain works. We know what we are afraid of, but the opponent doesn't and almost certainly faces the same situation.   The Nimzo/Bogo opening repertoire that you are going to discover is a solid, lifetime opening choice that you will be able to start playing immediately and, with some small adjustments @@StartBracket@@popular openings such as the Nimzo/Bogo are always advancing theoretically@@EndBracket@@ for at least the next decade.   The lines are a combination of mainly solid structures, but you will also encounter some of the “must be remembered” variations, avoiding getting into trouble during the first 10-15 moves of the opening.   The Nimzo/Bogo is an opening that is much less forced than, let’s say, the “Grünfeld” and can be mainly played based on experience and good positional understanding in most cases. Still, some % of the lines have to be memorized correctly due to the complexity of the positions and can hardly be correctly executed in a practical game only using “feelings”.   Personally, I still think that somehow it feels correct to fight for the center, and playing ...Nf6, ...e6, ...Bb4 is just logical. During the games where I chose to play the KID instead, for example, my thoughts were often going in the direction: “I am playing without the center; how can my position be normal?” Probably all of this is a matter of taste, and dependent on one’s playing style. Still, in my personal opinion, if you are not a professional chess player, it is much easier to have a nice game playing with the center than without it.   I would also like to give my personal advice on “how to remember” the lines.   Only professional players have enough time for daily repetition of the pgns, again and again and again. In most cases, one or other of the players forgets his/her lines and the game has a “fresh” continuation. In today's analyses, which are mainly made by human+engine at the top level, many of the moves are very hard to understand and explain. This is why, in many opening files of hobby or amateur players, there are also very scary computer lines which in 99.9% of the cases will never be seen on board, because of one simple reason: the moves are illogical, which equates to “hard to remember”.  Players often, or even usually, already choose the wrong @@StartBracket@@i.e. not computer-suggested!@@EndBracket@@ road within the first 10 moves of the opening.   In today's chess, the top 5 engine suggestions might be impossible to guess, even for a strong GM, so to me this has no practical value. We all forget the lines, but we should be playing lines that we are able to understand, to bring to the board with logic and not by pure memorization.   And here comes the problem of the author when you try to make a good job: engine lines are not really practical, but the “human” lines could be easily criticized by anybody with an engine.   I decided that I would try to stay as much as I can in the form of “human” but, I assure you, all the lines that you are going to find have been checked with a good engine. Give it a try and prove me wrong :@@EndBracket@@ I would be most thankful, as I could then implement it into my own games!   My advice: make more out of your time – focus on knowing the “main” lines, the rest you can do over the board. Do not expect to win out of the opening, but appreciate a solid and playable position so you are psychologically ready to fight. And actually why are we playing chess if we do not enjoy the game?! Personally, I do, and the element of a tough fighting game is what excites me!   I wish you all great results with your games in the Nimzo/Bogo opening family, and let it be your lucky opening choice – we all need a bit of luck in our games!   GM Arkadij Naiditsch  
Chessable note: A few times in the course recordings GM Naiditsch invites the student to consult the .pgn files of the course. Chessable does not make .pgn files available to users, but of course the referenced chapter can be consulted in the course itself on Chessable. Or students may use the browse repertoire tree function, available among the options on the right side menu in the course. }
