[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.g3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ Playing the Nimzo-Indian in Catalan-style has become really popular nowadays due to some new ideas against the main ... d5 setups. The second most popular line against the system is to play with  4...c5  , but it transposes to some main lines after  5.Nf3  which we don't play. Therefore, I suggest a relatively rare, but perfectly playable system here. }
4... Bxc3+
{ Black is aiming for a strategic position, where the main c4-weakness can be more easily attacked once the bishop is developed to g2. }
5. bxc3 d6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black has two plans in this position: one is to push ...e5, and the other is to attack the c4-pawn with ...b6, ...Ba6 and ...Na5. The last move perfectly supports both. }
8. O-O e5
{ I already prefer Black's position here, or at least it is much easier to play. We are still targeting the c4 weakness, but in some cases we can also use the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal and sometimes the plan of pushing e4 can also be better for Black. White has tried a lot of moves here, and almost everything was played by good GMs, but none of them seem to be successful. }
9. Rb1
{ Now it is important to play h6.  9.Ne1  ,  9.d5  ,  9.Qa4  and Shirov's  9.Bg5  are the continuations analyzed in the first chapter. }
9... h6 { Preventing Bg5 first and only after this continuing with ...Re8. }
10. Ba3
{ Black was also better after  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Qc2  Qe7  in the game Zajogin-Kazakovskiy, Germany 2020. In the case of @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pp1/2np1n1p/4p3/2PP4/2P2NP1/P3PPBP/1RBQ1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c5  , Black can get a better position after  10...e4!  11.Nd2  and now both  11...d5  and  11...Re8  are good. }
10... Re8 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Qc1 Qd7
{ After this strong continuation, Black was just better in Naoum-Saric, Greece 2017. In the case of White moving the rook on d1, attacking the queen, we always have the idea of playing ...Qg4 attacking the c4-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.f3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3
{ This is quite a popular line, played from time to time by many top players. For example, Mamedyarov has enjoyed many nice games with it. }
4... d5
{ We will choose the variation with  4...d5  .  Maybe it is not the most popular solution, but I think it is an interesting option to avoid the main-line theory. }
5. a3 { White has nothing better. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ There are different options here as well, but we will only focus on  6...O-O }
6... O-O 7. cxd5
{ 7.e3  does not have its own significance as after  7...c5  we should transpose to the main lines with  8.cxd5  exd5  . }
7... exd5 8. e3 c5 9. Bd3
{ White has no better piece setup than this: other moves have no real meaning and White has to aim to castle short as soon as possible. }
9... b6 { We want to exchange the c8-bishop for the d3-bishop. } 10. Ne2 Ba6
{ A bit similar to our 4.e3 Nimzo-Indian variation, we are also exchanging the strong-light squared bishop from a6 and aim to get a position with a potentially better structure and leave White to suffer with their c1-bishop. However, things are not so simple, unfortunately... this variation is very strategic for both sides.   It is all about the e4-move: White needs to get it in at any cost to occupy the center and to activate the bishop, and Black needs to fight against it, or, when Black can no longer hold it back, there are typical ideas for making it less effective. Both sides have their standard ideas to support their plans. Of course, there are some concrete lines to learn, but in general, this line is more about understanding. }
11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Re8 { The fight continues for and against the e4 move. }
13. Ng3 Nc6
{ Attacking the d4-pawn, and now White has two ways to continue the preparation for e4. }
14. Bb2
{ The main line and also the most critical continuation. White does not waste any time and is ready to push e4 next. Therefore, Black must start the standard counterplay to destabilize the g3-knight...   14.Ra2  With the idea of Re2, Bb2 and e4 is considered to be less critical as it gives more time for Black to prepare their counterplay. This line can be found here. }
14... h5 { We once again prevent the e4-push because of ...h4. } 15. e4
{ This is very interesting and definitely one of the most critical lines. White has scored almost 100% with this move, defeating many good players. In almost all these games Black continued with the most natural move ...h4, but that leads to White's advantage in some very concrete tactical lines. My improvement has been played in only one game so far... }
15... c4
{ White has 4 squares to go to with the queen, but against each one Black finds great counterplay. Attention please! In the following lines it matters greatly when we need to start with ...h4, and when with ...dxe4! }
16. Qe2 h4 { We are going for the e4-pawn. } 17. Nf5 dxe4 18. fxe4
{ This time Black needs to take with the rook on e4. } 18... Rxe4 19. Qf3 Re6
{ And Black would like to play ...Qd5 next, with a perfect position. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5
{ The so-called Leningrad System of the Nimzo-Indian defence. It used to be a major and very serious weapon in the past, but nowadays it is out of fashion, mainly because modern computers showed a safe way to completely neutralize this system.   A very important point to note is that many times the ...h6/Bh4 pair of moves are included as a kind of automatic response. However, in this variation, it is key to avoid this inclusion! We are going to see why in the main line! }
4... c5 5. d5
{ The only critical move and the whole point of the system. Other moves, such as  5.Rc1  cxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.Qxf6  gxf6  , already lead to a better endgame for Black. }
5... d6 6. e3
{ In general, White would like to build a d5-e4-f3 pawn structure, but it must be done slowly, completing development first, otherwise White can get into trouble. The concrete  6.e4  would be met by  6...Bxc3+  7.bxc3  h6  and White is forced to give up the important bishop, otherwise White simply loses the e4-pawn. But even after  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  Black is better because of the weaknesses in White's structure. }
6... exd5 7. cxd5 Nbd7
{ Black prepares ...Qa5 by protecting the knight on f6. White's concrete problem is that should he complete development with Bd3, Nge2 and O-O, the d5-pawn will be hanging. Otherwise, there is no natural way to get the pieces to healthy positions in time. }
8. Bd3 Qa5
{ Just in time before the knight arrives to e2 and White can play O-O. Black now wins a pawn and the question is if White is able to create enough compensation... }
9. Ne2 Nxd5
{ Move 9 and we are a pawn up – usually not a bad sign for an interesting game! }
10. O-O Bxc3
{ Attention!!! An important move to be remembered – and not an easy move to play over the board in case you are repeating this line. }
11. bxc3
{ 11.Nxc3?  blunders a piece after  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  and now  12...c4!  attacking both bishops. }
11... c4
{ This is the key move of the variation and the reason why we did not include ...h6 earlier. The bishop on g5 stands in a lot of motifs by the queen. For example,  12.Bxc4?  loses to  12...N5b6!  with a double attack, and @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp1n1ppp/3p4/q2n2B1/2p5/2PBP3/P3NPPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Be4  also walks into  12...N5f6  and White has to give up its bishop, but then Black is just a pawn up. }
12. Bc2 { Other bishop moves are worse. } 12... O-O
{ We have reached the critical position from White's point of view, where the first player has to search for interesting options and compensation. However, thanks to the strong computers of the modern era, it seems the conlcusion is that the maximum for White here is to reach equality with very precise play, otherwise, White is just facing trouble. }
13. Bh4
{ It is best to remove the bishop from the tactical ideas.   13.Ng3  ,  13.Qd4  ,  13.Nd4  and  13.Rb1  are the continuations analyzed in the third chapter. }
13... Nxc3 14. Bxh7+
{ White is winning back one pawn, but this is not even enough for equality. }
14... Kxh7 15. Qc2+ Kg8 16. Nxc3 Ne5
{ The knight finds an excellent outpost on d3. White's problem is that even after winning the d6-pawn. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Bd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2
{ Recently this move has started to enjoy some popularity even at the highest level. However, in most cases, White plays e3 next move or after Nf3, and those lines transpose to the  4.e3  Nimzo-Indian,  5.Bd2 variations. In this game, we will only be checking the alternative moves, but they are not dangerous at all, as we will see. }
4... O-O 5. Nf3 { 5.e3  d5  transposes to the 4.e3 Nimzo-Indian. } 5... d5 6.
a3
{ This line was recently played by Ivanchuk and Korobov.  6.e3  is the main move, but it would again just transpose to the 4. e3 Nimzo-Indian with 5. Bd2 where we meet 6. e3 with 6...b6. }
6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ White has achieved something at least – the bishop pair. On the other hand, Black is in time to create dynamic play and equalize... }
7... dxc4
{ I suggest this most challenging approach for Black as it is not that obvious how White can win back or compensate for the sacrificed pawn. Black wants to hold the extra pawn by playing ...b5, but  8.Qa4  would be a mistake as it runs into  8...Qd5!  when ... b5 next move leaves White without compensation. }
8. e3
{ 8.a4  seems to win back the pawn after all, but Black has many ways to equalize because having already played 6. a3 the further a-pawn move is a loss of tempo. The line can be found here. }
8... b5 9. b3
{ Undermining moves such as b3 are typical for Catalan structures, but right now it is already White who needs to be careful not to end up in a worse position. }
9... cxb3 10. Bxb5
{ White should rather play  10.Qxb3  and try to play for compensation, even though Black has the simple ...a6 and in my opinion there is not much to fear. Now, White might get into some trouble... }
10... Qd5 { A very tricky move. } 11. Ba4 b2 { The key idea! } 12. Bxb2 Ba6
{ And White is facing serious difficulties with castling, which naturally gives Black great play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3
{ The Saemisch Variation of the Nimzo-Indian. A very sharp opening that resides in the repertoire of many top players, who often use it as a dangerous surprise weapon – especially those players who also like the  4.f3  system, as these two lines often lead to similar positions. It is a very concrete provocation of the bishop to take on c3. White forces the damage of their own pawn structure, but intends to compensate for this with the bishop pair and a very strong center, which is often occupied with the further move e4. }
4... Bxc3+ { We have no real choice but to take the knight. } 5. bxc3 O-O
{ It is very important to castle first to get the right move order. Now, White must occupy the center with e4 and there are two ways to do it: the main line is  6.f3  here, however, in that case, Black plays  4...d5  and we transpose to the Nimzo-Indian 4.f3 variation. Please see the 4.f3 chapter. }
6. e3
{ With the idea of completing development first with Bd3 and Ne2 and only later pushing e4. This position also arises from the Nimzo-Indian @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  variation after  4...O-O  5.a3  Bxc3  . }
6... d6
{ There are many other playable setups as well, but the practice has shown that Black has excellent chances to grab the initiative with the current line. }
7. Bd3 e5 8. e4
{ 8.Ne2  e4!  Closing the diagonal, not allowing White to occupy the center with e4 and getting ready to attack the c4-weakness. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. }
8... exd4
{ Usually it is not advisable to release the tension and improve White's pawn structure, but Black has a concrete idea in mind. }
9. cxd4 Nxe4
{ Taking the most important central pawn, as  10.Bxe4  Re8  wins back the piece without sufficient compensation for White. }
10. Ne2 Re8 11. O-O d5
{ Black is a pawn up, which is usually a good sign. The computer gives compensation for White here, but at most, it is only enough for equality with precise play from White. }
