[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Nf3 with 5.Qc2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ A very solid system for Black which might also arise from the Queen's Indian move-order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.Nc3  Bb4  .  Since Nf3 is a flexible move for White, there are now a wide list of alternatives to the main  5.Bg5  line, but often they will just transpose to other Nimzo-Indian variations. }
5. Qc2 Bb7 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 O-O
{ We can only reach this position from this current move-order since after@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  we play  4...d5  .  However, White has already made their decision with Nf3, which used to be a popular move in the past, but nowadays it is completely out of fashion and it is considered to be a harmless line @@StartBracket@@from the 4.Qc2 move-order we have the same position, just with the knight still on g1 and the bishop on c8, and the only critical move there is Bg5 with f3 or e3 setups@@EndBracket@@. White now has three possible setups: e3, g3 or Bg5. }
8. Bg5 d6 9. Nd2
{ The most common move with the idea of occupying the center with f3-e4. It has been played in the past by Carlsen, Kasparov and other legendary players. }
9... Nbd7 10. e3
{ Is the alternative for White and now it is important to start with ...Rc8.  10.f3  the most concrete move, preparing to push e4, can be found here. }
10... Rc8 { To be able to recapture on c5 with the rook after ...c5, dxc5. }
11. f3 c5 12. dxc5
{ The standard reaction for White in this variation, but now the twin, deep ideas of playing ...Rc8 first and having not included ...h6, Bh4 pays off! }
12... Rxc5 { Now we see the key idea behnd ... Rc8. } 13. Bh4
{ And here Shirov grabbed the initiative against Krush in Edmonton 2005 with the powerful ...b5! }
13... b5 14. b4 { And now it would have been even stronger to play ...Rc7. }
14... Rc7 { When White loses control over the center. } 15. c5 a6
{ Protects b5 and prepares to take on c5. } *

