[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Nf3 with 5.Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ A very solid system for Black which might also arise from the Queen's Indian move-order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.Nc3  Bb4  .  Since Nf3 is a flexible move for White, there are now a wide list of alternatives to the main  5.Bg5  line, but often they will just transpose to other Nimzo-Indian variations. }
5. Qb3
{ A very serious alternative to the main line, played frequently by Mamedyarov. }
5... c5
{ In this variation, Black often, instead of the natural ...Bb7, quickly puts strong pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6 and possibly later switches attention to the c4-pawn with ...Na5 and ...Ba6. }
6. Bg5 { Pinning the knight is the most common continuation. } 6... h6 7. Bh4
g5 8. Bg3 Ne4
{ Black is ready to create doubled pawns for long-term weaknesses and also to remove the strong g3-bishop. }
9. e3
{ 9.O-O-O  is risky in view of  9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Nc6  and the pawns are easily attackable by our typical manoeuvres ...Na5, ...Ba6 and ... Rc8, leaving the king also exposed on c1.  Here I played @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p2p1p2/1p2p2p/2p3p1/1bPPn3/1QN1PNB1/PP3PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  against Kramnik, which is playable, but I also like the following continuation. }
9... Bb7 10. d5
{ Played by Topalov against Georgiev in 2013. The point is to not allow the knight to develop to c6, but Black has other good places for the knight. }
10... d6 11. O-O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3
{ And here Black should have just played ...Qf6. } 12... Qf6 13. Kb2 Nd7
{ And only Black can be better with his superior structure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Nf3 with 5.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5
{ The Nimzo line with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  b6  5.Bg5  may look dangerous, but with exact play, Black has good play and can reach interesting positions. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 g5
{ It is more common to reach our main line from the ...Bb7 move order either now, or on the previous move, but in this way we can avoid the dangerous  7.Nd2  line. }
7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. e3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d6 11. Bd3
{ Once again, the move  11.Nd2  leads to the type of positions that we discussed in the 8.Rc1 Bb7 line after  11...Nxg3  12.hxg3  Nd7  . }
11... f5
{ Black successfully secures the outpost of the knight on e4 and the control of the h1-a8 diagonal. However, Black has also weakened their structure, so White must urgently try to make use of this before Black completes development with ...Nd7 and starts an attack with ...h5. }
12. d5
{ A known idea. White tries to sacrifice a pawn to close the long diagonal, in order to damage the healthy pawn chain and to get the very nice d4-square for his knight, after which the black steed on e4 can be kicked out with f3. The drawbacks of the move are that it gives up the c5-square, and in the long-term the doubled c-pawns will be doomed. }
12... Na6
{ The knight heads immediately to the weakened square. There are other options as well, but I prefer this very principled main idea. }
13. Bxe4
{ One test of the previous move could be to accept the pawn sacrifice... }
13... fxe4 14. Qxe4 Qf6 15. O-O O-O-O 16. Qxe6+ Qxe6 17. dxe6 Bxf3
{ It is important to get rid of the knight as, after Nd4, White could use the kingside pawn majority more effectively. }
18. gxf3 Nc5
{ This position has been reached in several grandmaster games and Black has never had any problems, despite being a pawn down after the capture on e6. There are many reasons for this, one being that in this whole variation, in many lines the bishop on g3 is restricted by the d6/c7 pawns and it is simply unable to improve. Another factor is obviously the poor structure of the remaining white pawns. Actually, it is interesting, but this position is even given as better for Black according to the strongest engines. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.e3 and 5.Nge2 without 8.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2
{ Welcome to the Reshevsky System, which received huge attention after Carlsen defeated Anand with it in only 29 moves at the Tal Memorial tournament in Moscow, 2013. }
5... c6
{ Our choice here is an interesting 'sideline' which I consider to be an attractive alternative to the main lines with 5...d5.  The main idea for Black is to bring the bishop to c7 - and its position on c7 is actually a great one! At first view, it will look a bit scary, and visually better for White, but in fact, the position is very dynamic and it is anything other than easy to prove an advantage. Please do not make the mistake of thinking that the move   5...c6  is made just to play ...d5 sometime soon, and then on White's cxd5 to answer ...cxd5 - this is not the point of our line at all. }
6. a3 Ba5 7. b4
{ The most natural move for White.  7.c5  has been tried by Wesley So, but it doesn't seem to be dangerous.  7.Ng3  and  7.Qc2  are analyzed in chapter 10. }
7... Bc7
{ Finally, we have reached the most critical position of the entire line. } 8.
Ng3
{ The main and most dangerous move is  8.e4  which is analyzed in the next variation.   8.Bb2  d5  9.Ng3  Nbd7  transposes to 8. Ng3 d5 9. Bb2 }
8... d5 9. Bb2 Nbd7 { We are ready for the ...e5 thrust. } 10. Bd3
{ 10.cxd5  exd5  makes little sense for White with his bishop on b2.  10.f4  and  10.Rc1  are also analyzed in chapter 10. }
10... e5 { Finally! } 11. cxd5 exd4
{ We have this intermediate capture on d4. } 12. exd4 Re8+
{ A nice check with tempo. } 13. Nge2 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. O-O Nb6
{ Black is better because of the poor b2-bishop and the huge hole on c4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.e3 and 5.Nge2 with 8.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2 c6 6. a3 Ba5 7. b4 Bc7 8. e4
{ The most ambitious and dangerously straightforward plan. White is trying to gain as much space as possible and Black has to react very precisely just to avoid complete suffocation. However, pawns don't move backwards, and if Black succeeds in undermining the opponent's center, then the initiative can easily be regained. }
8... d5 { Black has to act and this central counter is the right way. } 9. e5
{ Other continuations are not that dangerous, for example  9.Ng3  e5!  and the center opens in Black's favor. }
9... Nfd7
{ This looks a bit ugly, but it works. First of all, Black is ready to move this knight further to b6 and c4, and if White prevents it with c4-c5 then the typical knight sacrifice on e5 is very interesting in many cases. }
10. Nf4
{ A logical response. White prevents ...f7-f6 but Black has another @@StartBracket@@not obvious at all@@EndBracket@@ way to undermine the opponent's center. }
10... a5
{ We need to activate the rook on a8 to fight against White's central pawns. }
11. Rb1 { 11.b5  c5!  and Black successfully undermines the e5-pawn. } 11...
axb4 12. axb4
{ On first sight, White's position looks preferable, but here comes the key move of the whole line... }
12... c5
{ This is the most important tactical resource, one that justifies the whole setup. Without this move, White would just be comfortably better. }
13. bxc5
{ This capture is a must.  13.dxc5  it doesn't make sense for White to give away the e5-pawn.  13...dxc4  14.Bxc4  Nxe5  is just a nice position for Black. }
13... Ba5 14. Bd2 dxc4 { 14...Nc6  is also strong. } 15. Bxc4 Nxe5
{ It is quite amazing how often the move ...Nxe5 works! } 16. dxe5 Qd4
{ With a double attack on the c4-bishop and the c3-knight. Black wins back the sacrificed piece and keeps a small edge. }
17. Qb3 Bxc3 { Still! Beautiful to the very end. } 18. Bxc3
{ 18.Qxc3?  Qe4+!  is the key, with White losing the b1-rook. } 18... Qxf4 19.
O-O Bd7
{ Most probably the game is going to end in a draw, but one thing is clear - Black for sure doesn't experience any difficulties here. ...Bc6 with ...Nd7 could be the next moves, giving a very nice position with which to continue the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3
{ Welcome to the absolute mainline of the 4.e3 Nimzo. The game is going to be mostly positional and we will need to understand the basic ideas to be able playing the opening well. }
5... d5 6. cxd5
{ We will start with the  6.cxd5  line and then continue with the other 3 main continuations:  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  , and  6.a3 }
6... exd5
{ As in most of the lines I advocate, we recapture on d5 with ...exd5. Personally, I have never been afraid of White's cxd5 - in these structures I have always had great confidence in Black's position. }
7. Ne2 Re8
{ ...Re8 is a useful move in many scenarios: it gives Black the option of playing ...Bf8, and places extra pressure on White's center in case they have any f3-e4 ideas. }
8. O-O Bd6
{ 8...b6  is possible as well, but it is a different line. Another important thing to remember is that the sacrifice Bxh2+ followed by ... Ng4 doesn't work in most cases! }
9. f3
{ Other possible moves for White are  9.Nf4  ,  9.Bd2  and  9.a3  - all of them are analyzed in chapter 12. }
9... c5
{ On White's f3 we usually answer with ...c5 - that's the key point to remember. Also, it is nice that we are still having the b8-knight at home rather than on d7, because the next move could be ...Nc6 with pressure on White's center. }
10. Rf2
{ 10.Qe1  is the most played move in the position, and can be found here. }
10... Nc6 11. g4
{ It has been tried by many good players, but it hardly can be evaluated as 'interesting'. Black could launch counterplay with ...a6, and ...b5, just like in the 10.a3 line, but here also a sacrifice gives Black an edge. }
11... cxd4 12. exd4 Bxg4 { A beautiful move, opening White's king position. }
13. fxg4 Nxg4 14. Rg2 { 14.Rf3  Qh4  15.h3  Nh2  is decisive. } 14... Qh4
{ Suddenly, all the black pieces are in the attack. } 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Nxf4 Ne3
{ And it is easy to see that something has gone very wrong for White. You can find more in-depth analysis here. }
