[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.a3 with 9.Ne2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3
{ White forces Black to take on c3. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
{ We are faced with an interesting position: White has the bishop pair which is clearly a plus and theoretically - if White manages to develop comfortably - a small, long-term advantage. On the other hand, White lost a tempo on playing a3 and now Black has some development advantage.   The question is: does Black have enough time to create some play, or will White will be able to fulfill the dreams of a small but long-term bishop pair advantage. In my opinion, Black has enough resources to be doing fine. }
7... dxc4
{ Once the bishop has moved from f1, we have the option of winning a 'half a tempo' - a common motif in many NimzoIndian @@StartBracket@@and Queen's Gambit@@EndBracket@@ variations. }
8. Bxc4 c5
{ We have reached the main position of our line. White has 4 different continuations: the two main lines are  9.Nf3  and  9.Ne2  , but the two alternatives,  9.Bb2  and  9.Bd3  , are also serious options and have been played by top players. }
9. Ne2
{ This position might also arise from the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2NBP3/PP3PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQ d6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nge2  dxc4  7.Bxc4  c5  8.a3  Bxc3  9.bxc3  move order. }
9... Qc7 { Asking the bishop to decide which diagonal it wants to hold. } 10.
Ba2 b6
{ Now that ...e5 is not of option in view of d5, Black should develop his bishop on a6. }
11. O-O Ba6
{ Black's idea is simple: we want to play ...Nc6, ...Rac8, ... Rfd8, etc. } 12.
Re1 Nc6 13. Ng3 { White is preparing the e3-e4 push. } 13... Rfd8
{ It is never wrong to have the rook vs queen on the same file. } 14. Bb2 Na5
{ Going for the c4-square. } 15. Rc1
{ An attempt to prepare for the Bc4 move without locking the rook in the corner. }
15... Bc4 16. Bb1
{ Of course, White is trying to avoid the exchange, but here comes... } 16...
Nb3 17. Rc2 e5
{ The position of the white pieces looks just ugly and Black has great, dynamic play. As in any dynamic position, Black's next moves depend on what White will play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.a3 with 9.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3
{ White forces Black to take on c3. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
{ We are faced with an interesting position: White has the bishop pair which is clearly a plus and theoretically - if White manages to develop comfortably - a small, long-term advantage. On the other hand, White lost a tempo on playing a3 and now Black has some development advantage.   The question is: does Black have enough time to create some play, or will White will be able to fulfill the dreams of a small but long-term bishop pair advantage. In my opinion, Black has enough resources to be doing fine. }
7... dxc4
{ Once the bishop has moved from f1, we have the option of winning a 'half a tempo' - a common motif in many NimzoIndian @@StartBracket@@and Queen's Gambit@@EndBracket@@ variations. }
8. Bxc4 c5
{ We have reached the main position of our line. White has 4 different continuations: the two main lines are  9.Nf3  and  9.Ne2  , but the two alternatives,  9.Bb2  and  9.Bd3  , are also serious options and have been played by top players. }
9. Nf3 Qc7
{ Just as in the 9.Ne2 line, asking the bishop to choose a direction is the right decision. White has several options, but we have to point out that two logical-looking moves lose on the spot:  10.Qe2?  cxd4  11.cxd4  b5!  and ...Qc3+ next wins material, while  @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppq2ppp/4pn2/2p5/2BP4/P1P1PN2/5PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bd3?  cxd4  11.cxd4  Qc3+  also wins, as  12.Bd2  is not possible in view of the hanging d3-bishop. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppq2ppp/4pn2/2p5/2BP4/P1P1PN2/5PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qd3  doesn't make much sense as the queen will be misplaced and will walk into different tactical motifs after ...b6 and ...Bb7. }
10. Be2
{ 10.Ba2  is the chief alternative to the main line.  10.Qd3  , as we have already mentioned, makes no sense because after the simple  10...b6  11.O-O  Bb7  the position of the white queen is, at the very least, not perfect. }
10... b6
{ 10...Nc6  is the other main line, but I like the most recent way of handling the position, introduced by Giri. }
11. Bb2
{ 11.O-O  is more common, but in many cases they transpose to each other. This was played recently by many top players; White delays casting in order to make the standard queenside moves with Bb2, Rc1, c4 in order to be better prepared for Black's counterplay. }
11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Ba6 { The standard bishop exchange. } 13. Bxa6
{ It is interesting that Wesley So decided not to take on a6, which would misplace the black knight on the edge of the board, after which Black's main plan would be anyway to redirect it to ...Nb8-d7. }
13... Nxa6 14. O-O Rac8
{ There are many other moves for Black. The position is fine and can be played in different ways. }
15. Rc1
{ 15.Qe2  Nb8  should just be a transposition after  16.Rac1  Qb7  . While @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/p1q2ppp/np2pn2/8/3P4/P3PN2/1B3PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Ne5  can also be answered by  15...Nb8  when Black is happy to trade the knights. }
15... Qb7 16. Qe2 Nb8 { The knight is going to d7. } 17. Nd2 Nbd7 18. e4
{ Finally, White manages to play e4, but it doesn't change much. } 18... Rxc1
{ 18...Rfd8  or starting counterplay with  18...b5  are also fine. } 19. Rxc1
Rc8
{ Usually, it is the right plan for Black to exchange as many pieces as possible, trying to reach an endgame. We should not forget that the pawn endgame is going to be most probably winning for Black because of the pawn structure we see in the current position. Black can create an outside passed pawn, and outside pawns can run very fast sometimes :@@EndBracket@@ }
