[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ The three main moves now are  10.Qa4  ,  10.Qd3  and  10.Bd2  . In case of  10.Ne5  ,  we transpose to the 9.Ne5 lines. }
10. Qa4 Qc8 11. Bd2 Re8 12. Rfc1
{ A deep move by White. There are a few points behind putting this rook on c1. We will see a concrete one in the main line, but also White's main strategy here is to play on the queenside with a3-b4, when the rook has nothing to do on f1, so it should rather support the queenside actions. This seems to also cause the most headaches for Black. }
12... Bf8 13. Ne2 c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5
{ Carlsen's favorite approach; Black compensates for the isolated pawn with active piece play. The missing of the light-squared bishops is definitely a big deal for Black. We will follow the game of Fressinet, who is a second of Carlsen, and we can be sure that they analyzed these kinds of structures very deeply - he shows us how to play with Black. We can also see now the point of putting the f-rook on c1; White does not need to worry about the upcoming ...Qa6 move as the a2-pawn is protected. }
15. Qc2 Qb7 16. Bc3 Nfe4
{ This is the ideal position for the knights. One goes to e4, the other one is going to exchange a white one from e6. The rook is coming to c8. You can find more in-depth analysis of this line here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Qc2 d5 with 5.Nf3 and 6.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5
{ The two main moves by far are  5.cxd5  and  5.a3  , but now we are going to check the alternatives. }
5. Nf3 dxc4
{ The three most common moves are  6.e4  ,  6.Bg5  and  6.e3  @@StartBracket@@all of them are analyzed in depth in chapter 16@@EndBracket@@, but the rarely played  6.a3  seems an extremely dangerous alternative, where Black really needs to know what to do to avoid ending up in a worse position. }
6. a3 { Perhaps the most dangerous of White's continuations. } 6... Bxc3+ 7.
bxc3 { After  7.Qxc3  Black can hold on the c4-pawn with b5. } 7... c5
{ The ...c5 move is used in many different scenarios. Trying to keep the c4 pawn alive by playing  7...b5  is risky,  8.a4  and Ba3 might prevent Black from castling, and getting stuck with the king on e8 is dangerous. }
8. e4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Nc6
{ Black successfully attacks the center and if White protects it with  10.Be3  or  10.Bb2  , then  10...Na5!  is strong in both cases. }
10. Bxc4 Nxd4
{ White is a pawn down, but the bishop pair and a better development give great compensation. Black must be careful. }
11. Qc3
{ The point is that  11...Nxf3  is strongly met by  12.gxf3!  and somehow Black does not have a good defense against Rg1, Bb2 or Bh6 - the g7-pawn is the weak point. }
11... Nc6
{ A very important retreat, with the idea to exchange queens with ...Qa5. } 12.
O-O O-O 13. Bb2
{ Obviously, White has full compensation, but nothing more than that. } 13...
Qa5 14. Qe3 e5
{ Just in time to close the diagonal, but White's activity is still sufficient to keep the position in balance. Black would like to play ...Bg4 and later ...Nd4, and if White prevents this with  15.h3  , then  15...h6  ,  controlling the g5 square in order to play ...Re8 and ...Be6 later. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Qc2 and 5.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3
{ One of the main moves and clearly a move that we need to pay close attention to. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3
{ Here and in the next move Black has a wide range of choices. I suggest one of the more dynamic approaches, which on the other hand requires in some lines a high level of exactness. }
6... Ne4 { There are many other continuations for Black here. } 7. Qc2 c5
{ We start, from the very early stage, a dynamic play against White's center. }
8. dxc5
{ Other moves are simply bad or have no meaning of their own, such as  8.cxd5  exd5  9.dxc5  Nc6  which is just a transposition to our main lines. }
8... Nc6
{ We develop the knight and at the same time create the threat of ...Qa5, which could be dangerous for White. }
9. cxd5
{ This is the only line where White tries to preserve the extra pawn, however, nowadays, it is considered to be a bit risky, because it opens the game and Black can get a very strong compensation by using the e-file and playing the bishop on f5 or g4. }
9... exd5
{ White has two wild options here. Both of them were very popular some years ago even at the highest level. We are going to see some really crazy lines. }
10. Nf3 Qf6
{ Here as well, following the latest trend seems to be the best decision. } 11.
e3 Bg4 12. Be2
{ 12.Nd4  is a move that was tried in a few games. Black can play  12...O-O  with a very good position, but how to resist making such a beautiful move:  12...Bd1!?  - you can find this line here. }
12... O-O
{ Two moves have been tried here. In almost all the cases, h3 just helps Black as the bishop retreats to f5 and stands more actively. }
13. O-O Rfe8
{ This great move was introduced by Ivanchuk in 2006! It supports the ...d4 push in many important lines. White has tried five different moves here;  14.Rd1?  would lose due to  14...Ne5  as the f2-pawn cannot be protected. }
14. b3
{ It aims to be an improvement of the 14.b4 line, when the black queen could not leave the corner and, otherwise, White aims to complete the c1-bishop development. However, this move also has a drawback... }
14... Nc3 15. Bb2 { White has nothing better than this. } 15... Nxe2+ 16. Qxe2
d4
{ With full compensation. You can find a more in-depth analysis of this line here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Qc2, 5.cxd5 and 6.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4
{ Recently very popular even at higher levels and a very sharp alternative to the main line  6.Bg5  . }
6... c5 { The most challenging move with a quick attack on the center. } 7.
dxc5 Nc6 8. e3 { 8.Nf3  O-O  9.e3  d4  transposes to the main line. } 8... O-O
{ The other critical move is  8...Qa5  , which also leads to very sharp positions. }
9. Nf3 d4
{ The beginning of a very exciting line that leads, toward the end, to an even game. }
10. O-O-O
{ The only move that could create some problems for Black.  10.a3  could be simply met by  10...Bxc5 }
10... Bxc5 11. exd4 Bd6
{ Black sacrifices a pawn, but the action against the white king provides enough play to be perfectly fine. }
12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. a3
{ Otherwise Nb4 can be really unpleasant, but on the other hand it is another weakening of the b3-square that also delays development. }
13... Be6
{ This was Dominguez's prepared novelty against Caruana in 2020, played online. Black is ready to exploit the b3 weakness with ...Na5. The computer confirms that Black has full compensation in all lines. }
14. d5 Nxd5
{ A good move for Black, since both Bc4 and Ng5, which would try to exploit the pin on the d-file, would be met with Qf4+. }
15. g3 { If White prevents Qf4, Black also can do the same against Ng5. } 15...
h6
{ The position looks a bit dangerous for Black, but there is nothing to worry about. }
16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Bc4 Ne7
{ With equal position, as White still needs to solve some problems on the c-file. This line shows well why Caruana chose the move 14. Kb1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Qc2, 5.cxd5 and 6.Bg5 h6 7.Bxf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
{ Probably the main move of our 4. Qc2 Nimzo-Indian. } 6... h6
{ It is very important not to forget to play instantly  6...h6  . } 7. Bxf6
{ There is nothing to worry about once you see the bishop taking on f6. } 7...
Qxf6 8. a3
{ The idea of this line for White is that the bishop 'must' take on c3 now, otherwise the d5-pawn is lost. }
8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3
{ It leads to much quieter positions. White would like to achieve a typical Carlsbad structure @@StartBracket@@once Black plays ...c6@@EndBracket@@, where he wants to fight for a small initiative with the standard minority attack with b4-b5 in the long run. However, Black has a more dynamic way of handling the position. }
9... O-O 10. e3 Bf5
{ Black is ready to sacrifice the c-pawn, since it would be suicidal to capture that pawn without finishing the development. Black would invade with the rooks the c-file. Otherwise, Black would want to spare the move ...c6 and play instead for ...Nd7 and the quick ...c5. }
11. Ne2 { With the idea to get the knight to g3. } 11... Nd7 12. Nf4
{ The only way to fight against c5.  12.Qxc7  is still too brave, Black would continue again with  12...Rfc8  and a rook invasion. @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pppn1pp1/5q1p/3p1b2/3P4/P1Q1P3/1P2NPPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.b4  is again met by the same  12...a5!  move as in the 11. Nf3 lines. }
12... c6
{ Actually the move 12...c5 is still possible and it leads to big complications, but I suggest an easier and more practical continuation. }
13. Be2
{ And here, thanks to White spending too much time, I recommend a novelty. }
13... a5
{ The point of this plan is to stop the minority attack on the queenside. } 14.
b4
{ After  14.O-O  we can play  14...a4!  with an equal position. The a4-pawn can be safely protected. In some cases, Black might even consider the plan of playing ...b5 and ...Nb6-c4. }
14... axb4 15. axb4
{ 15.Qxb4  is rather a mistake as after  15...b5!  ,  Black is in time to play ...Nb6 next with an advantage because of the a3 weakness. It is important to note that White cannot undermine the b5 pawn with  16.a4  , since after  16...bxa4  White has not yet castled and can be punished for this along the b-file. }
15... b5 { A typical reaction in this type of structure. } 16. O-O Nb6
{ White's knight on f4 is not perfectly placed, and we are in time to play ...Nc4 next. If someone is better here, it is Black. }
