[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian: 4.Qc2, 5.cxd5 and 6.Bg5 h6 7.Bh4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
{ Probably the main move of our 4. Qc2 Nimzo-Indian. } 6... h6
{ It is very important not to forget to play instantly  6...h6  . } 7. Bh4 g5
{ The main theoretical lines begin with  7...c5  8.dxc5  g5  9.Bg3  Ne4  with thousands of games and extreme complications. I would like to suggest a rare alternative, which is gaining popularity today after several top GMs have used it successfully. }
8. Bg3 Nc6
{ We do not usually put the knight on c6 before playing the move c5, but in this line there is a concrete reason to do so. }
9. e3 h5
{ A very dynamic variation, where it is easy to play for a win from the opening stage of the game. We got right to the crossroads, White tried 7 different moves here. }
10. Bb5
{ This is considered to be the main line and it is also the most frequently played move. }
10... h4 11. Be5 O-O { The alternative  11...Rh6  is also interesting. } 12.
Bxf6
{ As you probably already know, I personally never believe that White can gain anything by giving away the dark-squared bishop. }
12... Qxf6 13. h3 Ne7 14. Nf3
{ Played by strong GMs, but it does not seems to be dangerous. } 14... c6 15.
Bd3 Be6 { A very solid setup for Black. } 16. a3 Ba5
{ Keeping the bishop, and a very healthy position. In fact, the Black king is very safe despite having moved his pawns in front of him, while the White king is quite vulnerable. Black can launch a strong attack regardless of where White decides to castle. That is why I prefer to be Black here. }
