[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Bogo-Indian: 5.Nbxd2 O-O 6.g3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ We will not focus on other continuations such as  4...Qe7  ,  4...c5  or  4...a5  , as they lead to slightly worse positions, but of course, they are playable options. I myself have played  4...Qe7  and  4...c5  many times, but each time I ask myself why, when I am very sure that I will end up in a somewhat worse position straight from the opening! }
5. Nbxd2
{ This recapture is not considered to be the most accurate in this and similar openings, as the ideal - and much more active - placement for the knight is on c3. In fact, in many cases, the knight is completely misplaced on d2, for example in structures such as white pawns on e4/d5 and black pawns on d6/e5.   White needs to choose between three setups @@StartBracket@@e4, e3 or g3@@EndBracket@@ and Black's main plan is connected to the pawn structure outlined above: in most cases, I suggest ...d6-e5, however, against the g3 systems, I believe the easiest setup involves ...b6. Therefore I recommend the most flexible move order, to see first what White is planning next. }
5... O-O 6. g3
{ I like the idea of opposing the bishop on the long diagonal with ...b6. }
6... b6 7. Bg2 Bb7 { Our bishop is on b7 – a good sign! } 8. O-O c5
{ This is the point behind choosing the setup with ...b6: Black need not end up with a small space problem, but can challenge the center instead. It is known that in similar positions White can push d5 and after ...exd5 jump away with the f3-knight, utilizing the long diagonal pin to then win back the pawn with cxd5, with a small advantage. But now the difference is that the d2-knight interrupts these actions and White will not be able to win back the pawn after ...exd5. I checked some options for White, but none of them seem to be dangerous. }
9. dxc5 bxc5
{ This structural change should be in Black's favor as he takes towards the center. The position remains objectively balanced, but in such positions, I would already choose Black. }
10. Qc2 Nc6 11. Rfd1 Qc7
{ With ...Rfd8, followed by ...Rab8 and a comfortable position. } *

