[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Bogo-Indian: 5.Qxd2 d5 6.g3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ We will not focus on other continuations such as  4...Qe7  ,  4...c5  or  4...a5  , as they lead to slightly worse positions, but of course, they are playable options. I myself have played  4...Qe7  and  4...c5  many times, but each time I ask myself why, when I am very sure that I will end up in a somewhat worse position straight from the opening! }
5. Qxd2
{ Why does White recapture with the queen? The answer is simple: White intends to develop the knight to c3, which is a much better position for the steed than on d2. }
5... d5
{ Here the ... d5-setup is considered to be the most solid for Black, but as we will see, White can cause us some headaches in both options. He must decide the character of the game now by choosing which direction to develop his f1-bishop.   6.e3  does not have its own significance because, after  6...O-O  , White should transpose to the main line with  7.Nc3  . }
6. g3
{ This is a very serious option for White, directing the game towards the Catalan opening - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.g3  . }
6... c6 7. Bg2 O-O
{ Black's main idea is to develop safely with ...Nbd7, ...b6, ...Bb7 and later push ...c5 with equality. However, against the main move  8.O-O  , we have a new direction in mind, therefore White must also consider some other options here. }
8. O-O dxc4
{ A rare, but relatively fresh idea by hard-working Russian top GMs, Vitiugov and Matlakov; Black takes the pawn and tries to hold it as long as possible. }
9. Ne5 { If White manages to win back the c4-pawn, they will stand better. }
9... b5
{ Black needs to give back the pawn, but in case of  10.Nxc6  Nxc6  11.Bxc6  Rb8  ,  he achieves a better position because of the superior pawn structure. White must instead try to compensate by finding active play. }
10. b3
{ A plan known from the Catalan opening. White often sacrifices a pawn like this, trying to get a dominating position where he is a pawn down, but the black pieces are very passive. }
10... cxb3 { There is nothing better for Black. } 11. axb3 Bb7
{ There is only one game that reached this position, in which White chose to continue with Nc3. }
12. Rc1 { And we have time for the important positional move: } 12... a5
{ After this move Black should be completely fine. As we have seen in the previous two lines, it was critical for White to prevent our counterplay with b4 at some point. }
13. Qb2 Qb6 { I think even according to just feeling that Black must be fine! }
14. Nd2
{ Black already has different good options, but the one Vitiugov played was good and solid enough. }
14... Nbd7 { Again the typical sacrifice of the c6-pawn. } 15. Nxc6 Rfe8
{ Covering the e7-square. } 16. Rc2 Nd5 17. Rac1 N7f6
{ Black had no issues and later Nikita nicely outplayed his opponent in Dragnev-Vitiugov, Moscow 2019. }
