[Black "Bogo-Indian: 4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3
{ The main and most logical continuation: White immediately goes for the bishop pair, which should guarantee him a small but long-lasting edge. There are two alternatives as well: Bxd2 or Nxd2. }
5... Bxd2+
{ White has different set-ups depending on how he recaptures on d2. } 6. Qxd2
{ This is the most common move, with the clear intention to develop the c1-bishop on the long diagonal. }
6... Bb7
{ White needs to decide where he wants to develop his f1-bishop. He has two options, but the main and most common move by far is e3. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Be2
{ This is the most common continuation by far, followed by developing the other bishop on b2. }
8... d5
{ Yet again, I would like to offer you this very rare line. The position is full of interesting and untried ideas that I would like to share with you. }
9. b3
{ The most typical reaction to the ...d5 move - White would like to keep his center and develop his bishop on b2. }
9... c5
{ Of course, the most natural move is  9...Nbd7  which is what happened in most of the games, but this idea looks really interesting. There are no games with the upcoming variations, as in the two games in the database, Black just transposed with ...Nbd7 next move. As you will soon see, we have other ideas in mind! }
10. Bb2
{ The most natural move in the position, developing and getting ready for the opening of the game.  10.cxd5  is harmless after  10...Bxd5  and if  11.dxc5  Ne4  . }
10... Ne4 { This leads to very sharp lines... } 11. Qc2 cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13.
bxc4
{ After clearing the tension from the center, it looks like White has achieved everything he could hope for. However, Black has only done this because of one concrete reason - to play now ...b5. }
13... b5
{ Black opens the way for his queen to give a very unpleasant check on a5! Of course, if he manages to take on c4, the pawn structure would favor him, therefore White can choose between three logical continuations: c5, cxb5 and Bd3. }
14. Bd3 Nf6
{ A very nice and unexpected retreat. Black would still like to take on c4 with a perfect pawn structure, so White must try to accept the pawn sacrifice. }
15. cxb5 Bxf3 { Damaging White's pawn structure eternally! } 16. gxf3 Nbd7
{ With very strong compensation for the pawn. The b2-bishop is out of the game and the white king is going to be vulnerable once Black plays ...Rc8, ...Nd5 and ... Qh4, using the seriously weakened dark squares offered by the damaged pawn structure. }
