[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Nimzo Indian, an introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ Welcome to the starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defence, named after the great chess player and author, Aron Nimzowitsch @@StartBracket@@1886-1935@@EndBracket@@. Most of us will have read and appreciated his famous publication 'My System', published in 1925, and if you haven't then you really should! The known origin of the opening seems to be the game between Englisch vs Blackburn, played in London way back in 1883.  Let me list a few factors why the Nimzo has been so loved for the past 140 years and remains one of the most played and popular openings!  - It is a very solid opening.  - Nobody has ever shown a clear way for White to get an advantage.  - Black can choose from many different playable lines.  - Many lines can be played naturally over the board based on feeling and understanding and not only on memorization of forced continuations.  - Black has a very safe king position @@StartBracket@@and we all know how unpleasant it is to be under a direct attack!@@EndBracket@@.  On move 4, White has to decide the direction of play. There are 6 major approaches.  -  4.e3  is the very main move. The positions are going to be complex with many different structures, but most important is that the positions need to be understood! In many lines, not making the best move is not such a big deal, but we should avoid going in the wrong direction. The move 4.e3 has been played at the very top level of chess for almost as long as chess theory started to develop. There been periods where it seemed that White had gained the upper hand, only for Black to again manage to get a good game, and so it continued... At the current moment, things seem to be very solid for Black!   -  4.Qc2  is the other major move, and it involves a simple and direct approach: White will play a3 next and enjoy the bishop pair advantage. In this line, we will need to be exact, but Black will enjoy very interesting positions directly from the first moves of the opening.   -  4.Nf3  At the present moment this move has slipped out of White's main focus, even though the positions arising are complex and are very playable for both colors. I would not say that 4.Nf3 is dangerous, but it is clearly one of the main continuations that we have to be familiar with. It needs to be noted that White can also decide to play e3 next, and once again we could end up in the same positions as after 4.e3, just via a different move order.   -  4.a3  This variation is back in fashion, with a lot of new games from the world's top Grandmasters. The idea is simple: White wants to obtain the bishop pair directly, but in doing so worsening its pawn structure. To have a fair share of the ensuing play, we have to be precise, and if we can manage that, I believe that Black's chances are no worse than White's.   -  4.f3  A tricky move! White is going directly for the center and wants to play e4 next. In the 4.f3 variation, many sharp positions will arise and you will see a crossroads with the move 4.a3. This is a good line for both colors if the players want to have a sharp battle for the full point.   -  4.Bg5  is a very direct approach but it is not so popular for a good reason. It seems that Black gets an excellent position from the opening BUT... be very careful. The line is much trickier than it seems to be and it is easy to chose the wrong move order, or to take a quick decision that could rebound and leave you with serious regrets.   - 4. The rest. In case you know what to do against the last 6 main options of White, even not knowing the lesser-played sidelines that might appear on move 4 you should have no problems finding a decent plan and reaching at least an OK position, Still, we will take a look at few of them - safety first, just for the feeling of confidence! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
