[White "1) Nimzo-Indian with 4.g3"]
[Black "7.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ Playing the Nimzo-Indian in Catalan-style has become really popular nowadays due to some new ideas against the main ... d5 setups. The second most popular line against the system is to play with  4...c5  , but it transposes to some main lines after  5.Nf3  which we don't play. Therefore, I suggest a relatively rare, but perfectly playable system here. }
4... Bxc3+
{ Black is aiming for a strategic position, where the main c4-weakness can be more easily attacked once the bishop is developed to g2. }
5. bxc3 d6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Bg5
{ Is not a logical move to give up the bishop pair as White will have less compensation for his worse pawn structure. }
7... Nbd7
{ I like  7...e5  8.Nf3  h6  for Black, but Ivanchuk recently played this line. }
8. Nf3 h6 { Time to ask White what to do next with the g5-bishop. } 9. Bxf6
Nxf6 10. O-O Rb8
{ Black wants to play ...b6 to be able to attack the c4-pawn. } 11. Nd2 b6 12.
a4 { Fighting against ...Ba6 with a5. } 12... a5 13. e4 e5 14. f4 Re8
{ Keeping the tension. Black's position is already preferable as the e4-, c4- and a4-pawns can be attacked very easily with ...Bb7, ...Bc6 and ...Qd7, while for White it is difficult to suggest an active plan when their pieces are tied to protecting the weaknesses. Flom-Ivanchuk, Online 2021. }
