[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ Playing the Nimzo-Indian in Catalan-style has become really popular nowadays due to some new ideas against the main ... d5 setups. The second most popular line against the system is to play with  4...c5  , but it transposes to some main lines after  5.Nf3  which we don't play. Therefore, I suggest a relatively rare, but perfectly playable system here. }
4... Bxc3+
{ Black is aiming for a strategic position, where the main c4-weakness can be more easily attacked once the bishop is developed to g2. }
5. bxc3 d6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black has two plans in this position: one is to push ...e5, and the other is to attack the c4-pawn with ...b6, ...Ba6 and ...Na5. The last move perfectly supports both. }
8. Qd3
{ Lately, this move has become the most popular move and therefore we could also use it as the main line. The point is to have @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/4p3/2PP4/2PQ1NP1/P3PPBP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nd2  if Black plays @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2nppn2/8/2PP4/2PQ1NP1/P3PPBP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5  . That position is also very interesting and playable after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/4p3/2PP4/2PQ2P1/P2NPPBP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Re8  10.e4  and now  10...b6  , but I suggest using the other plan available to us in the position. }
8... Rb8
{ After leaving the long diagonal, Black is ready to play ...b6, ...Ba6 and ...Na5. }
9. Nd2
{ Is a common idea for White to prevent ...b6 and to be able to play Nb3 in case of ...Na5. Black should respond with ...Qd7. }
9... Qd7 { Refreshing the ...b6-plan. } 10. Nb3 b6 11. Bg5
{ Black should not worry and just move the knight away. } 11... Ne8 12. O-O
{ White is threatening to win an exchange with Bxc6 and Be7, but now Black has a pleasant choice between  12...Ne7  with ...Ba6 next, or  12...f6  . }
12... f6 13. Bc1 Ba6
{ Threatening ...d5 and ...Nd6, but also ...f5 and ...Nf6 might give Black a great position. }
