{ Playing the Nimzo-Indian in Catalan-style has become really popular nowadays due to some new ideas against the main ... d5 setups. The second most popular line against the system is to play with  4...c5  , but it transposes to some main lines after  5.Nf3  which we don't play. Therefore, I suggest a relatively rare, but perfectly playable system here. }
4... Bxc3+
{ Black is aiming for a strategic position, where the main c4-weakness can be more easily attacked once the bishop is developed to g2. }
5. bxc3 d6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black has two plans in this position: one is to push ...e5, and the other is to attack the c4-pawn with ...b6, ...Ba6 and ...Na5. The last move perfectly supports both. }
8. O-O e5
{ I already prefer Black's position here, or at least it is much easier to play. We are still targeting the c4 weakness, but in some cases we can also use the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal and sometimes the plan of pushing e4 can also be better for Black. White has tried a lot of moves here, and almost everything was played by good GMs, but none of them seem to be successful. }
9. Qa4
{ Happened in the Xu-Le, Xingtai 2019, but Black would have been better after  9...e4  .   9.dxe5  dxe5  10.Ba3  was played by Grandelius, but Black could have just played  10...Re8  with a better position. }
9... e4 10. Nd2
{ And now there are many good options, but the most precise is  10...Qe8  with the threat of playing ...Nxd4. }
10... Qe8 11. Qc2 Bf5
{ And we are having a perfect setup for Black. We played ...e4 and supported it with ...Bf5 while White has been losing tempi with the Qa4-Qc2 maneuver. }
*

