1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ Playing the Nimzo-Indian in Catalan-style has become really popular nowadays due to some new ideas against the main ... d5 setups. The second most popular line against the system is to play with  4...c5  , but it transposes to some main lines after  5.Nf3  which we don't play. Therefore, I suggest a relatively rare, but perfectly playable system here. }
4... Bxc3+
{ Black is aiming for a strategic position, where the main c4-weakness can be more easily attacked once the bishop is developed to g2. }
5. bxc3 d6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black has two plans in this position: one is to push ...e5, and the other is to attack the c4-pawn with ...b6, ...Ba6 and ...Na5. The last move perfectly supports both. }
8. O-O e5
{ I already prefer Black's position here, or at least it is much easier to play. We are still targeting the c4 weakness, but in some cases we can also use the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal and sometimes the plan of pushing e4 can also be better for Black. White has tried a lot of moves here, and almost everything was played by good GMs, but none of them seem to be successful. }
9. c5
{ A logical move trying to get rid of the weaknesses, but this move always allows ...e4 and then ...d5 as White no longer controls the center. }
9... e4 10. Ng5
{ 10.Nd2  d5  has occurred in several games, but it is also just better for Black because of the poor white bishops and the bad pawn structure. }
10... d5
{ If Black does not want to allow the complications, simple play with  10...Re8!?  also leads to a better position, but the upcoming piece sacrifice does not seem to be correct at all from White's point of view. }
11. f3 { There is nothing better White can do against the threat of ...h6. }
11... h6 12. fxe4 { Otherwise White is just clearly worse. } 12... hxg5 13.
Bxg5 { This looks a bit dangerous, but with exact play, Black is just better. }
13... dxe4 14. Rf4
{ 14.Bxe4?  Qe8!  successfully leaves the pin and wins the game. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pp1/2n2n2/2P3B1/3Pp3/2P3P1/P3P1BP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.Bxe4  Qe7  16.Qd3  Kg7  followed by  ...Rh8  is also good for Black. }
14... Qd5 { The next moves are kind of forced. } 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Bxe4 Qg5
{ We got our queen across to the defense! } 17. Qd3 Ne7
{ and Black had a winning position in the game V. Georgiev-Mancini, La Fere 2012.   Conclusion: The line with 4...Bxc3 is not Black's main choice, but it deserves a lot of attention. Black's play is simple and White needs to prove a lot because of the bad pawn structure, which is never easy. I personally like this line a lot because of its practicality and ease of play over the board. }
