[Black "7.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3
{ This is quite a popular line, played from time to time by many top players. For example, Mamedyarov has enjoyed many nice games with it. }
4... d5
{ We will choose the variation with  4...d5  .  Maybe it is not the most popular solution, but I think it is an interesting option to avoid the main-line theory. }
5. a3 { White has nothing better. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ There are different options here as well, but we will only focus on  6...O-O }
6... O-O 7. Bg5
{ In these variations, when the pawn structure changes later with cxd5 exd5 and e3, because of the weakness of the e3 pawn, White would rather have his bishop on c1 to support the pawn chain. Therefore, this active-looking move to free the bishop first and only later play e3 is a mistake. }
7... c5 8. cxd5 exd5 9. e3 h6
{ And now the problem is that the e3-pawn will soon be under attack with ...Re8 and White has difficulties protecting it healthily. }
10. Bh4 Re8 { With pressure on the e3-pawn. } *

