[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Nimzo-Indian with 4.f3"]
[Black "7.cxd5 with 8.e3 and 11.Bxa6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3
{ This is quite a popular line, played from time to time by many top players. For example, Mamedyarov has enjoyed many nice games with it. }
4... d5
{ We will choose the variation with  4...d5  .  Maybe it is not the most popular solution, but I think it is an interesting option to avoid the main-line theory. }
5. a3 { White has nothing better. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ There are different options here as well, but we will only focus on  6...O-O }
6... O-O 7. cxd5
{ 7.e3  does not have its own significance as after  7...c5  we should transpose to the main lines with  8.cxd5  exd5  . }
7... exd5 8. e3 c5 9. Bd3
{ White has no better piece setup than this: other moves have no real meaning and White has to aim to castle short as soon as possible. }
9... b6 { We want to exchange the c8-bishop for the d3-bishop. } 10. Ne2 Ba6
{ A bit similar to our 4.e3 Nimzo-Indian variation, we are also exchanging the strong-light squared bishop from a6 and aim to get a position with a potentially better structure and leave White to suffer with their c1-bishop. However, things are not so simple, unfortunately... this variation is very strategic for both sides.   It is all about the e4-move: White needs to get it in at any cost to occupy the center and to activate the bishop, and Black needs to fight against it, or, when Black can no longer hold it back, there are typical ideas for making it less effective. Both sides have their standard ideas to support their plans. Of course, there are some concrete lines to learn, but in general, this line is more about understanding. }
11. Bxa6
{ In the e3 Nimzo-Indian, we have learned that, in most cases, it is better for White to take on a6, because the black knight gets misplaced on the edge of the board, and in those lines, many times Black transfers it back to b8 then c6. The situation is different here: taking on a6 is considered an inaccuracy in this position because the knight will be able to go to e6 very quickly and it turns out to be an excellent position for it in the fight against the e4-move. }
11... Nxa6 12. O-O Nc7
{ The black knight is on its way to taking up the perfect position on e6. } 13.
Ng3 Re8
{ White needs to play for the e4-push. In such situations, playing on the queenside with  14.a4  and the idea of Ba3 is harmless as the bishop would still remain bad. Black would simply play ...Rc8. }
14. Ra2
{ The idea is to transfer the rook to e2 to support the e4-move but usually White starts first with  14.Qd3  , which is clearly the main move in the position. }
14... Rc8
{ Black creates the threat of counterplay with ...cxd4 followed by ...Nb5, which has to be prevented. }
15. a4 { 15.Qd3  Ne6  transposes to the 14.Qd3 Ne6 line. } 15... Ne6
{ Black has a fine position. } 16. Bb2
{ The game Paravyan-Saric, Yerevan 2014 continued with the text move, but this is illogical after having played Ra2 two moves previously. Black could have continued with the standard plan: ...h5. }
16... h5
{ We are going to discuss the point of this standard move in the main lines. Now, for example, White cannot push e4. }
17. e4 dxe4 18. fxe4 Ng4 { With the threats of ...Ne3 and ...Qh4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Nimzo-Indian with 4.f3"]
[Black "7.cxd5 with 8.e3 and 11.Bxa6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3
{ This is quite a popular line, played from time to time by many top players. For example, Mamedyarov has enjoyed many nice games with it. }
4... d5
{ We will choose the variation with  4...d5  .  Maybe it is not the most popular solution, but I think it is an interesting option to avoid the main-line theory. }
5. a3 { White has nothing better. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ There are different options here as well, but we will only focus on  6...O-O }
6... O-O 7. cxd5
{ 7.e3  does not have its own significance as after  7...c5  we should transpose to the main lines with  8.cxd5  exd5  . }
7... exd5 8. e3 c5 9. Bd3
{ White has no better piece setup than this: other moves have no real meaning and White has to aim to castle short as soon as possible. }
9... b6 { We want to exchange the c8-bishop for the d3-bishop. } 10. Ne2 Ba6
{ A bit similar to our 4.e3 Nimzo-Indian variation, we are also exchanging the strong-light squared bishop from a6 and aim to get a position with a potentially better structure and leave White to suffer with their c1-bishop. However, things are not so simple, unfortunately... this variation is very strategic for both sides.   It is all about the e4-move: White needs to get it in at any cost to occupy the center and to activate the bishop, and Black needs to fight against it, or, when Black can no longer hold it back, there are typical ideas for making it less effective. Both sides have their standard ideas to support their plans. Of course, there are some concrete lines to learn, but in general, this line is more about understanding. }
11. Bxa6
{ In the e3 Nimzo-Indian, we have learned that, in most cases, it is better for White to take on a6, because the black knight gets misplaced on the edge of the board, and in those lines, many times Black transfers it back to b8 then c6. The situation is different here: taking on a6 is considered an inaccuracy in this position because the knight will be able to go to e6 very quickly and it turns out to be an excellent position for it in the fight against the e4-move. }
11... Nxa6 12. O-O Nc7
{ The black knight is on its way to taking up the perfect position on e6. } 13.
Ng3 Re8
{ White needs to play for the e4-push. In such situations, playing on the queenside with  14.a4  and the idea of Ba3 is harmless as the bishop would still remain bad. Black would simply play ...Rc8. }
14. Qd3 Ne6
{ Just in time to prevent e4 by attacking the d4-pawn. White again has two typical plans to try to get in e4: Ra2 and Bb2. }
15. Ra2
{ Dropping the rook to d2 to be able to push e4 is the first approach. } 15...
Rc8 16. Rd2
{ 16.Re2  doesn't make much sense now as the d4-pawn is still unprotected and if White wants to support it with Bb2, in that case, White still cannot push e4 as White just moved into the ...Nf4 fork.  Black could use the standard move  16...h5  in reply. }
16... h5
{ An improvement on the previous games with 16...Qc7.  Many times the g3-knight is the best supporter of the e4-break and Black is ready to destabilize it. }
17. Rdd1
{ With the idea to open the Bc1 before pushing e4 @@StartBracket@@also to control the f4-square@@EndBracket@@. }
17... cxd4 18. cxd4 Rc4 { Continuing to put pressure on the center. } 19. Ne2
{ Finally, White is ready to play e4, but the black pieces are already well-placed for counterplay. }
19... b5 { Buttressing the important rook on c4. } 20. e4 dxe4 21. fxe4 Re7
{ ...Rd7 is coming next and Black successfully attacks the central pawns. After that, not only is the d4-pawn hanging, but Black is also threatening ...Nc5, winning the e4-pawn. White has problems holding his pawns and pushing e5 would allow ... Nd5 with a beautiful position for Black. }
