11... Nxa6 12. O-O Nc7
{ The black knight is on its way to taking up the perfect position on e6. } 13.
Ng3 Re8
{ White needs to play for the e4-push. In such situations, playing on the queenside with  14.a4  and the idea of Ba3 is harmless as the bishop would still remain bad. Black would simply play ...Rc8. }
14. Qd3 Ne6
{ Just in time to prevent e4 by attacking the d4-pawn. White again has two typical plans to try to get in e4: Ra2 and Bb2. }
15. Bb2 h5
{ Just when White is ready to push e4, Black arrives with their counterplay. }
16. e4 { Can be met by ...h4. } 16... h4 17. Nf5 Nf4
{ Black's pieces are again ready to launch counterplay. } 18. Qe3 N6h5
{ Using the f4-square to create counterplay is another very common idea against e4. Black has a decisive threat of ...Qg5 @@StartBracket@@...Qxf5 utilizing the pin on the e-file, and checkmate on g2 are the twin threats@@EndBracket@@ and White does not have a proper defense. }
