{ There are different options here as well, but we will only focus on  6...O-O }
6... O-O 7. cxd5
{ 7.e3  does not have its own significance as after  7...c5  we should transpose to the main lines with  8.cxd5  exd5  . }
7... exd5 8. e3 c5 9. Bd3
{ White has no better piece setup than this: other moves have no real meaning and White has to aim to castle short as soon as possible. }
9... b6 { We want to exchange the c8-bishop for the d3-bishop. } 10. Ne2 Ba6
{ A bit similar to our 4.e3 Nimzo-Indian variation, we are also exchanging the strong-light squared bishop from a6 and aim to get a position with a potentially better structure and leave White to suffer with their c1-bishop. However, things are not so simple, unfortunately... this variation is very strategic for both sides.   It is all about the e4-move: White needs to get it in at any cost to occupy the center and to activate the bishop, and Black needs to fight against it, or, when Black can no longer hold it back, there are typical ideas for making it less effective. Both sides have their standard ideas to support their plans. Of course, there are some concrete lines to learn, but in general, this line is more about understanding. }
11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Re8 { The fight continues for and against the e4 move. }
13. Ng3 Nc6
{ Attacking the d4-pawn, and now White has two ways to continue the preparation for e4. }
14. Bb2
{ The main line and also the most critical continuation. White does not waste any time and is ready to push e4 next. Therefore, Black must start the standard counterplay to destabilize the g3-knight... }
14... h5 { We once again prevent the e4-push because of ...h4. } 15. e4
{ This is very interesting and definitely one of the most critical lines. White has scored almost 100% with this move, defeating many good players. In almost all these games Black continued with the most natural move ...h4, but that leads to White's advantage in some very concrete tactical lines. My improvement has been played in only one game so far... }
15... c4
{ White has 4 squares to go to with the queen, but against each one Black finds great counterplay. Attention please! In the following lines it matters greatly when we need to start with ...h4, and when with ...dxe4! }
16. Qe2 h4 { We are going for the e4-pawn. } 17. Nf5 dxe4 18. fxe4
{ This time Black needs to take with the rook on e4. } 18... Rxe4 19. Qf3 Re6
{ And Black would like to play ...Qd5 next, with a perfect position. } 20. Bc1
{ White is ready to play Bg5. Although  20.Ne3  prevents our ...Qd5 plan, it also retreats the most active white piece and Black can simply play  20...Qc7  , followed by bringing the a8-rook to the game as  21.d5  walks into ...Ne5. }
20... Qd5 21. Qh3 Ne7
{ Giving back the h4-pawn, but getting rid of the f5 knight. } *

