11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Re8 { The fight continues for and against the e4 move. }
13. Ng3 Nc6
{ Attacking the d4-pawn, and now White has two ways to continue the preparation for e4. }
14. Bb2
{ The main line and also the most critical continuation. White does not waste any time and is ready to push e4 next. Therefore, Black must start the standard counterplay to destabilize the g3-knight... }
14... h5 { We once again prevent the e4-push because of ...h4. } 15. e4
{ This is very interesting and definitely one of the most critical lines. White has scored almost 100% with this move, defeating many good players. In almost all these games Black continued with the most natural move ...h4, but that leads to White's advantage in some very concrete tactical lines. My improvement has been played in only one game so far... }
15... c4
{ White has 4 squares to go to with the queen, but against each one Black finds great counterplay. Attention please! In the following lines it matters greatly when we need to start with ...h4, and when with ...dxe4! }
16. Qe3 dxe4 { This time we take on e4 first. } 17. fxe4 h4 18. Nf5 Nxe4
{ Black has won a pawn, but the knight on f5 is very dangerous. Luckily the b2-bishop is completely out of the game, which gives Black time to organize the defences. }
19. Qf3 Qf6 20. Rad1
{ Preventing Nd2 and now Black can choose between  20...Rad8  ,  20...Ng5  , or the move I suggest... }
20... Na5
{ Heading to b3, threatening a knight landing on d2 again and further paralyzing the b2-bishop. }
21. Rfe1 g6 { This leads to a forced simplification. } 22. Rxe4 Qxf5 23. Qxf5
gxf5 24. Rxh4
{ White wins back the pawn, but his bishop is still bad, and also the active rook on the e-file fully compensates for the doubled f-pawns. }
24... Nb3
{ Control over the e-file and White's bad bishop compensate for Black's damaged pawn structure. }
