13. Ng3 Nc6
{ Attacking the d4-pawn, and now White has two ways to continue the preparation for e4. }
14. Bb2
{ The main line and also the most critical continuation. White does not waste any time and is ready to push e4 next. Therefore, Black must start the standard counterplay to destabilize the g3-knight... }
14... h5 { We once again prevent the e4-push because of ...h4. } 15. Rae1 h4
16. Nf5 h3
{ We have reached the last crossroads of the variation. The position has occured recently in several games by strong GMs. After all is said and done, it seems like Black has enough resources everywhere to maintain the balance. }
17. g4
{ Played in Esipenko-Maghsoodloo, Online 2020, but Black reacted well with ...Ne7. }
17... Ne7 18. Ng3 Rc8 19. e4
{ It is definitely very principled, but on the other hand, it gives up a pawn. }
19... dxe4 20. fxe4 cxd4 21. cxd4 Nxg4
{ In case of d5, Black can establish a blockade on the e5-square with ...Ng6, and the other critical target could be the f7-pawn, but it can be safely guarded by the knight on h6. }
22. Qf3 Nh6
{ And ...Ng6 next @@StartBracket@@if Rc2 is prevented@@EndBracket@@ with mutual chances. An attempt to remove our defender with Bc1 can be met in the worst-case scenario by ... Rxc1 followed by taking on d4. }
