[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Nimzo-Indian with 4.Bg5"]
[Black "6.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5
{ The so-called Leningrad System of the Nimzo-Indian defense. It used to be a major and very serious weapon in the past, but nowadays it is out of fashion, mainly because modern computers showed a safe way to completely neutralize this system.   A very important point to note is that many times the ...h6/Bh4 pair of moves are included as a kind of automatic response. However, in this variation, it is key to avoid this inclusion! We are going to see why in the main line! }
4... c5 5. d5
{ The only critical move and the whole point of the system. Other moves, such as  5.Rc1  cxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.Qxf6  gxf6  , already lead to a better endgame for Black. }
5... d6 6. f3
{ Is a decent alternative, trying to set up a Saemisch or 4.f3 Nimzo-Indian type of structure. }
6... O-O 7. e4 h6
{ Now it is time to ask the bishop which diagonal it is going to choose. } 8.
Bd2
{ allows the very typical maneuver to undermine the structure while the white pieces are still undeveloped. }
8... exd5 9. cxd5 Nh5
{ With the direct threat of ...Qh4+ and if White prevents it, ...f5! starts to dismantle White's position very effectively. }
10. Nge2 { 10.g3  f5  is also perfect for Black. } 10... f5 11. Qc2
{ There are other moves for White, but Black is doing great in all of them. }
11... fxe4 12. fxe4
{ And here a small improvement can be made on the game Parker-Lautier, Mondariz 2000, by playing ...Bg4. }
12... Bg4 13. O-O-O Nd7 { With a big advantage. } *

