[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Nimzo-Indian with 4.Bg5"]
[Black "6.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5
{ The so-called Leningrad System of the Nimzo-Indian defense. It used to be a major and very serious weapon in the past, but nowadays it is out of fashion, mainly because modern computers showed a safe way to completely neutralize this system.   A very important point to note is that many times the ...h6/Bh4 pair of moves are included as a kind of automatic response. However, in this variation, it is key to avoid this inclusion! We are going to see why in the main line! }
4... c5 5. d5
{ The only critical move and the whole point of the system. Other moves, such as  5.Rc1  cxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.Qxf6  gxf6  , already lead to a better endgame for Black. }
5... d6 6. Qc2
{ Seems logical and has been played in some games to support the e4-move, but delaying development might backfire if Black reacts quickly and accurately. }
6... exd5 7. cxd5 Nbd7
{ In a lot of lines we see this ...Nbd7 move, which is a typical way to play the current structures. Please do not worry about the c8-bishop – it will come into the game when the time is right! }
8. Nf3 O-O 9. Nd2
{ A standard knight maneuver in the Benoni structure. White supports the e4 move and knight is heading later to the ideal c4-square, but Black now has the very strong ...Qe8! }
9... Qe8
{ Leaving the bishop's pin and creating another pin of the e-file, which reveals that the d5-pawn cannot be protected in any normal way, since after  10.e4  ,  Black can take on c3 followed by ...Nxd5. Black is better. }
*

