[Black "6.Nf3 with 8.Nd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5
{ The so-called Leningrad System of the Nimzo-Indian defense. It used to be a major and very serious weapon in the past, but nowadays it is out of fashion, mainly because modern computers showed a safe way to completely neutralize this system.   A very important point to note is that many times the ...h6/Bh4 pair of moves are included as a kind of automatic response. However, in this variation, it is key to avoid this inclusion! We are going to see why in the main line! }
4... c5 5. d5
{ The only critical move and the whole point of the system. Other moves, such as  5.Rc1  cxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.Qxf6  gxf6  , already lead to a better endgame for Black. }
5... d6 6. Nf3 { With the plan of Nd2 and e4, which is also too slow. } 6...
exd5 7. cxd5 Nbd7 8. Nd2
{ 8.e4  would be premature again as Black can play  8...h6  when after  9.Bh4  g5  Black wins the e4-pawn, while taking on f6 is just a better position for Black. }
8... O-O 9. e4
{ Finally, White has reached the planned set-up, but just as in the 6.Qc2 variation, Black has the very strong ...Qe8! }
9... Qe8
{ Avoiding the pin and effectively attacking both e4- and d5-pawns at the same time. }
10. Bd3 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qe5
{ Once again using the fact that the ...h6/Bh4 pair of moves are not included. This forces White to take on f6, but then Black is just better. }
12. Bxf6 Nxf6 { These structures usually give Black better chances. } *

