[Black "6.Nf3 with 8.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5
{ The so-called Leningrad System of the Nimzo-Indian defense. It used to be a major and very serious weapon in the past, but nowadays it is out of fashion, mainly because modern computers showed a safe way to completely neutralize this system.   A very important point to note is that many times the ...h6/Bh4 pair of moves are included as a kind of automatic response. However, in this variation, it is key to avoid this inclusion! We are going to see why in the main line! }
4... c5 5. d5
{ The only critical move and the whole point of the system. Other moves, such as  5.Rc1  cxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.Qxf6  gxf6  , already lead to a better endgame for Black. }
5... d6 6. e3
{ In general, White would like to build a d5-e4-f3 pawn structure, but it must be done slowly, completing development first, otherwise White can get into trouble. The concrete  6.e4  would be met by  6...Bxc3+  7.bxc3  h6  and White is forced to give up the important bishop, otherwise White simply loses the e4-pawn. But even after  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  Black is better because of the weaknesses in White's structure. }
6... exd5 7. cxd5 Nbd7
{ Black prepares ...Qa5 by protecting the knight on f6. White's concrete problem is that should he complete development with Bd3, Nge2 and O-O, the d5-pawn will be hanging. Otherwise, there is no natural way to get the pieces to healthy positions in time. }
8. Bd3 Qa5
{ Just in time before the knight arrives to e2 and White can play O-O. Black now wins a pawn and the question is if White is able to create enough compensation... }
9. Ne2 Nxd5
{ Move 9 and we are a pawn up – usually not a bad sign for an interesting game! }
10. O-O Bxc3
{ Attention!!! An important move to be remembered – and not an easy move to play over the board in case you are repeating this line. }
11. bxc3
{ 11.Nxc3?  blunders a piece after  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  and now  12...c4!  attacking both bishops. }
11... c4
{ This is the key move of the variation and the reason why we did not include ...h6 earlier. The bishop on g5 stands in a lot of motifs by the queen. For example,  12.Bxc4?  loses to  12...N5b6!  with a double attack, and @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp1n1ppp/3p4/q2n2B1/2p5/2PBP3/P3NPPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Be4  also walks into  12...N5f6  and White has to give up its bishop, but then Black is just a pawn up. }
12. Bf5
{ It has been played in dozens of games, even by the legends, such as Timman-Karpov back in 1976, but here Black should simply castle. }
12... O-O
{ Instead of Karpov's  12...f6  , which is a bit too weakening. The white bishops are now standing in tactical motifs along the 5th rank. }
13. e4
{ 13.Qc2  can be answered by  13...N7f6  , exchanging the active pieces and keeping the extra pawn. @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1n1ppp/3p4/q2n1BB1/2p5/2P1P3/P3NPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qd2  happened in the game Yuneev-Dautov, Daugavpils 1989, but Black just took another pawn with  13...Nxc3  and enjoyed a big advantage. }
13... Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Qxc3 { We are 2 pawns up, but White has some counterplay: }
15. Rc1
{ 15.Qxd6  Qe5!  also preserves a healthy extra pawn without enough compensation for White. }
15... Qe5 16. Rxc4 Nb6
{ With an extra pawn in the game Jacob-Luther, Austria 2005. } *

