11... c4
{ This is the key move of the variation and the reason why we did not include ...h6 earlier. The bishop on g5 stands in a lot of motifs by the queen. For example,  12.Bxc4?  loses to  12...N5b6!  with a double attack, and @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp1n1ppp/3p4/q2n2B1/2p5/2PBP3/P3NPPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Be4  also walks into  12...N5f6  and White has to give up its bishop, but then Black is just a pawn up. }
12. Bc2 { Other bishop moves are worse. } 12... O-O
{ We have reached the critical position from White's point of view, where the first player has to search for interesting options and compensation. However, thanks to the strong computers of the modern era, it seems the conlcusion is that the maximum for White here is to reach equality with very precise play, otherwise, White is just facing trouble. }
13. Nd4 Nxc3 { We take the pawn! } 14. Qh5
{ Occurred in the game Bareev-Dautov, Moscow 1990, when Black should have continued with ...f5. }
14... f5 { As we saw in the line above, it usually works! } 15. Be7 Nf6
{ An important intermediate move which holds Black's position together and once we survive the next few moves, we will enjoy the extra material. }
16. Qh4 Rf7 { Everything appears solid. } 17. Bxd6 Nce4
{ And an extra pawn is an extra pawn: Black is clearly much better. } *

