1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2
{ Recently this move has started to enjoy some popularity even at the highest level. However, in most cases, White plays e3 next move or after Nf3, and those lines transpose to the  4.e3  Nimzo-Indian,  5.Bd2 variations. In this game, we will only be checking the alternative moves, but they are not dangerous at all, as we will see. }
4... O-O 5. a3 { Completely harmless as Black can react by taking on c3. } 5...
Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Ne4
{ It is important to go for the bishop before White can preserve it. } 7. Rc1
{ Black has many easy ways to equalize after this alternative. } 7... d6 8. Nf3
Qe7
{ Black can also play for ...e5, while ...b6 and ... Bb7 also offers easy equality. }
9. e3 c5
{ We do not hurry with the capture on c3 because the bishop has no squares to run to. }
10. Be2 b6 11. O-O
{ Now that White wants to play Be1 next, we must take on c3. } 11... Nxc3 12.
Rxc3 Bb7
{ And as we already know from other Nimzo lines, such structures do not give White any advantage. }
