1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2
{ Recently this move has started to enjoy some popularity even at the highest level. However, in most cases, White plays e3 next move or after Nf3, and those lines transpose to the  4.e3  Nimzo-Indian,  5.Bd2 variations. In this game, we will only be checking the alternative moves, but they are not dangerous at all, as we will see. }
4... O-O 5. Nf3 { 5.e3  d5  transposes to the 4.e3 Nimzo-Indian. } 5... d5 6.
a3
{ This line was recently played by Ivanchuk and Korobov.  6.e3  is the main move, but it would again just transpose to the 4. e3 Nimzo-Indian with 5. Bd2 where we meet 6.e3 with 6...b6. }
6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ White has achieved something at least – the bishop pair. On the other hand, Black is in time to create dynamic play and equalize... }
7... dxc4
{ I suggest this most challenging approach for Black as it is not that obvious how White can win back or compensate for the sacrificed pawn. Black wants to hold the extra pawn by playing ...b5, but  8.Qa4  would be a mistake as it runs into  8...Qd5!  when ... b5 next move leaves White without compensation. }
8. a4
{ Seems to win back the pawn after all, but Black has many ways to equalize because having already played 6.a3 the further a-pawn move is a loss of tempo. }
8... b6 9. e3 Ba6 { Trying to play ...Nbd7 and ... c5. } 10. Ne5 Ne4
{ White must be careful or black gets the edge, as  11.Bxc4  would be met by taking on c4, then on c3, with ...Qd5 at the end landing a double attack on c4 and g2. }
11. Qc2 { There is nothing better for White. } 11... Nxc3 12. Qxc3 Nd7
{ Completing development and reaching complete equality. } 13. Bxc4
{ More exchanges will follow. } 13... Bxc4 14. Nxc4 c5
{ And once again Black has equal play. The ...c5 break has been played successfully, so why should we be worse now?! }
