{ With the idea of completing development first with Bd3 and Ne2 and only later pushing e4. This position also arises from the Nimzo-Indian @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  variation after  4...O-O  5.a3  Bxc3  . }
6... d6
{ There are many other playable setups as well, but the practice has shown that Black has excellent chances to grab the initiative with the current line. }
7. Ne2
{ Having foreseen that Black wants to play the ...e5 line, this is a common response in similar situations: White moves the knight to g3 first and keeps a wider choice of moves in case of ...e5. However, in this case, Black can change plan... }
7... c5
{ Black uses the standard plan of attacking the weakness on c4. The idea is ...Nc6, followed by ...b6, ...Ba6, ...Na5 and, if needed, ...Rc8. }
8. Ng3 Nc6 9. Bd3 b6 { Now, in case of  10.e4  ,  the d4-pawn is hanging. } 10.
O-O Ba6
{ Black executes the abovementioned plan and the c4-pawn is going to come under a heavy attack. }
11. Qe2 Rc8 12. Bb2
{ Protecting the d4-pawn in order to be able to push e4, and also trying to defend the c4 weakness.  12.d5?!  is strongly met by  12...Ne5!  with an excellent position for Black. }
12... Na5 { The final move of the plan – now the c4-pawn is hanging. } 13. d5
Nd7
{ A small improvement on previous games. Black would like to play ...Ne5, which works even after  14.dxe6  Ne5  , and if White prevents it by @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/p2n1ppp/bp1pp3/n1pP4/2P5/P1PBP1N1/1B2QPPP/R4RK1 w - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.f4  , then  14...exd5  . }
14. f4 exd5 { A simple and strong response. } 15. cxd5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 c4
{ Black will follow with ...Nc5-d3 and the other knight jumps to b3 with complete control over the b2-bishop and White's position. }
