1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3
{ The Saemisch Variation of the Nimzo-Indian. A very sharp opening that resides in the repertoire of many top players, who often use it as a dangerous surprise weapon – especially those players who also like the  4.f3  system, as these two lines often lead to similar positions. It is a very concrete provocation of the bishop to take on c3. White forces the damage of their own pawn structure, but intends to compensate for this with the bishop pair and a very strong center, which is often occupied with the further move e4. }
4... Bxc3+ { We have no real choice but to take the knight. } 5. bxc3 O-O
{ It is very important to castle first to get the right move order. Now, White must occupy the center with e4 and there are two ways to do it: the main line is  6.f3  here, however, in that case, Black plays  4...d5  and we transpose to the Nimzo-Indian 4.f3 variation. Please see the 4.f3 chapter. }
6. e3
{ With the idea of completing development first with Bd3 and Ne2 and only later pushing e4. This position also arises from the Nimzo-Indian @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  variation after  4...O-O  5.a3  Bxc3  . }
6... d6
{ There are many other playable setups as well, but the practice has shown that Black has excellent chances to grab the initiative with the current line. }
7. Bd3 e5 8. Ne2 e4
{ Closing the diagonal, not allowing White to occupy the center with e4 and getting ready to attack the c4-weakness. }
9. Bb1 Be6 10. Ng3 Bxc4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4
{ White finally manages to free the position a bit, but it is still very difficult to activate the c1-bishop. In addition, White will also be forced to give up his bishop pair, or otherwise be unable to castle. I suggest a novelty here, which already gives Black an advantage. }
12... Nc6
{ With the idea that White needs to play Bd3 now @@StartBracket@@or after  13.Rb1  Rb8  @@EndBracket@@  in order to play O-O, but in this case the black knight immediately arrives to replace the c4-bishop. }
13. Bd3
{ It is hard to find something better for White: to play long-term without short castling looks very dangerous! }
13... Na5
{ Black would like to play ...d5 next with a structural advantage and a superior knight over the bishop. }
14. e4
{ The only chance to break out, but the structure can be undermined by ...f5, which is possible right away or after  14...Qd7  . }
14... f5 { Very strong play and an idea to remember! } 15. Bxc4+ Nxc4 16. Qb3
{ White tries for tactical chances, as there is no better attempt. } 16... d5
{ Most important is that the c4-knight has a stable position. } 17. e5 f4
{ This kills the c1-bishop and obtains excellent attacking chances for Black. Going for the b7-pawn is a suicide, but in any case, Black is much better here. }
18. Qxb7 Rb8 { The white king will soon be in big trouble. } 19. Qc6 Rb6 20.
Qc5 { And finally we have the nice push... } 20... f3
{ White cannot survive the attack, especially having with the king on e1 and having nowhere safe to go.   Conclusion: If it was up to me, I would love my opponents to try this line of the Nimzo against me! I believe Black quickly obtains at least a playable position, with great chances of taking over the initiative. }
