[White "6) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qb3 and 4.Bf4"]
[Black "4.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ It is hard to find something 'new' in the Nimzo, so in the current chapter we are going to take a look at 2 different and relatively rare continuations: 4. Qb3 and 4.Bf4. Neither continuation is dangerous, but still, it is better to know how to act against them than not! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bf4
{ A very rare move, and it cannot be dangerous of course, but on the other hand it is also not possible to punish it. We should just focus on healthy development, which should lead us to a nice position. }
4... c5
{ Just as against the  4.Bg5  line, it is natural to directly challenge the center. }
5. e3
{ 5.dxc5  Na6  is harmless, while after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/2p5/1bPP1B2/2N5/PP2PPPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq c6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d5?!  Black can already look for an advantage with  5...Ne4  6.Qc2  Qf6!  . }
5... d5 6. Nf3
{ Delaying development might backfire. For example:  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.bxc3  Qa5!  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/1bPP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq d6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.dxc5  Nbd7!  7.Nf3  Nxc5  8.Be2  Nfe4  – both lines are already becoming a bit unpleasant for White. }
6... cxd4
{ Black can also start with  6...O-O  , which should eventually lead to the same position. }
7. exd4
{ There is no need to be afraid of  7.Qa4+  because of  7...Nc6  8.Nxd4  and now  8...Qa5  . }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ White has to lose the tempo with the bishop, as they need to hurry with development. Trying to change the structure with  8.c5?  is clearly premature as Black can simply undermine the pawn with  8...b6  and get an advantage. }
8... dxc4 9. Bxc4
{ And here Black has a choice. At first sight  9...Nd5  looks very tempting to make use of the pin and the early move of the c1-bishop, but somehow the position is not so easy after the retreat  10.Bd2  . An alternative is to play @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4pn2/8/1bBP1B2/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b6  10.O-O  Bb7  which transposes to one of the very big main lines of the Nimzo-Indian with 4.e3, where White has played a rare and not so strong move with Bf4. Still, there would be a lot to learn in that case, and I don't believe that such a move like 4.Bf4 deserves such attention, therefore I have found a very easy and strong alternative with ...a6. }
9... a6 { And the very simple plan of playing ...b5 and ...Bb7. } 10. a4
{ Would give up the b4-square as well. In this case, Black should complete development with ...Nc6. }
10... Nc6 11. O-O b6
{ Followed by ...Bb7 with a nice position against the isolated d4-pawn. There is no need to be afraid of the d5-break as after ...Na5 with tempo, followed by taking on c3, Black will win the d5-pawn. }
12. Ba2 { White prepares for the d5-break. } 12... Ne7
{ And Black creates a perfect blockade on d5 after ...Bb7. } *

