1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3
{ A relatively rare move that is used sometimes as a surprise weapon, even by grandmasters. }
4... c5
{ The most natural move, protecting the bishop and challenging the center at the same time. }
5. Bg5
{ 5.Nf3  b6  Of course, 5...b6 is not necessary, and Black can also play  5...Nc6  6.e3  and either  6...d5  immediately, or after  6...cxd4  7.exd4  d5  in both cases with an equal position.   5.e3  b6  6.Nf3  does not have its own significance as we just transpose to the Nimzo-Indian 4.Nf3 variation with 5. Qb3. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 g5 { The game is becoming very dynamic. } 7. Bg3 Nc6
{ Black immediately aims for White's center. } 8. dxc5 Ne4
{ Transposes to the 5.dxc5 Nc6 main line with 6. Bg5 h6. } *

