[White "6) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qb3 and 4.Bf4"]
[Black " 4.Qb3 c5 5.dxc5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

{ It is hard to find something 'new' in the Nimzo, so in the current chapter we are going to take a look at 2 different and relatively rare continuations.  4.Qb3  and  4.Bf4  . Neither continuation is dangerous, but still, it is better to know how to act against them than not! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3
{ A relatively rare move that is used sometimes as a surprise weapon, even by grandmasters. }
4... c5
{ The most natural move, protecting the bishop and challenging the center at the same time. }
5. dxc5
{ The main response. Compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  Nimzo-Indian line with  4...c5  @@StartBracket@@we don't play this move@@EndBracket@@,  the queen on b3 is completely misplaced. }
5... Nc6
{ Black is not in rush to take back the pawn as it will not run away and, meanwhile, Black can create more threats with ...Ne4 or ...Qa5. }
6. Nf3 Ne4
{ There are other good moves as well, but it looks tempting to either crush the pawn structure or grab the bishop pair. }
7. Bd2
{ White is better to not allow the capture on c3 as he won't have any compensation for the weaknesses. }
7... Nxd2 8. Nxd2 Bxc5
{ Black has a healthy pawn structure and the bishop pair. The only question is if it is realistic to play for an advantage or not. }
9. g3
{ Not the most frequently-played move, but fianchettoing the bishop is the most logical continuation. If  9.Nde4  Black can simply retreat with ...Be7 and later if he wants he can push back the knight with ...f5. And here Black can decide the character of the game according to his style. Black can still continue with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2b5/2P5/1QN3P1/PP1NPP1P/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b6  10.Bg2  Bb7  with a completely fine middlegame, which is also the most common move in the position. But, he can also choose to play an endgame with ...Qb6. }
9... Qb6
{ Which has not been played in any games yet, but the arising position is really comfortable. }
10. Qxb6 Bxb6 11. Bg2 d6 { What a pleasant endgame for Black! } 12. e3 Ke7 13.
Ke2 Bd7
{ Objectively with equality, but in the long-term Black has better potential to turn the game in their favor, once Black manages to put pressure on the c4-pawn and the two bishops start to express their power.   Conclusion: Neither move of White, 4.Qb3 and 4.Bf4, are dangerous in many different ways and there is nothing special to remember as Black. Use the usual ideas – play safe and central! }
