[Black "5.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ A very solid system for Black which might also arise from the Queen's Indian move-order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.Nc3  Bb4  .  Since Nf3 is a flexible move for White, there are now a wide list of alternatives to the main  5.Bg5  line, but often they will just transpose to other Nimzo-Indian variations. }
5. g3 Bxc3+
{ Black can damage the structure. White has compensation in the bishop pair, but the one on g2 will be immediately opposed by the great b7-bishop. }
6. bxc3 Bb7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O d6
{ This position was considered to be completely fine for Black, but some new ideas made it interesting. }
9. a4 { With the idea of pushing a5. } 9... Nc6 10. Nd2
{ White can play this knight retreat without trading the bishops, and plans to push e4 next. However, Black's position is still perfectly fine. }
10... Na5 11. e4 c5
{ A typical way of fixing the c4-weakness, which will be attacked by ...Ba6 and ...Rc8. Black's position might already be better, especially because the knight on d2 is tied to protecting the c4-pawn, but it also locks in the c1-bishop while the a1-rook is useless on the queenside. }
12. d5 Qe7 *

