[Black "5.g3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ A very solid system for Black which might also arise from the Queen's Indian move-order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.Nc3  Bb4  .  Since Nf3 is a flexible move for White, there are now a wide list of alternatives to the main  5.Bg5  line, but often they will just transpose to other Nimzo-Indian variations. }
5. g3 Bxc3+
{ Black can damage the structure. White has compensation in the bishop pair, but the one on g2 will be immediately opposed by the great b7-bishop. }
6. bxc3 Bb7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O d6
{ This position was considered to be completely fine for Black, but some new ideas made it interesting. }
9. d5
{ This is a common idea from the 4. g3 Queen's Indian. White would like to play Nh4 in case of ...exd5, and otherwise, he wishes to get his knight on d4 and protect the structure with e4. There have been a lot of games lately, but I suggest a novelty against it...   9.Bg5  is actually the most common move, but it cannot cause any problems as after both  9...h6  , or  9...Nbd7  first and then ... h6, White gives up his bishop pair, which is supposed to give the compensation for the damaged pawn structure. }
9... Qc8
{ After protecting the b7-bishop, Black is threatening to take on d5. White is forced to make an ugly move to protect it, but Black's position remains very good in any case. }
10. Bg5 { 10.Nh4  Nbd7  with ...Ne5 or just ...Nc5 ideas is also good. } 10...
Nbd7 11. Nd4 Re8
{ Avoiding the  11...exd5  12.Nf5  trap that would allow White to fix their pawn structure. The d5-pawn is already hanging and Black is also ready to ask the bishop a question with ...h6 and  @@StartFEN@@r1q1r1k1/pbpn1ppp/1p1ppn2/3P2B1/2PN4/2P3P1/P3PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12.e4  could be answered by  12...exd5  when White would be forced to take back with  13.exd5  , but after  13...h6  only Black can stand better. }
*

