1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ A very solid system for Black which might also arise from the Queen's Indian move-order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.Nc3  Bb4  .  Since Nf3 is a flexible move for White, there are now a wide list of alternatives to the main  5.Bg5  line, but often they will just transpose to other Nimzo-Indian variations. }
5. Qb3
{ A very serious alternative to the main line, played frequently by Mamedyarov. }
5... c5
{ In this variation, Black often, instead of the natural ...Bb7, quickly puts strong pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6 and possibly later switches attention to the c4-pawn with ...Na5 and ...Ba6. }
6. a3 Ba5
{ Black can preserve the bishop to keep the tension, and take on c3 later to potentially double the pawns. Here all the moves are possible again, just as without the inclusion of the a3/...Ba5 pair of moves, but I don't see any lines where White can profit from this: on the contrary, sometimes it is useful for Black to have this addition because the bishop might not be hanging on b4 in some variations. }
7. dxc5
{ Could be a difference, as we cannot take back with the bishop, but on the other hand, we can play ...Ne4. }
7... Ne4 { A nice intermediate move. } 8. cxb6 Qxb6 9. Qxb6 axb6
{ With a better endgame for Black after destroying the structure by taking on c3. Obviously  10.b4?  allows  10...Bxb4  . }
*

