5. Qb3
{ A very serious alternative to the main line, played frequently by Mamedyarov. }
5... c5
{ In this variation, Black often, instead of the natural ...Bb7, quickly puts strong pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6 and possibly later switches attention to the c4-pawn with ...Na5 and ...Ba6. }
6. e3 { This cannot be the most dangerous move. } 6... O-O 7. Be2 Ne4
{ Black would like to damage the white pawn structure. If  8.O-O  Bxc3  9.bxc3  Nc6  is good for Black, as next we can start an attack against the c4-weakness with ...Na5, ...Ba6 and ...Rc8. The e4-knight can be stabilized with ...f5 if needed. }
8. Bd2 Nxd2 9. Nxd2 Nc6
{ Black was already a bit better in the game Browne-Lein, Chicago 1982. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
