[White "7) Nimzo Indian with 4.Nf3, 5.Qc2 and 5.Qb3+"]
[Black "5.Qb3 with 6.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ A very solid system for Black which might also arise from the Queen's Indian move-order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.Nc3  Bb4  .  Since Nf3 is a flexible move for White, there are now a wide list of alternatives to the main  5.Bg5  line, but often they will just transpose to other Nimzo-Indian variations. }
5. Qb3
{ A very serious alternative to the main line, played frequently by Mamedyarov. }
5... c5
{ In this variation, Black often, instead of the natural ...Bb7, quickly puts strong pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6 and possibly later switches attention to the c4-pawn with ...Na5 and ...Ba6. }
6. Bg5 { Pinning the knight is the most common continuation. } 6... h6 7. Bh4
g5 8. Bg3 Ne4
{ Black is ready to create doubled pawns for long-term weaknesses and also to remove the strong g3-bishop. }
9. e3
{ 9.O-O-O  is risky in view of  9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Nc6  and the pawns are easily attackable by our typical manoeuvres ...Na5, ...Ba6 and ... Rc8, leaving the king also exposed on c1.  Here I played @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p2p1p2/1p2p2p/2p3p1/1bPPn3/1QN1PNB1/PP3PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  against Kramnik, which is playable, but I also like the following continuation. }
9... Bb7 10. d5
{ Played by Topalov against Georgiev in 2013. The point is to not allow the knight to develop to c6, but Black has other good places for the knight. }
10... d6 11. O-O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3
{ And here Black should have just played ...Qf6. } 12... Qf6 13. Kb2 Nd7
{ And only Black can be better with his superior structure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Nimzo Indian with 4.Nf3, 5.Qc2 and 5.Qb3+"]
[Black "5.Qb3 with 6.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ A very solid system for Black which might also arise from the Queen's Indian move-order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.Nc3  Bb4  .  Since Nf3 is a flexible move for White, there are now a wide list of alternatives to the main  5.Bg5  line, but often they will just transpose to other Nimzo-Indian variations. }
5. Qb3
{ A very serious alternative to the main line, played frequently by Mamedyarov. }
5... c5
{ In this variation, Black often, instead of the natural ...Bb7, quickly puts strong pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6 and possibly later switches attention to the c4-pawn with ...Na5 and ...Ba6. }
6. Bg5 { Pinning the knight is the most common continuation. } 6... h6 7. Bh4
g5 8. Bg3 Ne4
{ Black is ready to create doubled pawns for long-term weaknesses and also to remove the strong g3-bishop. }
9. e3
{ 9.O-O-O  is risky in view of  9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Nc6  and the pawns are easily attackable by our typical manoeuvres ...Na5, ...Ba6 and ... Rc8, leaving the king also exposed on c1.  Here I played @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p2p1p2/1p2p2p/2p3p1/1bPPn3/1QN1PNB1/PP3PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  against Kramnik, which is playable, but I also like the following continuation. }
9... Bb7 10. Nd2
{ Was a very interesting try by Edouard against Karpov in 2015. Edouard also played this position against me very recently in the 2022 Bundesliga. Black has a lot of options, but I suggest taking on c3. }
10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Nxg3
{ I would prefer to eliminate the strong bishop, rather than to let the white king sit in the center where it is still protected by a lot of pawns. }
12. hxg3
{ And now White has the idea of playing a4-a5 which should be prevented right away since trying to do so a move later would still allow a5 as the bishop is hanging on b7. }
12... Nc6
{ This move was rejected by Karpov and actually, I played  12...d6  because I did not remember the lines and I thought ...d6 looks solid. But, in fact,  12...Nc6  is a very exact way of gaining a fine position. }
13. dxc5
{ This indeed wins a pawn, but the remaining white pawn structure remains so weak, that Black has definitely full compensation for the pawn, even if he does not win it back right away... }
13... Qc7 14. cxb6 axb6 15. Rb1 Nd8
{ With ideas of ...Bc6 @@StartBracket@@sometimes ...Qa7@@EndBracket@@ and ...Nb7-c5. }
*

