5. Qb3
{ A very serious alternative to the main line, played frequently by Mamedyarov. }
5... c5
{ In this variation, Black often, instead of the natural ...Bb7, quickly puts strong pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6 and possibly later switches attention to the c4-pawn with ...Na5 and ...Ba6. }
6. Bg5 { Pinning the knight is the most common continuation. } 6... h6 7. Bh4
g5 8. Bg3 Ne4
{ Black is ready to create doubled pawns for long-term weaknesses and also to remove the strong g3-bishop. }
9. e3
{ 9.O-O-O  is risky in view of  9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Nc6  and the pawns are easily attackable by our typical manoeuvres ...Na5, ...Ba6 and ... Rc8, leaving the king also exposed on c1.  Here I played @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p2p1p2/1p2p2p/2p3p1/1bPPn3/1QN1PNB1/PP3PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  against Kramnik, which is playable, but I also like the following continuation. }
