[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Nimzo Indian with 4.Nf3, 5.Qc2 and 5.Qb3+"]
[Black "5.Qb3 with 6.Bg5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ A very solid system for Black which might also arise from the Queen's Indian move-order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.Nc3  Bb4  .  Since Nf3 is a flexible move for White, there are now a wide list of alternatives to the main  5.Bg5  line, but often they will just transpose to other Nimzo-Indian variations. }
5. Qb3
{ A very serious alternative to the main line, played frequently by Mamedyarov. }
5... c5
{ In this variation, Black often, instead of the natural ...Bb7, quickly puts strong pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6 and possibly later switches attention to the c4-pawn with ...Na5 and ...Ba6. }
6. Bg5 { Pinning the knight is the most common continuation. } 6... h6 7. Bh4
g5 8. Bg3 Ne4
{ Black is ready to create doubled pawns for long-term weaknesses and also to remove the strong g3-bishop. }
9. e3
{ 9.O-O-O  is risky in view of  9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  Nc6  and the pawns are easily attackable by our typical manoeuvres ...Na5, ...Ba6 and ... Rc8, leaving the king also exposed on c1.  Here I played @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p2p1p2/1p2p2p/2p3p1/1bPPn3/1QN1PNB1/PP3PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  against Kramnik, which is playable, but I also like the following continuation. }
9... Bb7 10. Bd3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 Nc6
{ Again this should be played to get the knight to  a5  with a long-term attack against the c4-pawn. Black should play for ...O-O-O when the king will be safe.  13.Rh5  can be met by  13...Qf6  with a double-edged position, where Black is not worse. }
13. dxc5
{ There is no need to be afraid of losing a pawn, as Black can get the e5-square for his knight. }
13... g4 { Chasing away the f3-knight. } 14. Nd2 Ne5 15. Be4
{ There is nothing better for White. } 15... Bxe4 16. Nxe4 bxc5
{ And the knight on e5 will become much more powerful as Black can send away the other one with ...f5 or ...Qc7-c6 with a better position for Black because of the better structure.   Conclusion: We just saw a lot of different 'smaller' lines, with rich positions and many different ideas for both sides. Nothing seems to be very dangerous for Black and sometimes we even have good counter chances, with many alternatives for playing for the full point. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Nimzo Indian with 4.Nf3 and 5.Bg5"]
[Black "8.Rc1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5
{ The Nimzo line with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  b6  5.Bg5  may look dangerous, but with exact play, Black has good play and can reach interesting positions. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 g5
{ It is more common to reach our main line from the ...Bb7 move order either now, or on the previous move, but in this way we can avoid the dangerous  7.Nd2  line. }
7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Rc1 Bb7 9. Nd2
{ The text move can be considered as an alternative, but hardly a dangerous one. Black should use the standard exchange to damage the opponent's pawn structure and then remove the strong dark-squared bishop. }
9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nxg3 11. hxg3
{ Personally, I enjoy such structures as Black. I think Black has easy play and by having a nice pawn structure it offers a clear way to play the position. }
11... d6 12. e4 Nd7 13. Bd3
{ With the idea of protecting the e4-pawn in order to be able to improve the knight with Nf1-e3. Black reacted very well with ...c5. }
13... c5 14. Nf1 Qf6
{ Putting pressure on the center and trying to force d5, after which Black would also gain access to some holes in White's position. }
15. Bc2 h5
{ A very important plan from this variation's point of view. When Black succeeds in pushing ...h4, that is usually the moment when we can already speak about an advantage. Black would happily exchange the h-pawn for the opposing pawn on d4. }
16. Ne3 h4 17. gxh4 gxh4 18. Ba4 O-O-O
{ With a clean advantage for Black in the game Braun-Meier, Magdeburg 2021. Black's king is safe, whereas White's on e1 is in long-term danger, which makes Black's the simpler of the two. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Nimzo Indian with 4.Nf3 and 5.Bg5"]
[Black "8.Rc1 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5
{ The Nimzo line with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  b6  5.Bg5  may look dangerous, but with exact play, Black has good play and can reach interesting positions. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 g5
{ It is more common to reach our main line from the ...Bb7 move order either now, or on the previous move, but in this way we can avoid the dangerous  7.Nd2  line. }
7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Rc1 Bb7 9. Nd2
{ The text move can be considered as an alternative, but hardly a dangerous one. Black should use the standard exchange to damage the opponent's pawn structure and then remove the strong dark-squared bishop. }
9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nxg3 11. hxg3
{ Personally, I enjoy such structures as Black. I think Black has easy play and by having a nice pawn structure it offers a clear way to play the position. }
11... d6 12. e4 Nd7 13. Qa4
{ This is usually an important point for White to try to prevent Black from castling queenside. However, as we will see, the black king can be safe on other parts of the board as well. Meanwhile, the queen might find herself misplaced on a4. }
13... c5 14. Bd3
{ And just as in the game from the previous 13.Bd3 c5 line, Black took the chance to play ...h5. }
14... h5
{ Black not only gets rid of his weak, backward pawn, but also prepares to squeeze the opponent on the kingside, an area where White is supposed to be doing well. }
15. Kf1 h4 16. Re1 Ke7
{ Not strictly necessary, but Black demonstrates that the king can be safe in the center as well. }
17. gxh4 Rxh4 18. Rxh4 gxh4 19. Re3 Qg8 20. Nf3 Qg4
{ Gareev-Adams, Los Angeles 2011. } *

