[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Nimzo Indian with 4.Nf3 and 5.Bg5"]
[Black "8.Qc2 with 9.Be5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5
{ The Nimzo line with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  b6  5.Bg5  may look dangerous, but with exact play, Black has good play and can reach interesting positions. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 g5
{ It is more common to reach our main line from the ...Bb7 move order either now, or on the previous move, but in this way we can avoid the dangerous  7.Nd2  line. }
7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. Be5
{ A wild move, played by many strong grandmasters, but Black can neutralize it with cold-blooded play. }
9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Rg8
{ There is no need to enter into the big complications with  10...f6  . Now if  11.Nd2  , it is just better for Black after  11...f5!  as White also needs to spend some time to save the e5-bishop. }
11. d5
{ Dreev and Sjugirov have tried this idea against Ivanchuk and Karjakin respectively, and both top GMs continued with  11...f5  , however, it is not at all clear what happens if Black just accepts the sacrifice. Of course, with the help of modern engines, it is easier to advise such things... }
11... exd5 12. cxd5 Bxd5 { A very sharp position, but we are a pawn up! } 13.
Rd1 Bb7
{ At first sight, it appears that White should have compensation, but after some precise moves it disappears. }
14. e3 d6 15. Rd4 Nd7 { This is a crazy computer line. } 16. Bb5 f5
{ Black just wants to play ...Qe7 and ...O-O-O and White ended up without compensation in the game Berczes-Greet, Budapest 2005. }
*

