1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5
{ The Nimzo line with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  b6  5.Bg5  may look dangerous, but with exact play, Black has good play and can reach interesting positions. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 g5
{ It is more common to reach our main line from the ...Bb7 move order either now, or on the previous move, but in this way we can avoid the dangerous  7.Nd2  line. }
7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. e3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d6 11. Bd3
{ Once again, the move  11.Nd2  leads to the type of positions that we discussed in the 8.Rc1 Bb7 line after  11...Nxg3  12.hxg3  Nd7  . }
11... f5
{ Black successfully secures the outpost of the knight on e4 and the control of the h1-a8 diagonal. However, Black has also weakened their structure, so White must urgently try to make use of this before Black completes development with ...Nd7 and starts an attack with ...h5. }
12. c5
{ Is a very interesting modern idea, which is also supported by the computer.  12...bxc5  13.Qb3  leads to crazy complications which I suggest avoiding from a practical point of view. }
12... Nd7 13. cxd6 cxd6 14. O-O
{ And now it is very important to play ...Rc8. } 14... Rc8
{ It seems like the only way to equalize. The position remains very sharp... }
15. Qa4 { It is an interesting attempt to improve on the previous play. } 15...
Rxc3 16. Bxe4 fxe4 17. Nd2 Qc7
{ White sacrifices a pawn but it looks like they can't get more than just compensation for it. The computer suggests an unusual repetition with  18.Nb1  Rc6  19.Nd2  Rc3  with a draw. }
18. Nb3 { A more human way to continue. } 18... Ke7 19. Rac1
{ But Black can neutralize the pressure by taking on c1. } 19... Rxc1 20. Rxc1
Qb8 21. Qa3
{ The alternative  21.Nd2  Rc8  22.Rxc8  Qxc8  is better for Black. } 21... Rc8
{ We continue to exchange the pieces. } 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. Nd2 Nf6
{ And Black is just in time to consolidate and protect everything with  24.Nc4  Ne8  after which we can also activate the bishop via b7-d5. }
