[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Nimzo Indian with 4.Nf3 and 5.Bg5"]
[Black "8.Qc2 with 9.e3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5
{ The Nimzo line with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  b6  5.Bg5  may look dangerous, but with exact play, Black has good play and can reach interesting positions. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 g5
{ It is more common to reach our main line from the ...Bb7 move order either now, or on the previous move, but in this way we can avoid the dangerous  7.Nd2  line. }
7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. e3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d6 11. Bd3
{ Once again, the move  11.Nd2  leads to the type of positions that we discussed in the 8.Rc1 Bb7 line after  11...Nxg3  12.hxg3  Nd7  . }
11... f5
{ Black successfully secures the outpost of the knight on e4 and the control of the h1-a8 diagonal. However, Black has also weakened their structure, so White must urgently try to make use of this before Black completes development with ...Nd7 and starts an attack with ...h5. }
12. d5
{ A known idea. White tries to sacrifice a pawn to close the long diagonal, in order to damage the healthy pawn chain and to get the very nice d4-square for his knight, after which the black steed on e4 can be kicked out with f3. The drawbacks of the move are that it gives up the c5-square, and in the long-term the doubled c-pawns will be doomed. }
12... Na6
{ The knight heads immediately to the weakened square. There are other options as well, but I prefer this very principled main idea. }
13. Nd4
{ Is definitely a critical test of the variation, leading to sharper positions than the main line. But on the other hand, it does not win material here. }
13... Nac5
{ White has three interesting options now:  14.dxe6  ,  14.Nxe6  and  14.O-O }
14. dxe6 Qf6 15. f3 { Is strongly met by ...Nxd3+ } 15... Nxd3+ 16. Qxd3 f4
{ An important intermediate move to avoid losing the f5-pawn and to completely destroy White's pawn structure. }
17. exf4 Nc5
{ Is good for Black, as they can take on f4 next move, which will be protected by ...Nd3 check. }
18. Qc2 gxf4 19. Bf2 O-O-O
{ Black was better in the game Pinter-Jankovic, Sibenik 2008. } *

