{ This position has been reached in several grandmaster games and Black has never had any problems, despite being a pawn down after the capture on e6. There are many reasons for this, one being that in this whole variation, in many lines the bishop on g3 is restricted by the d6/c7 pawns and it is simply unable to improve. Another factor is obviously the poor structure of the remaining white pawns. Actually, it is interesting, but this position is even given as better for Black according to the strongest engines. }
19. h4
{ Was played twice by Wang Yue. It is probably the right decision to simplify the game before White gets seriously worse. }
19... Nxe6 20. hxg5 hxg5 21. Kg2
{ Visually the position might look better for White because of the extra pawn, but in fact Black is doing perfectly OK. }
21... Rhf8 22. Rad1
{ And here, in both Wang Yue games, Leko and Adams played  22...Rf5  23.Rd5  Rdf8  24.Rxf5  Rxf5  and the games finished in a draw not much later. I would, however, suggest a small improvement... }
22... Rf6
{ Followed by ...Rdf8, keeping both rooks on board. White has no chance to make progress on the kingside, while Black is ready to activate their king on the queenside. The engine even gives a small plus for Black.   Conclusion: This is a hard line to learn, with long variations, and sometimes we must be exact. On the other hand, we can obviously aim for more than a draw straight out of the opening. The positions are sharp and very unclear. It is hard to imagine that both White and Black are going to play 20 best moves of theory, and most probably some side is going to respond in a 'new' way and the game is going to be wide open. I would advise you not to be 'too scared' of the long lines. In case you forget something, the position is still going to be in most cases 'unclear'. Even so...this is a line which it is 'better' to know than just to be played on feeling. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, an introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein variation. The biggest, most critical, and most dangerous for Black in my opinion. Be ready to fight for equality, as it is not so simple. On the other hand, you will reach a lot of very interesting positions, and discover beautiful ideas - this is a great example of how colorful an opening can be! }
4... O-O
{ White can now choose between 6 main moves, so basically it is an opening inside an opening. Luckily for us, some of the lines are just transpositions, so we can save some time. }
5. Bd3
{ This is clearly the main line.   A@@EndBracket@@  5.a3  Bxc3+  6.bxc3  d6  transposes to the Nimzo Indian 4.a3 variation. Please check it in the 4.a3 chapter.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Nf3  does not have individual significance as after  5...b6  6.Bd3  d5  transposes to the 5.Bd3 main line.   6.Bd2  d5  transposes to the 5.Bd2 line.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.Bd2  it is easy to see that this move should clearly not refute the Nimzo, but still, it is better to know what to reply with and to collect the positional understanding on similar positions for our own chess knowledge and future games.  5...d5   D@@EndBracket@@  5.Nge2  This is a tricky line. White wants to play a3 next and get the bishop pair, or 'win a tempo'. On the other hand, the position of the knight on e2 while still having the bishop on f1 is obviously not the best. It does, however, lead to very interesting positions, and we will try here a relatively rare move.  5...c6  6.a3  Ba5  and our bishop escapes to c7 - a nice square. The game is likely to be very exciting with a lot of counter-chances for Black, and in addition, you have the chance that your opponent is not really ready to show anything 'special' against 5...c6!? }
5... d5
{ We have reached what is perhaps the most critical position of the Nimzo-Indian. White has 4 main options here:  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  ,  6.a3  , and  6.cxd5  - and all of them are a realistic attempt to get a better position out of the opening! In the lines you are going to see, we are fighting for equality and sometimes even hoping to get dynamic play.   Nobody can promise you 100% that Black is fine or equal in all of the lines, and from time-to-time White is going to find some new approach and we will have to update and revise our lines, but I believe that with the current Chessable course you will have excellent fundamental material to start with and also advance your future Nimzo knowledge! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Bd2"]
[Black "6.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2
{ Welcome to the line with 5.Bd2. Obviously, the idea of the move is to play a3 at a good moment and if Black takes on c3, White recaptures with the bishop, maintaining a healthy pawn structure. However, this line is in general not dangerous for Black. }
5... d5
{ As in most of our recommended lines, we will focus our attention on the ...d5 move. We are fighting for control of the center and I believe that in most cases this will be the most solid approach. }
6. Nf3 b6 7. Rc1
{ White can try to avoid losing a tempo on moving with the Bf1, and Rc1 seems to be a useful move. }
7... Ba6
{ Black, in turn, can try to be clever and attempt to deprive White from castling. }
8. Qa4
{ 8.cxd5  Bxf1  and without castling rights, and having its king in the center, White has no chance of even dreaming of a better position. }
8... Be7 { The bishop takes up its usual 'comfortable' position on e7. } 9. Be2
dxc4
{ The usual reaction. Once White has lost a tempo on moving the Bf1, we take on c4. }
10. Bxc4 Bb7 { The simplest route to equality. } 11. O-O Nbd7
{ Black is ready for the ...c5 push.  11...Bxf3  is not a good idea because although after  12.gxf3  White`s king position is open, the problems on the light squares will prove very troublesome for Black. }
12. Ba6 Qc8
{ Very exact play! The black queen is going to be nicely placed on b7. } 13.
Bxb7 Qxb7
{ And our main idea of playing ...c5 next cannot be prevented, which means, in other words, total equality. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Bd2"]
[Black "6.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2
{ Welcome to the line with 5.Bd2. Obviously, the idea of the move is to play a3 at a good moment and if Black takes on c3, White recaptures with the bishop, maintaining a healthy pawn structure. However, this line is in general not dangerous for Black. }
5... d5
{ As in most of our recommended lines, we will focus our attention on the ...d5 move. We are fighting for control of the center and I believe that in most cases this will be the most solid approach. }
6. Nf3 b6 7. Rc1
{ White can try to avoid losing a tempo on moving with the Bf1, and Rc1 seems to be a useful move. }
7... Ba6
{ Black, in turn, can try to be clever and attempt to deprive White from castling. }
8. Qa4
{ 8.cxd5  Bxf1  and without castling rights, and having its king in the center, White has no chance of even dreaming of a better position. }
8... Be7 { The bishop takes up its usual 'comfortable' position on e7. } 9.
cxd5
{ 9.Ne5  c5=  If Black can safely play ...c5, why not do it?! A good rule of thumb in such positions. }
9... Bxf1 10. Kxf1 exd5 11. g3 Qc8
{ The direct  11...c5  is premature as White can quickly attack the center with Kg2 and Rhd1. }
12. Kg2 Qb7 13. Rhd1 Rc8
{ The final preparation before developing the knight to a6 and playing ...c5. The immediate  13...Na6  can be strongly met by  14.Ne5  ,  resulting in some problems around the c6-square. }
14. b4
{ This move prevents our idea of ...Na6 and ...c5, but it also has a drawback... the c4-square.  14.Be1  is already met by  14...Na6  with ...c5 next move. }
14... c6
{ With the idea of playing ...Nbd7, ...b5 and occupying the beautiful c4-square with ...Nb6-c4. }
