[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Bd2"]
[Black "6.Nf3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2
{ Welcome to the line with 5.Bd2. Obviously, the idea of the move is to play a3 at a good moment and if Black takes on c3, White recaptures with the bishop, maintaining a healthy pawn structure. However, this line is in general not dangerous for Black. }
5... d5
{ As in most of our recommended lines, we will focus our attention on the ...d5 move. We are fighting for control of the center and I believe that in most cases this will be the most solid approach. }
6. Nf3 b6 7. cxd5 exd5
{ Now  8.Bd3  transposes to the main line of 5. Bd3, so please refer to the chapter with 5. Bd3. }
8. Rc1 { If we want to play the ...Ba6-system, we should play ...Re8. } 8...
Re8
{ This is a useful waiting move. Both sides are delaying the development of their light-squared bishops. Black wants to play ...Ba6 only after the f1-bishop has moved. }
9. Ne5
{ German GM and theoretician Matthias Bluebaum's favorite move. White still tries to avoid transposing to the main line with  9.Bd3  Ba6  and additionally the text move also sets a trap, as the tempting @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/p1p2ppp/1p3n2/3pN3/1b1P4/2N1P3/PP1B1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...c5  runs into the unpleasant  10.Bb5  . }
9... Bb7
{ White has reached what it wants - Black played the bishop to b7. But the knight on e5 is not perfectly placed and we are going to see why... }
10. Bb5
{ This one is the most natural move to me, although it has not yet been tried. }
10... c6 11. Bd3 Nfd7
{ A very interesting idea, trying to make use of the extra ...c6 move. White has the chance to force a draw now with  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Qh5  and deliver a perpetual check on the squares h5 and f7, but having the white pieces, no one should aim to force a draw in just 12 moves! Such a finish counts as a moral and theoretical victory for Black. }
12. f4 Qh4+ 13. g3 Qh3
{ Black successfully creates a lot of holes on the light squares in White's camp and the upcoming play is an attempt to cash in on this new factor. }
14. Qf3 Bxc3
{ Here, the engines are a big help to us. Black's main idea is to play on the light squares, especially going for the e4-square. }
15. Bxc3 Ba6
{ Strategic play designed to gain control of the e4 square for the black knight. }
16. Bb1 Nf6
{ And White cannot castle short because of the a6-bishop scything across the diagonal. }
*

