{ Now  8.Bd3  transposes to the main line of 5. Bd3, so please refer to the chapter with 5. Bd3. }
8. Rc1 { If we want to play the ...Ba6-system, we should play ...Re8. } 8...
Re8
{ This is a useful waiting move. Both sides are delaying the development of their light-squared bishops. Black wants to play ...Ba6 only after the f1-bishop has moved. }
9. Ne5
{ German GM and theoretician Matthias Bluebaum's favorite move. White still tries to avoid transposing to the main line with  9.Bd3  Ba6  and additionally the text move also sets a trap, as the tempting @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/p1p2ppp/1p3n2/3pN3/1b1P4/2N1P3/PP1B1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...c5  runs into the unpleasant  10.Bb5  . }
9... Bb7
{ White has reached what it wants - Black played the bishop to b7. But the knight on e5 is not perfectly placed and we are going to see why... }
10. Bd3 Nbd7
{ Here we choose ... Nbd7 because we did not play the ...c6 move, so our b7-bishop is already more free. }
11. f4
{ White has to keep the knight on e5, but the downside of this move is the usual weakening of the e4-square, as we have just witnessed. }
11... Bxc3
{ In the Bluebaum game, Black continued with ...Bf8, but I believe our main line is more solid. }
12. Bxc3 { 12.bxc3  is met by  12...Ne4  with the idea of ...f6. } 12... a5
{ Again, we are trying to exchange the Bb7 for the Bd3: in case we achieve it, the e4-square will be ours! }
13. Qe2
{ Trying to prevent ...Ba6.  13.O-O  is met by  13...Ba6  when the bishops are going to be exchanged, the e4-square will belong to Black... mission accomplished! }
13... Ne4
{ With comfortable play for Black. Our idea could be to play ...f6 next, chasing the annoying knight away from e5. }
