[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Bd2"]
[Black "6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2
{ Welcome to the line with 5.Bd2. Obviously, the idea of the move is to play a3 at a good moment and if Black takes on c3, White recaptures with the bishop, maintaining a healthy pawn structure. However, this line is in general not dangerous for Black. }
5... d5
{ As in most of our recommended lines, we will focus our attention on the ...d5 move. We are fighting for control of the center and I believe that in most cases this will be the most solid approach. }
6. a3
{ 6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bd3  Re8  8.Nge2  b6  transposes to the 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 variation. }
6... Be7
{ 6...Bxc3  7.Bxc3  Ne4  is also possible, but @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/P1N1P3/1P1B1PPP/R2QKBNR b KQ - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  seems to be more flexible. Black is trying to play a standard Queen's Gambit position with a misplaced Bd2, which should normally be on g5 or f4. }
7. Nf3 b6
{ The usual way of developing the c8-bishop. We still have both options open - to play ...Ba6 or ...Bb7 - and it also helps to prepare the thrust ...c5 at some moment, laying down a strong central challenge. }
8. cxd5
{ We should be always ready for the move  8.cxd5  , and in a lot of different circumstances. }
8... exd5
{ Do not be tempted by the recapture  8...Nxd5?!  as usually it is just a positional mistake. We need our pawn on d5.   The reason why we take 8... exd5 does not have much to do with the development in b7 of the bishop, but rather with the struggle for the center. Usually, the structures that arise after 8...Nxd5 are somewhat better for White, who might proceed with the Bd3-Qc2-Rac1 maneuver or with the e4-push. In either case, Black usually has to suffer to achieve a draw. Understanding exactly why is not so simple and will always depend on special circumstances. What is important for us to remember is that in most cases we take ...exd5 and then play the move ...c5. }
9. Bd3 c5
{ I believe Black should be doing totally OK once ...c5 is on the board. } 10.
O-O Bb7
{ Leads to typical positions where the Bd2 is misplaced. The usual set-up for Black is ...Nbd7/ ...Rc8/ ...Re8 and then figuring out the procedure depending on what White does. Being very solid in the center secures Black nice play. }
*

