{ The usual way of developing the c8-bishop. We still have both options open - to play ...Ba6 or ...Bb7 - and it also helps to prepare the thrust ...c5 at some moment, laying down a strong central challenge. }
8. Bd3 dxc4
{ It's also possible to play  8...Bb7  9.cxd5  exd5  10.O-O  c5  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Rc1  Nbd7  with a typical middlegame, in which the d2-bishop is completely misplaced. }
9. Bxc4
{ Now that we have won 'half a tempo' because of White`s Bd3-Bxc4, we can continue with our normal development. }
9... Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7
{ Followed by ...Rc8 and ...c5. Once again we have a typical position where the Bd2 is clearly not in great shape, so Black should have no problems claiming equality.Conclusion: as we have seen, by playing natural moves Black reaches a normally playable position that makes the entire 5.Bd2 line non-critical. There is not much to remember, and a sound positional understanding should be sufficient to achieve an even game from the opening. }
