[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Nge2 without 8.e4"]
[Black "6.g3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2
{ Welcome to the Reshevsky System, which received huge attention after Carlsen defeated Anand with it in only 29 moves at the Tal Memorial tournament in Moscow, 2013. }
5... c6
{ Our choice here is an interesting 'sideline' which I consider to be an attractive alternative to the main lines with 5...d5.  The main idea for Black is to bring the bishop to c7 - and its position on c7 is actually a great one! At first view, it will look a bit scary, and visually better for White, but in fact, the position is very dynamic and it is anything other than easy to prove an advantage. Please do not make the mistake of thinking that the move   5...c6  is made just to play ...d5 sometime soon, and then on White's cxd5 to answer ...cxd5 - this is not the point of our line at all. }
6. g3 { This is not dangerous and Black equalizes with ease. } 6... d5 7. a3
Bd6
{ Of course, we do not take on c3 - this is the point. We choose ...Bd6 here instead of ... Ba5 simply because the rather slow move g3 was played by White, and therefore we can go directly for the ... e5 push. }
8. b3
{ There are many alternatives for White, but all of them seem to be OK for Black. This is just a logical, exemplary line so we can better see the main point of Black's play. }
8... e5 { With a perfect position for Black. } 9. cxd5
{ 9.Bg2  e4  looks nice for Black. } 9... cxd5 10. dxe5 Bxe5
{ Once again, we have an isolated pawn on d5, but as in many cases we get great play for it! }
11. Bg2 Nc6 { White needs to be careful of the ...d4 push coming next. } 12.
Bb2 Bg4
{ And once again ...d4 is a threat. Having fully-developed and active pieces, Black naturally enjoys great play. }
