[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Nge2 without 8.e4"]
[Black "6.Ng3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2
{ Welcome to the Reshevsky System, which received huge attention after Carlsen defeated Anand with it in only 29 moves at the Tal Memorial tournament in Moscow, 2013. }
5... c6
{ Our choice here is an interesting 'sideline' which I consider to be an attractive alternative to the main lines with 5...d5.  The main idea for Black is to bring the bishop to c7 - and its position on c7 is actually a great one! At first view, it will look a bit scary, and visually better for White, but in fact, the position is very dynamic and it is anything other than easy to prove an advantage. Please do not make the mistake of thinking that the move   5...c6  is made just to play ...d5 sometime soon, and then on White's cxd5 to answer ...cxd5 - this is not the point of our line at all. }
6. Ng3 { Here as well Black is out of any opening danger. } 6... d5 7. Bd3
{ Now, as usual, we win the @@StartBracket@@very useful!@@EndBracket@@ 'half a tempo'. }
7... dxc4 { This seems to be an improvement on  7...Nbd7  . } 8. Bxc4 c5
{ The usual one-two combo - ... dxc4 and ...c5 - hitting directly at White's center. }
9. O-O cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6
{ The black knight is usually better-placed on c6 because of the direct pressure it exerts on the d4-pawn. I would say, in general terms, that I do not believe White has any chance of playing for an advantage in positions with an 'isolated pawn' where he has a knight on g3. The knight simply doesn't affect the appropriate squares. }
11. Be3 e5 { 11...Nd5  is a calmer way that also achieves equality. } 12. dxe5
{ 12.d5  Na5  wins a pawn. } 12... Ng4
{ Now Black is even fighting for the initiative! } 13. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ In this endgame, Black is doing perfectly fine. All the black pieces are active and the pawn on e5 cannot be saved. }
14. e6 Bxe6 15. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Is there anything more to wish for other than an equal endgame straight from the opening as Black?! }
