{ Welcome to the Reshevsky System, which received huge attention after Carlsen defeated Anand with it in only 29 moves at the Tal Memorial tournament in Moscow, 2013. }
5... c6
{ Our choice here is an interesting 'sideline' which I consider to be an attractive alternative to the main lines with 5...d5.  The main idea for Black is to bring the bishop to c7 - and its position on c7 is actually a great one! At first view, it will look a bit scary, and visually better for White, but in fact, the position is very dynamic and it is anything other than easy to prove an advantage. Please do not make the mistake of thinking that the move   5...c6  is made just to play ...d5 sometime soon, and then on White's cxd5 to answer ...cxd5 - this is not the point of our line at all. }
6. a3 Ba5 7. Ng3 d5
{ Although the version with the moves a3 and ... Ba5 are included is better for White than the alternative without these moves, I still believe that with the knight on g3, and ...d5 having been played, Black should feel comfortable. }
8. cxd5 exd5
{ 8...cxd5  with the idea of playing ... Nc6, ...Bc7 and ...e5 also equalizes easily, but this recapture keeps much more winning chances. }
9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Nbd7
{ As you can see, the white bishop is still on c1 - the big question is whether or not White can find a use for it?! }
11. f3 Nf8
{ 11...c5  is, as we know, very principled in this structure after White plays f3. But how dangerous is the e4 push really? We are going to see over the next few moves... }
12. Bc2
{ White tries to execute the e4-break, but Black is perfectly prepared to meet it. }
12... Bc7 { The bishop takes up its great position on c7. } 13. e4
{ The e4-push is potentially dangerous, but rarely works. } 13... dxe4 14. fxe4
Ng4
{ And ...Qh4 was coming in the game Chan-Ganguly, Canberra 2016. Black has a clear advantage, and White cannot solve the tactical problems; we should not forget that ...Bb6 is also on its way! }
