[White "10) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Nge2 without 8.e4"]
[Black "6.a3 with 7.b4 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2
{ Welcome to the Reshevsky System, which received huge attention after Carlsen defeated Anand with it in only 29 moves at the Tal Memorial tournament in Moscow, 2013. }
5... c6
{ Our choice here is an interesting 'sideline' which I consider to be an attractive alternative to the main lines with 5...d5.  The main idea for Black is to bring the bishop to c7 - and its position on c7 is actually a great one! At first view, it will look a bit scary, and visually better for White, but in fact, the position is very dynamic and it is anything other than easy to prove an advantage. Please do not make the mistake of thinking that the move   5...c6  is made just to play ...d5 sometime soon, and then on White's cxd5 to answer ...cxd5 - this is not the point of our line at all. }
6. a3 Ba5 7. b4 { The most natural move for White. } 7... Bc7
{ Finally, we have reached the most critical position of the entire line. } 8.
Ng3
{ The main and most dangerous move is  8.e4  which is analyzed in the next chapter.   8.Bb2  d5  9.Ng3  Nbd7  transposes to 8. Ng3 d5 9. Bb2 }
8... d5 9. Bb2 Nbd7 { We are ready for the ...e5 thrust. } 10. f4
{ White's usual try. } 10... a5
{ 10...Nb6  11.c5  Nc4  also leads to interesting positions. } 11. c5 b6
{ Followed by the exchange of the light-squared bishops on a6. However,  11...e5  is still very interesting and actually, the computer supports the sacrifice, for example  12.fxe5  Nxe5  13.dxe5  Ng4! }
12. Be2 Ba6
{ Once we have managed to exchange the Bc8 vs the Bf1, Black is doing fine. }
13. Bxa6 Rxa6 14. O-O axb4
{ Is an example of what can happen in such structures. } 15. axb4 Rxa1 16. Qxa1
bxc5 17. bxc5 Ng4 { A beautiful attack on the e3-pawn, before playing ...Qa8. }
18. Rf3
{ 18.Re1  would allow  18...Nxh2  and Black wins a pawn due to ...Qh4+ and ...Qxg3. }
18... Qa8
{ If anybody is better here, it should be Black. The white rook on f3 is out of the game and Black is active on the a- and b- files. }
