8... d5 9. Bb2 Nbd7 { We are ready for the ...e5 thrust. } 10. Bd3
{ 10.cxd5  exd5  makes little sense for White with his bishop on b2. } 10... e5
{ Finally! } 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. cxd5 Nxd5
{ There is a massive exchange in the center, but the white knight remains in a passive position on g3. }
13. Be2 Nb6
{ Black can even try to exert some pressure.  13...Nxc3  14.Bxc3  Qe7  is just equal. }
14. Qc2 Nec4 { Trying to reach a position with the bishop pair. } 15. Bc1 a5
{ This looks dangerous for White, but in reality the position is more or less equal. }
16. Rb1 axb4 17. axb4 Be6
{ Black's pieces are out, while White will castle next - both sides have a solid position.    Conclusion: the whole line with 8. Ng3 is not really putting Black on the limit. With easy moves as 8... d5 and with the idea of ...dxc4 and ...e5 next we are getting an excellent play. In very many cases the Ng3 is misplaced. A quick recheck of the 8. Ng3 should be enough to know more or less the direction where to play next. There is no need to remember the moves by hard-to-play, relying on 'feel' should be perfectly OK. }
