{ The most ambitious and dangerously straightforward plan. White is trying to gain as much space as possible and Black has to react very precisely just to avoid complete suffocation. However, pawns don't move backwards, and if Black succeeds in undermining the opponent's center, then the initiative can easily be regained. }
8... d5 { Black has to act and this central counter is the right way. } 9. Bg5
h6 { It is important to first include this pawn move. } 10. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ Usually, once White gives away the dark-squared bishop, Black's position is fine. }
11. e5 Qe7
{ It is hard for White to keep the position closed @@StartBracket@@the usual plan when facing the bishop pair@@EndBracket@@. }
12. c5 f6
{ And Black opens the center. It is going to be hard for White to develop his pieces to normal positions, whereas Black always has the standard plan of playing ...a5/ ...b6, as well as the opening of the f-file. }
