18. Bb5 Bxd2+ 19. Qxd2 { And now we need to find a really hard move... } 19...
Ndb8
{ It is never easy to play backward moves, particularly when being a pawn down. In our particular case, however, it is the right choice. }
20. cxb6 Qxb6 21. Nac3 Rd8
{ And we are just in time to get back the pawn on d4 or e5. The position is equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Nge2 with 8.e4"]
[Black "8.e4 with 9.e5 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2 c6 6. a3 Ba5 7. b4 Bc7 8. e4
{ The most ambitious and dangerously straightforward plan. White is trying to gain as much space as possible and Black has to react very precisely just to avoid complete suffocation. However, pawns don't move backwards, and if Black succeeds in undermining the opponent's center, then the initiative can easily be regained. }
8... d5 { Black has to act and this central counter is the right way. } 9. e5
{ Other continuations are not that dangerous, for example  9.Ng3  e5!  and the center opens in Black's favor. }
9... Nfd7
{ This looks a bit ugly, but it works. First of all, Black is ready to move this knight further to b6 and c4, and if White prevents it with c4-c5 then the typical knight sacrifice on e5 is very interesting in many cases. }
10. Nf4
{ A logical response. White prevents ...f7-f6 but Black has another @@StartBracket@@not obvious at all@@EndBracket@@ way to undermine the opponent's center. }
10... a5
{ We need to activate the rook on a8 to fight against White's central pawns. }
11. Rb1 { 11.b5  c5!  and Black successfully undermines the e5-pawn. } 11...
axb4 12. axb4
{ On first sight, White's position looks preferable, but here comes the key move of the whole line... }
12... c5
{ This is the most important tactical resource, one that justifies the whole setup. Without this move, White would just be comfortably better. }
13. bxc5
{ This capture is a must.  13.dxc5  it doesn't make sense for White to give away the e5-pawn.  13...dxc4  14.Bxc4  Nxe5  is just a nice position for Black. }
13... Ba5 14. Bb2 { Doesn't work. } 14... Nxc5 { Yet another tactical blow! }
15. dxc5 d4 { And the white knight is pinned by the bishop on a5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3 and 5.Nge2 with 8.e4"]
[Black "8.e4 with 9.e5 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2 c6 6. a3 Ba5 7. b4 Bc7 8. e4
{ The most ambitious and dangerously straightforward plan. White is trying to gain as much space as possible and Black has to react very precisely just to avoid complete suffocation. However, pawns don't move backwards, and if Black succeeds in undermining the opponent's center, then the initiative can easily be regained. }
8... d5 { Black has to act and this central counter is the right way. } 9. e5
{ Other continuations are not that dangerous, for example  9.Ng3  e5!  and the center opens in Black's favor. }
9... Nfd7
{ This looks a bit ugly, but it works. First of all, Black is ready to move this knight further to b6 and c4, and if White prevents it with c4-c5 then the typical knight sacrifice on e5 is very interesting in many cases. }
10. Nf4
{ A logical response. White prevents ...f7-f6 but Black has another @@StartBracket@@not obvious at all@@EndBracket@@ way to undermine the opponent's center. }
10... a5
{ We need to activate the rook on a8 to fight against White's central pawns. }
11. Rb1 { 11.b5  c5!  and Black successfully undermines the e5-pawn. } 11...
axb4 12. axb4
{ On first sight, White's position looks preferable, but here comes the key move of the whole line... }
12... c5
{ This is the most important tactical resource, one that justifies the whole setup. Without this move, White would just be comfortably better. }
13. bxc5
{ This capture is a must.  13.dxc5  it doesn't make sense for White to give away the e5-pawn.  13...dxc4  14.Bxc4  Nxe5  is just a nice position for Black. }
13... Ba5 14. Bd2 dxc4 { 14...Nc6  is also strong. } 15. Bxc4 Nxe5
{ It is quite amazing how often the move ...Nxe5 works! } 16. dxe5 Qd4
{ With a double attack on the c4-bishop and the c3-knight. Black wins back the sacrificed piece and keeps a small edge. }
17. Qb3 Bxc3 { Still! Beautiful to the very end. } 18. Bxc3
{ 18.Qxc3?  Qe4+!  is the key, with White losing the b1-rook. } 18... Qxf4 19.
O-O Bd7
{ Most probably the game is going to end in a draw, but one thing is clear - Black for sure doesn't experience any difficulties here. ...Bc6 with ...Nd7 could be the next moves, giving a very nice position with which to continue the game.   What conclusion can we draw about the 5. Nge2 c6!? line: It is a very interesting try, even if the line is not that popular. This might actually be a bonus, as the opponent might be not well-enough prepared and take a too ambitious approach, attempting to refute the line, and quickly get into trouble in all the tactical complications we have just seen and, hopefully, learned! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.cxd5"]
[Black "8.Bd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3
{ Welcome to the absolute mainline of the 4.e3 Nimzo. The game is going to be mostly positional and we will need to understand the basic ideas to be able playing the opening well. }
5... d5 6. cxd5
{ We will start with the  6.cxd5  line and then continue with the other 3 main continuations:  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  , and  6.a3 }
6... exd5
{ As in most of the lines I advocate, we recapture on d5 with ...exd5. Personally, I have never been afraid of White's cxd5 - in these structures I have always had great confidence in Black's position. }
7. Ne2 Re8
{ ...Re8 is a useful move in many scenarios: it gives Black the option of playing ...Bf8, and places extra pressure on White's center in case they have any f3-e4 ideas. }
8. Bd2
{ This is a recently popular option with the prophylactic purpose of avoiding the line  8.O-O  Bd6  9.Bd2  and ...b6. The point of the move is to save a tempo by delaying castling, and playing the useful Rc1 instead. This means that White will have Nb5 in the case of the ...Bd6, ...b6 plan. The drawback of the move is that after  8.O-O  Bd6  , White has many other options besides the  9.Bd2  move. }
8... b6
{ We are preparing the plan with ...c5 and still keeping the twin options of playing ...Bd6 and ...Bf8 open. }
9. Rc1 { Now it is clear we can no longer play ...Bd6 because of Nb5. } 9...
Bf8 10. O-O c5
{ Black successfully executes the ... c5 plan. The key point of the plan is to use the misplaced d2-bishop. Ideally, White should have the pawn on b3 and the bishop on b2. In that case, it could build very strong pressure against Black's center. With the Bd2 being 'imperfectly placed', Black has comfortable play. }
11. dxc5 bxc5
{ Of course, we take back on c5 with the pawn to avoid isolated pawn structures, which might bring us long-suffering in a slightly worse position. }
12. Na4 c4
{ 12...Nbd7  also looks perfectly playable, but in this given moment, thanks to the misplacement of the Na4, advancing the center looks strong as well because we can develop our b8-knight to a more active square. }
13. Bb1 Nc6 { The knight on c6 is better placed than if it was on d7. } 14. Bc3
{ Undermining with  14.b3  allows ... Ba3 and the c1-rook has some problems. }
14... Rb8 { The immediate  14...Ne4  is also good. } 15. Nf4 d4
{ We are going to witness this ...d4 push idea in a few different scenarios. We should remember this pawn sacrifice! }
16. Bxd4 { This is just a mistake by White and allows Black great play. } 16...
Nxd4 17. Qxd4 Qxd4 18. exd4
{ We are in an endgame a pawn down, but for the pawn we do have the bishop pair, plus White's knights are really badly-placed. }
18... g5 19. Nh3 Rb4
{ The white knight on h3 and its colleague on a4 are both clearly misplaced. }
20. b3 cxb3 21. axb3 h6
{ Black is going to win the b3- or d4-pawns, leaving them with a bishop pair for nothing. This endgame is simply much better for Black. }
*

