[White "12) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.cxd5"]
[Black "8.O-O Bd6 9.f3 with 10.Nb5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3
{ Welcome to the absolute mainline of the 4.e3 Nimzo. The game is going to be mostly positional and we will need to understand the basic ideas to be able playing the opening well. }
5... d5 6. cxd5
{ We will start with the  6.cxd5  line and then continue with the other 3 main continuations:  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  , and  6.a3 }
6... exd5
{ As in most of the lines I advocate, we recapture on d5 with ...exd5. Personally, I have never been afraid of White's cxd5 - in these structures I have always had great confidence in Black's position. }
7. Ne2 Re8
{ ...Re8 is a useful move in many scenarios: it gives Black the option of playing ...Bf8, and places extra pressure on White's center in case they have any f3-e4 ideas. }
8. O-O Bd6
{ 8...b6  is possible as well, but it is a different line. Another important thing to remember is that the sacrifice Bxh2+ followed by ... Ng4 doesn't work in most cases! }
9. f3 c5
{ On White's f3 we usually answer with ...c5 - that's the key point to remember. Also, it is nice that we are still having the b8-knight at home rather than on d7, because the next move could be ...Nc6 with pressure on White's center. }
10. Nb5 Bf8 { Never give up the dark-squared bishop for no good reason! } 11.
dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nbd4
{ Yes, we do have an isolated pawn, but White has played the move f3 already. These structures should be evaluated as equal because of the weak pawn on e3. }
12... Nc6 { The backward e3-pawn is even weaker the the isolated pawn on d5. }
13. Bd2 Qb6
{ And Black was already slightly better in the game Gelfand-Carlsen, Moscow 2007. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.cxd5"]
[Black "8.O-O Bd6 9.f3 with 10.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3
{ Welcome to the absolute mainline of the 4.e3 Nimzo. The game is going to be mostly positional and we will need to understand the basic ideas to be able playing the opening well. }
5... d5 6. cxd5
{ We will start with the  6.cxd5  line and then continue with the other 3 main continuations:  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  , and  6.a3 }
6... exd5
{ As in most of the lines I advocate, we recapture on d5 with ...exd5. Personally, I have never been afraid of White's cxd5 - in these structures I have always had great confidence in Black's position. }
7. Ne2 Re8
{ ...Re8 is a useful move in many scenarios: it gives Black the option of playing ...Bf8, and places extra pressure on White's center in case they have any f3-e4 ideas. }
8. O-O Bd6
{ 8...b6  is possible as well, but it is a different line. Another important thing to remember is that the sacrifice Bxh2+ followed by ... Ng4 doesn't work in most cases! }
9. f3 c5
{ On White's f3 we usually answer with ...c5 - that's the key point to remember. Also, it is nice that we are still having the b8-knight at home rather than on d7, because the next move could be ...Nc6 with pressure on White's center. }
10. a3 Nc6 11. Rf2
{ This plan, connected to g2-g4, is a common idea in the structure. However, in this situation, Black is perfectly prepared to create his counterplay on the queenside. }
11... a6 12. Bc2 { Avoiding Black from playing ... c4 with tempo. } 12... b5
{ We should waste no time. } 13. g4 Rb8
{ The final preparation for the ...b4-push. The direct  13...b4  is also fine, but White does have the option of  14.Ba4  . }
14. g5 Nd7 15. dxc5 Bxc5
{ We are sacrificing the pawn on d5, but getting great compensation for it! }
16. Nxd5 Nde5
{ With huge compensation. White is completely behind in development and is weakened in all parts of the board. }
