{ Is also good for Black! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.cxd5"]
[Black "8.O-O Bd6 9.a3 with 10.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3
{ Welcome to the absolute mainline of the 4.e3 Nimzo. The game is going to be mostly positional and we will need to understand the basic ideas to be able playing the opening well. }
5... d5 6. cxd5
{ We will start with the  6.cxd5  line and then continue with the other 3 main continuations:  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  , and  6.a3 }
6... exd5
{ As in most of the lines I advocate, we recapture on d5 with ...exd5. Personally, I have never been afraid of White's cxd5 - in these structures I have always had great confidence in Black's position. }
7. Ne2 Re8
{ ...Re8 is a useful move in many scenarios: it gives Black the option of playing ...Bf8, and places extra pressure on White's center in case they have any f3-e4 ideas. }
8. O-O Bd6
{ 8...b6  is possible as well, but it is a different line. Another important thing to remember is that the sacrifice Bxh2+ followed by ... Ng4 doesn't work in most cases! }
9. a3
{ White is preparing to play b4 in case of our ...b6, in order to prevent the ...c5 move. }
9... c6 { 9...Nbd7  also makes sense, remaining flexible on the queenside. }
10. Qc2
{ Played by Kasparov once. On  10.b4  , Black has a great answer with  10...b5  .  The idea is to fix the b4-weakness, which is going to be undermined by ...a5! Another point is to bring our knight to the c4-square via d7-b6. }
10... b6
{ With two ideas: either to push ...c5, or to exchange the bishops with ...Ba6! }
11. b4 Ba6
{ And we manage to exchange the light-squared bishops, which is usually a good thing for Black. }
12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. b5
{ White is trying to break the pawn structure, but with the light-squared bishops off the board, this plan is no longer dangerous. }
13... cxb5 14. Nxb5 Bf8
{ As usual, we should preserve our dark-squared bishop. We have a typical position, where Black might go ...Qd7, ...Rec8 and ...Nc7, getting rid of the knight on b5. The position is playable for both colors, and objectively I do not see any problems for Black. }
*

