12. f5 Nc6 { Trying to force White to play dxc5.  12...h6  is an alternative. }
13. dxc5 { 13.Bb5  Bd7  is also OK for Black. } 13... d4
{ This is probably even stronger than  13...bxc5  , which would allow  14.Bg5  . }
14. Na4 Ne5 { And once again we have great dynamic play as Black. } 15. Bb5 Bd7
{ Complex positions are great when we want to play for the full point. } 16.
Bxd7 Nfxd7
{ Just like in the lines we saw before, the knight on a4 is really misplaced. }
17. cxb6 axb6 { ...b5 is now a dangerous threat. } 18. b3 Qf6
{ With strong compensation for Black, to say the least. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.cxd5"]
[Black "8.O-O Bd6 9.Bd2 with 10.Nf4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3
{ Welcome to the absolute mainline of the 4.e3 Nimzo. The game is going to be mostly positional and we will need to understand the basic ideas to be able playing the opening well. }
5... d5 6. cxd5
{ We will start with the  6.cxd5  line and then continue with the other 3 main continuations:  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  , and  6.a3 }
6... exd5
{ As in most of the lines I advocate, we recapture on d5 with ...exd5. Personally, I have never been afraid of White's cxd5 - in these structures I have always had great confidence in Black's position. }
7. Ne2 Re8
{ ...Re8 is a useful move in many scenarios: it gives Black the option of playing ...Bf8, and places extra pressure on White's center in case they have any f3-e4 ideas. }
8. O-O Bd6
{ 8...b6  is possible as well, but it is a different line. Another important thing to remember is that the sacrifice Bxh2+ followed by ... Ng4 doesn't work in most cases! }
9. Bd2 b6
{ As usual, we want to play ...c5 and ...Ba6. The sacrificial attack with  9...Bxh2  10.Kxh2  Ng4  doesn't work due to  11.Kg3!  and White is winning. }
10. Nf4
{ Just as in the 9.Nf4 main line, I like changing the structure by taking the knight on f4. }
10... Bxf4 11. exf4 c5
{ But we have to be quick now because if White manages to stabilize, their position might be a little better. }
12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Re1 { 13.f5  is met by the usual  13...h6  . } 13... Ba6
{ I guess this could already be a moment where we could evaluate the position as 'nice' or 'pleasant' for Black, but let us check some more moves as an example of what might happen... }
14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Nxd5
{ Is a nice tactical resource but gives no edge to White. } 15... Nxd5 16. Qh5
{ The h7-pawn and d5-knight are both hanging. } 16... Nf6 17. Qf3
{ That's White's big idea; the rook on a8 cannot be protected. } 17... Bxd3 18.
Qxa8 Nc6 { 2 pieces vs rook+pawn usually leads to equal play in the endgame. }
19. Qxe8+ Nxe8
{ After all the complications, we have reached an equal endgame. } *

