[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nge2"]
[Black "6.Nge2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Ne2
{ I would not call this a dangerous line for Black, especially as we have a direct line of play against it. }
6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 { Going directly for White's centre. } 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3
{ 9.bxc3  should be the most challenging line after 6. Nge2, however, transposes to the 6. a3 variation, which you can find in the 4. e3 with 6. a3 chapter. }
9... cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6
{ Usually, such positions are just equal. White's advantage lies in the bishop pair, but having an isolated pawn gives Black enough play for equality. }
11. Be3 b6
{ The light-squared bishop is going to take up a nice position on b7. } 12. O-O
Bb7
{ Black's ideas involve ...Ne7, ...Ned5 as well as the prophylactic move ...h6. }
13. Ba2
{ Now that the bishop has left c4, White is ready to play Qf3 @@StartBracket@@as ...Na5 no longer hits both pieces@@EndBracket@@. For this reason, it is considered to be better to start with  13...Ne7  now instead of  13...h6  . }
13... Ne7 14. Bg5
{ The only critical move, aiming to create some concrete threats connected with d5 before Black can reach the ideal places with the pieces. }
14... Nf5 { 14...Ng6  is also good. } 15. d5
{ One of the ideas of playing with an isolated pawn is to push it through, and this is exactly what White is trying to do. }
15... exd5 16. Qd3 d4 { The easiest way to equalize. } 17. Qxf5 dxc3 18. bxc3
Qc8
{ Getting rid of the pin and offering White to enter an endgame. Black has no problems at all. }
