[White "13) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nge2"]
[Black "6.Nge2 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Ne2
{ I would not call this a dangerous line for Black, especially as we have a direct line of play against it. }
6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 { Going directly for White's centre. } 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4
{ 9.Nxd4  is harmless, and Black can equalize easily with  9...Bd7  or  9...a6  . }
9... Nbd7
{ Black's idea is to develop with ...Nb6 followed by ...Bd7-c6, taking full control over the d5-square. The other main line is  9...Nc6  , which is equally fine. Now, White has to choose between various setups, but Black is doing well in any case. }
10. Bf4
{ It has been played by Nisipeanu, but it looks more active to put the bishop on g5. }
10... Nb6 11. Bb3 Bd7
{ Black is executing the main plan - to gain full control over the d5 square - plus getting the bishop from c8 to a much better square on c6. }
12. Qd3 Bc6 13. Bg5 Be7
{ This retreat with the bishop is quite typical. For us, all that matters is the d5-square! }
14. Nf4 Re8 { And we are ready to play ...Nfd5. } 15. Rad1 Nfd5 16. Bxe7 Rxe7
{ Because of the blockaded isolated pawn, Black was already better in the game Nisipeanu-Sargissian, Linares 2013. }
