[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nge2"]
[Black "6.Nge2 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Ne2
{ I would not call this a dangerous line for Black, especially as we have a direct line of play against it. }
6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 { Going directly for White's centre. } 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4
{ 9.Nxd4  is harmless, and Black can equalize easily with  9...Bd7  or  9...a6  . }
9... Nbd7
{ Black's idea is to develop with ...Nb6 followed by ...Bd7-c6, taking full control over the d5-square. The other main line is  9...Nc6  , which is equally fine. Now, White has to choose between various setups, but Black is doing well in any case. }
10. a3 Be7 { Of course, we don't take on c3 now. } 11. Bg5 Nb6 12. Ba2 Bd7
{ All as usual. Let's bring the bishop to c6 and play ...Nfd5 next. } 13. Qd3
Bc6 14. Rad1 Na4
{ An interesting move by Aronian, following the principles of trading the minor pieces, and using the fact that the b2-pawn is hanging. Of course, the standard moves  14...Nfd5  or  14...Re8  were also completely fine. }
15. Rd2 Nxc3
{ 16.bxc3  allows  16...Ne4!  and after exchanging on e7, the d2 rook and the a3 pawn are hanging. }
16. Nxc3 Qc7
{ Perhaps  16...Qa5  was preferable, not allowing White the mass simplification that leads to a draw. }
17. d5 { With this move, White escapes to the safety of a draw. } 17... Nxd5
{ The beginning of mass exchanges. } 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Bxe7
{ Almost all the pieces are getting exchanged. } 19... Qxe7 20. Bxd5 Rad8
{ And obviously the game does not last much longer. } 21. Qb3 Bxd5 22. Rxd5
Rxd5 23. Qxd5 Rd8
{ With a totally equal position.   Conclusion: This line seems not to be dangerous for Black, and indeed Black even has a lot of chances to take over the game and play for a slight advantage, especially if White does not force a draw immediately. I also have the feeling, that the positions can be easily understood; it is very safe and without many forced lines which is a big bonus - in case we forget something, it does not matter too much! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.a3"]
[Black "9.Ne2 with 10.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3
{ White forces Black to take on c3. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
{ We are faced with an interesting position: White has the bishop pair which is clearly a plus and theoretically - if White manages to develop comfortably - a small, long-term advantage. On the other hand, White lost a tempo on playing a3 and now Black has some development advantage.   The question is: does Black have enough time to create some play, or will White will be able to fulfill the dreams of a small but long-term bishop pair advantage. In my opinion, Black has enough resources to be doing fine. }
7... dxc4
{ Once the bishop has moved from f1, we have the option of winning a 'half a tempo' - a common motif in many NimzoIndian @@StartBracket@@and Queen's Gambit@@EndBracket@@ variations. }
8. Bxc4 c5
{ We have reached the main position of our line. White has 4 different continuations: the two main lines are  9.Nf3  and  9.Ne2  , but the two alternatives,  9.Bb2  and  9.Bd3  , are also serious options and have been played by top players. }
9. Ne2
{ This position might also arise from the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2NBP3/PP3PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQ d6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nge2  dxc4  7.Bxc4  c5  8.a3  Bxc3  9.bxc3  move order. }
9... Qc7 { Asking the bishop to decide which diagonal it wants to hold. } 10.
Bd3 Nc6
{ Black wants to play ...e5, making use of the bishop sitting on d3 as White cannot profitably answer with d5. }
11. f4
{ This is an attempt to prevent ...e5, but Black can quickly organize his play against the e4-square. }
11... b6 12. O-O Bb7
{ We are fully developed, which is never a bad thing. Next, we want to start our play on the light squares. }
13. e4
{ There have been several games played from this position, but Black's strongest move has not yet been played... }
13... Ne7 { Directly attacking the e4-pawn. } 14. Ng3
{ White wants to play this, but cannot protect the pawn on e4. } 14... cxd4
{ When Black has a tactical resource. } 15. cxd4 Qc3
{ The a1-rook and the pawn on d4 are both hanging, so White loses material. }
16. Be3
{ Certainly not the best move for White, but a great example allowing us to show the key line: }
16... Ba6
{ A fantastic move! White cannot defend the bishop on d3, so the e3-bishop is lost and, with it, the entire white position. }
