9. Ne2
{ This position might also arise from the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2NBP3/PP3PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQ d6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nge2  dxc4  7.Bxc4  c5  8.a3  Bxc3  9.bxc3  move order. }
9... Qc7 { Asking the bishop to decide which diagonal it wants to hold. } 10.
Ba2 b6
{ Now that ...e5 is not of option in view of d5, Black should develop his bishop on a6. }
11. O-O Ba6
{ Black's idea is simple: we want to play ...Nc6, ...Rac8, ... Rfd8, etc. } 12.
Bb2 { A very popular move recently, played twice by Carlsen. } 12... Nc6 13. c4
cxd4 14. exd4 { But now we go for the c4-pawn directly. } 14... Na5 15. d5
{ White's idea, as now Bxf6 is a threat. } 15... e5
{ Keeping the a1-h8 diagonal as closed as possible. } 16. Rc1
{ On  16.d6  Qc5  protects the e5-pawn. Now both captures are possible on c4, but I prefer taking with the knight. }
16... Nxc4
{ Previous games continued with  16...Bxc4  , but after  17.d6  Qc5  18.Ng3!  is an improvement, when White's compensation seems to be greater than in our line. }
17. Bxc4 Bxc4
{ This looks scary, but we always have the ...b5-push in case we need to protect our c4-bishop. }
18. d6 Qc5 19. Ng3 Qb5 { Attacking both f1 and b2. } 20. Re1 Qxb2 21. Rxc4 Rad8
{ Black is a pawn up but White has decent compensation for it. } 22. Nf5 Kh8
{ Evading the ...Ne7-c6 threat. After this more-or-less forced variation, White's activity should be only enough to hold the draw. }
