8. Bxc4 c5
{ We have reached the main position of our line. White has 4 different continuations: the two main lines are  9.Nf3  and  9.Ne2  , but the two alternatives,  9.Bb2  and  9.Bd3  , are also serious options and have been played by top players. }
9. Bd3
{ Removing the bishop from the vulnerable c4-square and not deciding yet about the development of the other two minor pieces. }
9... Qc7 { The queen is nicely placed on c7 in most cases. } 10. Bb2
{ 10.Ne2  would transpose to the 9.Ne2 line. } 10... Nc6
{ It is possible to play  10...b6  as well, but it looks like the most comfortable way to equalize is to destroy the center with ...e5! }
11. e4
{ An attempt to fight against ...e5 with d5, but delaying the development of the g1-knight runs into concrete problems. }
11... Qa5 { ...cxd4 is our threat. } 12. Qd2
{ And now the game Milov - Guido, Genova 2003 should be improved. } 12... b6
{ We will get our bishop out on a6. } 13. Ne2 Ba6
{ As we know, the exchange of the bishops favors Black. } 14. Bxa6 Qxa6 15. f3
Na5
{ And once again we have managed to get our knight to c4, with a nice position. }
