8. Bxc4 c5
{ We have reached the main position of our line. White has 4 different continuations: the two main lines are  9.Nf3  and  9.Ne2  , but the two alternatives,  9.Bb2  and  9.Bd3  , are also serious options and have been played by top players. }
9. Nf3 Qc7
{ Just as in the 9.Ne2 line, asking the bishop to choose a direction is the right decision. White has several options, but we have to point out that two logical-looking moves lose on the spot:  10.Qe2?  cxd4  11.cxd4  b5!  and ...Qc3+ next wins material, while  @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppq2ppp/4pn2/2p5/2BP4/P1P1PN2/5PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bd3?  cxd4  11.cxd4  Qc3+  also wins, as  12.Bd2  is not possible in view of the hanging d3-bishop. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppq2ppp/4pn2/2p5/2BP4/P1P1PN2/5PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qd3  doesn't make much sense as the queen will be misplaced and will walk into different tactical motifs after ...b6 and ...Bb7. }
10. Ba2
{ Is the chief alternative to the main line.  10.Qd3  , as we have already mentioned, makes no sense because after the simple  10...b6  11.O-O  Bb7  the position of the white queen is, at the very least, not perfect. }
10... b5
{ With the idea of playing ...Nbd7-b6 or just ...Bb7 is a very decent alternative to the main  10...b6  and  10...Nc6  moves,  played by the openings expert Peter Leko. }
11. O-O Bb7 12. Re1
{ Was played by the 4. e3 Nimzo expert, Korobov. However, Leko managed to get an advantage out of the opening in their encounter in 2019. }
12... Nbd7 13. Bb2 Nb6
{ The black knight takes up an excellent position and has options of going to a4 or c4 when needed. }
14. Qe2 Na4
{ Black already has a great position. Let's see how the game could continue. }
15. Ne5
{ 15.Qxb5  does not work for White because of  15...Bc6  16.Qe2  Rab8  and there is no good way to protect the bishop on  b2  .  17.Rab1  Be4-+  and Black is winning material. }
15... Rab8 16. Bb3 Nxb2 17. Qxb2 a5
{ And Black has a very good game on the queenside with some space advantage, while White's game is not yet on point. }
*

[Event "?"]
