[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nf3"]
[Black "7.cxd5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. cxd5 exd5 8. Ne5
{ This move order doesn't help White much, as Back can still play ...Ba6 and the c6-square cannot be used effectively. The O-O options will still transpose to the main lines. }
8... Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Nc6 { This is not dangerous for Black. } 10... Bxc3+
11. bxc3 Qd6
{ With a nice position for Black. In case of  12.Qa4  , the most precise answer is  12...Qd7! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nf3"]
[Black "7.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ba6 { Again, our standard plan. } 9. cxd5 exd5
{ 9...Bxd3  10.Qxd3  Qxd5  is the other completely playable main variation, but we are aiming for the same structures as we have in our main line. }
10. Bxa6
{ 10.O-O  still  transposes to our main lines, however, White can try to get in a quick c4 to achieve something different.   @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/p1p2ppp/bp3n2/3p4/3P4/P1PBPN2/5PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  Nc6  would lead us to the position that you can find in 7.O-O. }
10... Nxa6 11. Qd3 Qc8
{ A typical answer. Black defends the knight on a6 and supports the ...c5 plan. }
12. c4 c5
{ The best move. White's king is still on e1 and we should try to make use of this factor. }
13. O-O cxd4 14. cxd5 Nc5
{ The pawn on d4 can not be taken by the queen because of the fork with ...Nb3. }
15. Qc4 dxe3 16. Bxe3 Nce4
{ On  17.Qb3  or  17.Qd3  , the response  17...Rd8  is also going to win the d5-pawn. }
17. Rac1 Qxc4 { As in most endgames in the Nimzo, Black is doing fine here. }
18. Rxc4
{ And here the game Lenic-Palac, Bol 2013, can be improved upon by playing ...Rfd8. }
18... Rfd8 19. Rd1 b5 { When Black is soon going to win the d5-pawn. } *

