1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. a3
{ This cannot be a critical move. } 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3
{ Carlsen, in an online blitz game, played  10...Ne4  here, but Black should no longer allow the capture on a6, which now misplaces the knight on the edge of the board. Instead, Black should direct it towards the c4-square right away with ...Bxd3. }
10... Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nc6 { We want to play ...Na5 next. } 12. c4
{ This has to be played before White gets into positional trouble after ...Na5. }
12... Na5 13. Ne5 { 13.cxd5  Qxd5  followed by ...c5 is also equal. } 13... c5
14. Bb2 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Nc6
{ White cannot avoid ...cxd4, after which - if they don't want to stand worse with a perfectly-blockaded, isolated pawn on d4 - they should opt for mass simplification and a draw. }
16. Rfd1 cxd4 17. Bxd4 Nxd4 { We got the bishop! } 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Rxd4 Rfd8
{ And this endgame is obviously equal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nf3"]
[Black "7.O-O Ba6 8.cxd5 with 9.Ne5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5
{ This move has been played by Polish GMs, including Duda, however if Black reacts well it does not seem to be dangerous after all. }
9... Bxc3
{ A hard move to remember, because we are taking on c3 without being asked to by the usual a3 move. }
10. bxc3 c5
{ The position is very complex and white has a lot of different options. } 11.
f3 Re8
{ We are preparing to take on d3 and play ...Nbd7. Of course,  11...Re8  is not the only way to play on. }
12. Bb2 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 c4
{ Right now this is the best option, but sometimes we have to be careful with moves such as  13...c4  because in case White manages to push e4, Black's position will most probably be worse. }
14. Qc2 { 14.Qf5  is better, but after  14...Nbd7  Black is also fine. } 14...
Nbd7 { Quickly getting rid of the e5-knight. } 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Rae1 Qb7
{ We are preventing the e4-push. } 17. a4 Re6
{ Black has successfully prevented the e4-break and now starts to put pressure on the backward e3-pawn. Black already had a clear positional advantage in the game Peralta-Stefansson, Turin 2006, although here, surprisingly, the players agreed to a draw. }
*

