[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5
{ This move has been played by Polish GMs, including Duda, however if Black reacts well it does not seem to be dangerous after all. }
9... Bxc3
{ A hard move to remember, because we are taking on c3 without being asked to by the usual a3 move. }
10. bxc3 c5
{ The position is very complex and white has a lot of different options. } 11.
f3 Re8
{ We are preparing to take on d3 and play ...Nbd7. Of course,  11...Re8  is not the only way to play on. }
12. Re1 Bxd3 13. Nxd3
{ This is the consequent recapture after having played f3 and Re1. The idea is to play Nf2 and e4, like Portisch in his win over Panno in a similar position.   13.Qxd3  can be simply met by ... Nbd7 with equality, while the computer even suggests  13...Re6  followed by ... Nc6 with a tiny edge for Black. }
13... Qd6 14. Ba3 Nbd7 { And Black's position looks very solid. } 15. Nf2 Qc6
{ The queen is perfectly placed here, and it is going to be almost impossible for White to play e4. }
16. Qd3 Rad8
{ White has difficulties pushing through the e4 plan. On  17.Rad1  , Black can even go on an a2-pawn hunt with  17...Qa4  . }
17. e4
{ Let's see an example of what could happen in the event of White playing e4... }
17... dxe4 18. fxe4 Ne5 { The idea behind 16...Rad8. } 19. Qd1 cxd4 20. cxd4
Qc3 { And Black wins on the spot! } *

