7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5
{ This move has been played by Polish GMs, including Duda, however if Black reacts well it does not seem to be dangerous after all. }
9... Bxc3
{ A hard move to remember, because we are taking on c3 without being asked to by the usual a3 move. }
10. bxc3 c5
{ The position is very complex and white has a lot of different options. } 11.
f3 Re8
{ We are preparing to take on d3 and play ...Nbd7. Of course,  11...Re8  is not the only way to play on. }
12. Re1 Bxd3 13. Nxd3
{ This is the consequent recapture after having played f3 and Re1. The idea is to play Nf2 and e4, like Portisch in his win over Panno in a similar position.   13.Qxd3  can be simply met by ... Nbd7 with equality, while the computer even suggests  13...Re6  followed by ... Nc6 with a tiny edge for Black. }
13... Qd6 14. Nf2 Nc6
{ The fight is again around the e4 advance. White tries to achieve it, meanwhile Black tries to bring his pieces into the game by putting pressure on the central pawns to deter it. }
15. Ba3 Na5 { Trying to reach the c4-square. } 16. e4
{ Black has a fantastic line at his disposal. } 16... dxe4 17. fxe4 Nc4
{ A very nice move! Tatically, Black can make it work. } 18. e5 Qc6 19. exf6
{ 19.Bc1  Nd5  would be better for Black, with the dominating knights. } 19...
Rxe1+ { Best. } 20. Qxe1 Re8
{ Winning a tempo and bringing the rook into the game. Who cares about the a3-bishop! }
21. Qd1
{ In case of other queen moves, ...Ne3 is winning, with an inevitable checkmate on g2. }
21... Nxa3 22. fxg7 cxd4 { Black is planning something very tricky... } 23.
cxd4 Nc2 24. Rc1 { But whats next for Black? } 24... Qa4
{ Thanks to the beautiful back-rank checkmate idea and the ...Re1 threat, Black is going to win back the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@and later the g7-pawn@@EndBracket@@ with excellent winning chances. }
25. Rxc2 Qxc2 26. Qxc2 Re1# *

