{ A hard move to remember, because we are taking on c3 without being asked to by the usual a3 move. }
10. bxc3 c5
{ The position is very complex and white has a lot of different options. } 11.
a4
{ This position was reached in the game Caruana-Hou Yifan, Dortmund 2015, and Black could just take on d3. }
11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3
{ 12.Nxd3  Nbd7  followed by bringing the rooks to c8 and e8 is also equal. }
12... Re8 13. a5 Nbd7 { It is very important to exchange the knight on e5. }
14. Nxd7 Qxd7
{ It was also possible to take back with the knight on d7, to avoid the standard dxc5 and c4 idea, but in this current situation, Black seems to be OK as well. }
15. dxc5 bxc5 16. c4 dxc4
{ Very simple play by Black, and indeed it is enough to maintain equality. }
17. Qxc4 Ne4 18. Ra2 { 18.f3  can be answered by  18...Nd2! } 18... Rac8
{ Black has ideas of supporting his c-pawn by ...Nd6, sending away the queen, followed by pushing ...c4. After that, ...Nb5 will allow the black pawn to reach the c3-square. }
19. Rc2 Qc7 20. a6 Re6
{ The a6-pawn is going to fall in the long run and eventually we will probably reach a drawish rook endgame. }
