{ The three main moves now are  10.Qa4  ,  10.Qd3  and  10.Bd2  . In case of  10.Ne5  ,  we transpose to the 9.Ne5 lines. }
10. Qd3 Qc8
{ Once again we see this ...Qc8 move, defending the a6-knight and preparing to play ...c5. }
11. a3
{ With the idea of playing b4 if the bishop retreats, but Black can take on c3 and continue with ...c5. }
11... Bxc3 12. bxc3
{ 12.Qxc3  is probably a better move, but Black is completely fine anyway after ...c5. }
12... c5 13. Nd2 Re8
{ These structures we know already, and we also know that there is not much to be afraid of - we can continue to have confidence in Black's position! }
14. f3 Qb7 15. Bb2 c4 { When we see Bb2 being played, we continue with ...c4. }
16. Qe2 Re6 { As usual, the key is to avoid White being able to play e4. } 17.
Rfe1 Rae8 18. Nf1 Nh5
{ A cool move. Black wants to combine the ideas of playing ...Nf4 and ...f5. }
19. Qd2 f5
{ Black has a big positional advantage, as in Johannessen-Leko, Tromso 2013. A great game by Peter Leko, who demonstrated how to setup up the pieces against White's e4 and c4 play. He successfully prevented all the active plans of the opponent and the last job remained to activate his a6-knight. }
