[Black "9.Bxa6 with 10.Qd3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ The three main moves now are  10.Qa4  ,  10.Qd3  and  10.Bd2  . In case of  10.Ne5  ,  we transpose to the 9.Ne5 lines. }
10. Qd3 Qc8
{ Once again we see this ...Qc8 move, defending the a6-knight and preparing to play ...c5. }
11. Bd2
{ A very tricky position in my opinion and I would suggest a novelty here. Our usual plan is ...Re8, ...Bf8 followed by the ...c5 push, played even by Magnus Carlsen in this position back in 2015, in a rapid game.   However, in case of  11...Re8  , White has the very unpleasant reply  12.a3   @@StartBracket@@instead of Mamedyarov's  12.Rac1  , after which Black was in time with his play@@EndBracket@@  12...Bf8  and  13.b4!  White achieves a small, but stable advantage on the queenside, using the fact that  13...c5  cannot be played in view of  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Nxd5  . Therefore, my suggestion is to play ...Be7. }
11... Be7
{ With the idea to leave from the a3-b4 very big tempo gain and to be in time to push ...c5. Of course,  11...Rd8  is also possible. The problem is that with 11... Be7 we play ...c5 without putting the rook on d8, but instead the queen on b7. We play ...Rd8 only after a3-b4, to be ready with the ...c5 advance.  11... Be7 might be a little more accurate than 11... Rd8, but certainly both moves could be played. }
12. a3 Rd8
{ And the d5-pawn will be protected. The typical move ...c5 is coming next in any case, even after b4. }
13. b4 c5 { With equality. } *

