[Black "9.Bxa6 with 10.Bd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ The three main moves now are  10.Qa4  ,  10.Qd3  and  10.Bd2  . In case of  10.Ne5  ,  we transpose to the 9.Ne5 lines. }
10. Bd2 Re8 11. Rc1
{ 11.a3  Bf8  12.b4  can now be met by ...c5 with equality, while the direct  @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p1p2ppp/np3n2/3p4/1b1P4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Ne5  can again be answered by  11...c5  . }
11... Bf8
{ White can choose between different plans here. The move  12.Qa4  transposes to the 10.Qa4 variations.  @@StartFEN@@r2qrbk1/p1p2ppp/np3n2/3p4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nb5  makes little sense, as Black can play  12...c5  . The two critical moves are @@StartFEN@@r2qrbk1/p1p2ppp/np3n2/3p4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ne2  and @@StartFEN@@r2qrbk1/p1p2ppp/np3n2/3p4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ne5  . }
12. Qe2 Qc8
{ The usual treatment, followed by ...c5, or ...Qb7 first then ...c5. } 13.
Rfd1 Qb7 14. Be1 c5
{ The queen is perfectly placed on b7, protecting the d5-pawn and the knight on a6. }
15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Qb5
{ White was hoping to get a small endgame advantage, but the following strong reply neutralized it... }
16... Qc8
{ The d5 pawn is indirectly protected by ...Nc7, and otherwise Black is going to play ...Rb8 and ...Qb7 with equality. }
17. Qa5 Qb7 18. Qb5 Qc8 { The position seems to be dynamically equal. } *

