11... Bf8
{ White can choose between different plans here. The move  12.Qa4  transposes to the 10.Qa4 variations.  @@StartFEN@@r2qrbk1/p1p2ppp/np3n2/3p4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nb5  makes little sense, as Black can play  12...c5  . The two critical moves are @@StartFEN@@r2qrbk1/p1p2ppp/np3n2/3p4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ne2  and @@StartFEN@@r2qrbk1/p1p2ppp/np3n2/3p4/3P4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ne5  . }
12. Qe2 Qc8
{ The usual treatment, followed by ...c5, or ...Qb7 first then ...c5. } 13. Ne5
c5 14. f4
{ The only logical follow-up, with the idea of Be1-h4. The game Yusupov-Gajewski continued with  14.Qf3  ,  but after ...Nc7 Black was already better. }
14... Nc7 15. Be1 Qa6 { Would you care for an endgame?! } 16. Qf3 Rac8 17. Bh4
Ne4
{ Personally, I always believe that once we have exchanged the light-squared bishops, to play for an attack with the white pieces is a very risky endeavor. The position that we see on the board is quite easy to play for Black, but very hard for White in a practical game. }
