[Round "?"]
[White "15) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nf3"]
[Black "9.Bxa6 with 10.Ne2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ The three main moves now are  10.Qa4  ,  10.Qd3  and  10.Bd2  . In case of  10.Ne5  ,  we transpose to the 9.Ne5 lines. }
10. Ne2
{ This is already looking super, too-tricky! White wants to avoid everything and gain it all. Chess does not work like that! }
10... Bd6 11. b3
{ Played by Iordachescu; White prepares for the standard ...c5 break, when his minor pieces would finally stand ideally. However, in this case, Black should not hurry with executing the pawn break, but should focus instead on developing the pieces and staying flexible with their plans, depending on what White does. }
11... Re8 12. Bb2 Qe7
{ Black still does not hurry with the ...c5 push - it will not run away. } 13.
Rc1 Rac8 { Any moment White jumps in with Ne5, Black is ready to push ...c5! }
14. Ng3 Qe6
{ Black can further improve his position with ...Ne4, or with ...Nb8-d7. On the other hand, it is unclear what White should do. }
15. Qd3 Nb4 16. Qb1 Ne4
{ In such positions, Black can also consider ...Bxg3, changing the pawn structure with a potentially very dangerous attack @@StartBracket@@after hxg3@@EndBracket@@ by airlifting his heavy pieces to the h-file @@StartBracket@@queen to h5 and ...Re6-h6@@EndBracket@@. }
17. a3 Na6 18. Qd3 Nb8
{ With a good game for Black. ...Nd7 could follow next, as well as having useful moves such as ...g6 and ...h5 that can be played as well. }
