1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ The three main moves now are  10.Qa4  ,  10.Qd3  and  10.Bd2  . In case of  10.Ne5  ,  we transpose to the 9.Ne5 lines. }
10. Qa4 Qc8 11. Bd2 Re8 12. Rfc1
{ A deep move by White. There are a few points behind putting this rook on c1. We will see a concrete one in the main line, but also White's main strategy here is to play on the queenside with a3-b4, when the rook has nothing to do on f1, so it should rather support the queenside actions. This seems to also cause the most headaches for Black. }
12... Bf8 13. Ne2 c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5
{ Carlsen's favorite approach; Black compensates for the isolated pawn with active piece play. The missing of the light-squared bishops is definitely a big deal for Black. We will follow the game of Fressinet, who is a second of Carlsen, and we can be sure that they analyzed these kinds of structures very deeply - he shows us how to play with Black. We can also see now the point of putting the f-rook on c1; White does not need to worry about the upcoming ...Qa6 move as the a2-pawn is protected. }
15. Qc2 Qb7 16. Bc3 Nfe4
{ This is the ideal position for the knights. One goes to e4, the other one is going to exchange a white one from e6. The rook is coming to c8. }
17. b4 { Kicking out the knight, but making a hole on c4. } 17... Ne6 18. Qb3
Rac8 19. Bb2 b5
{ A very nice move, with the simple idea of playing ...Rc4 next. } 20. Rxc8
Rxc8 21. Rd1 Rc4 { With an equal game, as in Pein-Fressinet, England 2018. } *

