[Round "?"]
[White "15) Nimzo Indian with 4.e3, 5.Bd3 and 6.Nf3"]
[Black "9.Bxa6 with 10.Qa4 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3
{ And here comes the mainline of the mainlines, the Nimzo with Bd3 and Nf3! I believe the first time I worked on this position I was around 12 years old; now I am 36 and still, there is soooo much I do not know.My main move against the system has been the ...c5 approach, but the lines you are going to see are my recent lines that I have been carefully checking over recent years, and which - due to Corona and the limited amount of events - I've not had the chance to try. }
6... b6
{ We stay in the same 'rhythm' as in the previous lines; we want to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7. O-O
{ If White wants to avoid our main lines starting with  7.O-O  Ba6  ,  he has two options @@StartBracket@@beside 7. Bd2, which we analyzed in the 5. Bd2 line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Ba6 { White has a wide choice of moves. } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ The three main moves now are  10.Qa4  ,  10.Qd3  and  10.Bd2  . In case of  10.Ne5  ,  we transpose to the 9.Ne5 lines. }
10. Qa4 Qc8 11. Bd2 Re8 12. Rac1 Bf8 13. Ne2
{ The only critical move.  13.a3  cannot cause Black any problems, who can simply play  13...c5  and after  14.dxc5  both Carlsen's favorite, ... Nxc5 followed by ...Qa6 is fine, but also  14...bxc5  equalizes as White is not in time to put pressure on the central pawns. }
13... c5 14. Ng3
{ A continuation played by Aronian against Carlsen in Stavanger 2020. Black could have already reached a very good position with 14...Ne4!, but let's see how the game continued, to familiarize ourselves with the isolated pawn structures as well.  14...Qb7  15.dxc5  Nxc5   15...bxc5  was perfectly fine, but Carlsen prefers to play with the isolani.  16.Qb5  Rac8  17.Rfd1  a6  Chasing away the white queen.  18.Qf1  Nfe4  19.Be1  g6  Very nice positional play by both players. From such games, we can learn a lot for our future encounters!  20.Ne2  Na4  21.Rb1  Bg7  Forcing White to play Nfd4 or Ned4.  22.Nfd4  Nac5  And we are back to the 'waiting' strategy.  23.Nf3  Ne6  24.Ned4  Nxd4  To exchange one pair of knights is OK for Black, says Carlsen.  25.Nxd4  Rc4  Provoking White into playing b3, so that at some point the c3-square might be used.  26.b3  Rc7  27.Qd3  Nc5  28.Qd2  Ne4  29.Qd3  Nc5  30.Qd2  Ne4  A well-played game by both players, but Aronian seemed to be happier with the draw. He was struggling to neutralize the activity of his opponent, while his queen was completely misplaced. Aronian-Carlsen, Stavanger 2020. }
14... Ne4
{ Usually, in case Black can play the ...Ne4, it is a good idea to do so. Actually, there are no tactical tricks for White, and in case of  15.Nxe4  we can continue with  15...dxe4  . Of course, the position remains playable for both colors and we can be sure that White's claims of having an 'opening advantage' would not be correct. }
