[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2, an introduction "]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Nimzo with  4.Qc2  is clearly one of the main choices of White and should be one of the main focuses of our attention. }
4... d5
{ Our choice is the move  4...d5  . There are many other continuations for Black, and perhaps the main one should be considered  4...O-O  . }
5. cxd5
{ 5.a3  is to me maybe the most dangerous move. We have to be very careful here as Black to equalize; on the other hand, all seems to be under control.  5...Bxc3+  6.Qxc3  Ne4  7.Qc2  c5  with a direct play against the center of White. A lot of games have shown that for the moment Black is holding the position without major difficulties.   5.Nf3  The sidelines I do consider to be actually good for Black  5...dxc4  and as you will see in the course, Black is doing very well in most of the cases. We can hope for a full point here. }
5... exd5 6. Bg5
{ Clearly, the main line to focus on!!   6.Nf3  c5  in case you remember the lines, Black should be out of any danger.   6.Bf4  c5  a modern line, which I think just leads to a totally equal play. I see no reasons to be worried here. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Nc6
{ And we quickly get very interesting and original positions for both sides. A great opening line to play for a full point or for a 0 :@@EndBracket@@ which will depend on you! }
