[White "16) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2, sidelines"]
[Black "5.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5
{ The two main moves by far are  5.cxd5  and  5.a3  , but now we are going to check the alternatives. }
5. Bg5 dxc4
{ 6.Nf3  b5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  dxc4  6.Bg5  b5  , while after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/6B1/1bpP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R3KBNR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a3  Bxc3  7.Qxc3  Black can keep his extra pawn with  7...b5  8.a4  c6  . }
6. e3 b5 { We are going to try to keep the extra pawn as long as possible. } 7.
a4 c6 { And now White should transpose to the 5.Nf3 dxc4 line with 8.Nf3. } 8.
Bxf6
{ The only logical alternative, when Black needs to avoid the famous trap of  8...Qxf6?  9.axb5  cxb5  10.Qe4!  and the rook cannot be saved. }
8... gxf6 9. Be2 { With the idea of axb5 next. } 9... a6
{ As said earlier, we will try to keep the extra pawn! } 10. Bf3
{ White tries to compensate for the pawn with an active play. } 10... Ra7
{ Avoiding all the tricks. } 11. Ne2 O-O
{ It is not dangerous now to castle on the kingside, even having not the perfect pawn structure. }
12. O-O Rc7
{ Followed by ...Nd7 next. White should not have enough compensation for being a pawn down. }
