[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2, sidelines"]
[Black "5.e3 c5 6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5
{ The two main moves by far are  5.cxd5  and  5.a3  , but now we are going to check the alternatives. }
5. e3
{ It is quite unusual to combine Qc2 and e3 in the Nimzo. And, of course, we also have a direct way to get a comfortable position. }
5... c5 { Typical. Black is going for White's center. } 6. a3
{ A little too late, but in any case let's check what Black's reaction should be. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3
{ This continuation simply leads to a comfortable game, due to White spending too many queen moves in the opening phase. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6
{ Usually these structures are quite safe for Black, and now White has lost a time on Qc2 and a3, everything looks good even just making the most natural moves. }
9. Nf3 O-O
{ If the f1-bishop moves, Black takes on c4, followed by ... b6 and ...Bb7 with a slightly better position for Black. Not only does White not have enough activity for the isolated pawn on d4, but also the queen will have to lose even more time after Black goes ...Rc8. }
10. Bg5 dxc4 11. Bxc4
{ Here comes a known idea from the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian. When the bishop stands on g5 and the queen on c3, both sides must keep in mind the following option. }
11... Ne4 { Forcing the exchange of queens. } 12. Bxd8 Nxc3 13. Bg5 Nd5
{ Black's next moves are going to be f6, then Rd8, Nce7, Bd7-c6. White cannot really do anything against them, therefore Black can enjoy a small advantage with a good play against the isolated pawn. }
