[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2, sidelines"]
[Black "5.Nf3 dxc4 6.Bg5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5
{ The two main moves by far are  5.cxd5  and  5.a3  , but now we are going to check the alternatives. }
5. Nf3 dxc4
{ The three most common moves are  6.e4  ,  6.Bg5  and  6.e3  , but the rarely played  6.a3  seems an extremely dangerous alternative, where Black really needs to know what to do to avoid ending up in a worse position. }
6. Bg5 b5
{ The move b5 is a very typical one once we have grabbed the c4-pawn. } 7. a4
c6 { Black defends the b5-pawn with all his might. } 8. g3
{ The most challenging move based on the game Mamedyarov-Carlsen, Shamkir 2014, where White developed his light squared bishop in fianchetto. White must try to put pressure on the long diagonal with Bg2 and Ne5 next. }
8... Bb7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 { Black is developing its pieces in a very usual way. }
10. O-O Qb6
{ The move ...Qb6 should not be forgotten, Black's queen is leaving the pin and, at the same time, defending the Bb7. }
11. Ne5 O-O { The position is complex but we are a clear pawn up! } 12. Be3
{ It looks dangerous, but Black can still play with cold blood. } 12... a6 13.
Ne4
{ 13.d5  is met by  13...c5!   13.Nxc6  could win back the pawn, but Black has the very strong  13...Bd6!  14.d5  Bc5⩱  and Black's chances are better in this complex position. }
13... Qc7 { Now ...Nxe5 is already an option. } 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. b3
{ An known idea from the Catalan Opening. White tries to build long-term compensation for the pawn by undermining the queenside and plays Rfc1 with the idea of not allowing Black to clear his position with ...c5. Sometimes it is possible to get stuck in a very passive position with Black, but in this case we can choose activity over material. }
15... cxb3 16. Qxb3 a5
{ A very important move from a strategical point of view. The light-squared bishop will be able, in the long term, to get out thanks to the a6 square. }
17. Rfc1 bxa4
{ A normal continuation, although it seems a little strange because of the self-destruction of one's own pawn structure. }
18. Qxa4 Nb6 19. Qc2 Nd5
{ Improving the knight and blocking the long diagonal, so Black can also play Ba6-b5 somewhere in the future. White has enough compensation here to maintain the balance, but nothing more than that. }
*

