1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5
{ The two main moves by far are  5.cxd5  and  5.a3  , but now we are going to check the alternatives. }
5. Nf3 dxc4
{ The three most common moves are  6.e4  ,  6.Bg5  and  6.e3  , but the rarely played  6.a3  seems an extremely dangerous alternative, where Black really needs to know what to do to avoid ending up in a worse position. }
6. Bg5 b5
{ The move b5 is a very typical one once we have grabbed the c4-pawn. } 7. a4
c6 { Black defends the b5-pawn with all his might. } 8. g3
{ The most challenging move based on the game Mamedyarov-Carlsen, Shamkir 2014, where White developed his light squared bishop in fianchetto. White must try to put pressure on the long diagonal with Bg2 and Ne5 next. }
8... Bb7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 { Black is developing its pieces in a very usual way. }
10. O-O Qb6
{ The move ...Qb6 should not be forgotten, Black's queen is leaving the pin and, at the same time, defending the Bb7. }
11. e4 { This is not consequential after playing 8. g3. } 11... a6
{ Keeping the pawn structure solid. } 12. Rfd1 h6 13. Be3
{ And here Carlsen could have alraedy played 13... c5!, enjoying a nice advantage. This is a typical breakout in such structures. }
13... c5 14. d5 O-O
{ We transposed back to the Mamedyarov-Carlsen game. Black was ready to take back with the queen on e6, therefore Mamedyarov sacrificed another pawn to deflect the queen. }
15. a5
{ The disadvantage of this move is that there will be no more pressure on the pawns on the queenside, and the a5 pawn is also very weak in the long term, so if White fails to break through on the kingside, he will simply be lost. And White actually did not have enough resources to succeed in the attack. }
15... Qd8 16. dxe6 fxe6 17. Nh4 Qc7
{ A small improvement on Carlsen's  17...Qe8  . Black is clearly better, an extra pawn is an extra pawn. }
