{ The three most common moves are  6.e4  ,  6.Bg5  and  6.e3  , but the rarely played  6.a3  seems an extremely dangerous alternative, where Black really needs to know what to do to avoid ending up in a worse position. }
6. a3 { Perhaps the most dangerous of White's continuations. } 6... Bxc3+ 7.
bxc3 { After  7.Qxc3  Black can hold on the c4-pawn with b5. } 7... c5
{ The ...c5 move is used in many different scenarios. Trying to keep the c4 pawn alive by playing  7...b5  is risky,  8.a4  and Ba3 might prevent Black from castling, and getting stuck with the king on e8 is dangerous. }
8. e3
{ Played by Ivan Sokolov, this seems to be less dangerous if Black reacts well. }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4 b5
{ Holding the extra pawn as long as possible. It is not easy for White to win it back. }
10. a4 b4
{ Not a very usual way of acting against the White's a4-pawn, but it is clearly an idea to be remembered. }
11. a5 { With the idea of not allowing Black's ...a5 move. } 11... Ba6 12. Bxc4
O-O
{ Also very good for Black. White does not have perfect development and the b4-pawn cannot be won easily, Black will always have dynamic play at hand. }
