[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2, sidelines"]
[Black "5.Nf3 dxc4 6.e3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5
{ The two main moves by far are  5.cxd5  and  5.a3  , but now we are going to check the alternatives. }
5. Nf3 dxc4
{ The three most common moves are  6.e4  ,  6.Bg5  and  6.e3  , but the rarely played  6.a3  seems an extremely dangerous alternative, where Black really needs to know what to do to avoid ending up in a worse position. }
6. e3 b5 { Again we keep the c4-pawn alive. } 7. a4 c6
{ The usual ...b5 pawn protection. } 8. Bd2
{ White plays in the Noteboom variation style, which is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c6  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.e3  b5  6.a4  Bb4  7.Bd2  a5  8.axb5  Bxc3  9.Bxc3  cxb5  10.b3  Bb7  11.bxc4  b4  12.Bb2  with a very interesting line to play for both sides. The difference now is the inclusion of the moves Qc2 and Nf6, which is clearly in Black's favor. Black can play according to the Noteboom main lines and obtain a better position. }
8... Bb7 9. axb5
{ White has no other better option, otherwise Black might play ...a6 next with just a clear extra pawn. }
9... Bxc3
{ Taking on c3 is not a very attractive option, but it is necessary to keep the extra pawn. }
10. Bxc3 cxb5 11. b3
{ And now Black has a very strong continuation, an improved version of the Noteboom Variation. }
11... Be4 12. Qd1 a5 { A typical idea. } 13. bxc4 b4 14. Bb2 Nbd7
{ The position is complex, but I would prefer to be Black here. } 15. Be2 O-O
16. O-O Qc7
{ This is the typical midgame structure of Noteboom, when Black's strength lies in the connected passed pawns on the queenside, while White should try to use his central pawn majority. However, Black is coming much faster because of the improved version. One idea for Black might be to play ...Bc6 followed by ...a4. It is difficult for White to avoid this easy plan. }
