[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5
{ The two main moves by far are  5.cxd5  and  5.a3  , but now we are going to check the alternatives. }
5. Nf3 dxc4
{ The three most common moves are  6.e4  ,  6.Bg5  and  6.e3  , but the rarely played  6.a3  seems an extremely dangerous alternative, where Black really needs to know what to do to avoid ending up in a worse position. }
6. e4 b5 7. a4 Bb7
{ The other option is  7...c6  which is also playable but I prefer  7...Bb7  . We are giving up the extra pawn but we get a very active play. }
8. e5 Nd5 9. axb5 Nb6
{ This maneuver is also known in other openings. Black saves his c4-pawn and wants to undermine the b5-pawn with ...a6, with the idea that he can move his b8 knight to d5 @@StartBracket@@ via b4@@EndBracket@@. Eventually, Black also has a chance to get rid of his doubled pawns with ...c5. Meanwhile, the b7-bishop stands perfectly on the diagonal. }
10. Be2 a6 { A move that we should remember. } 11. bxa6 Nxa6 12. O-O
{ And now another important move for Black. } 12... Be7
{ Freeing the b4-square for the knight. } 13. Be3 Nb4 14. Qd2 O-O
{ Black is already clearly better. } 15. Nb5
{ White is trying to win the c4-pawn. } 15... Qd7 16. Na3 Bd5
{ After the knight has moved to a3, Black can also change his original plan and put the bishop on d5 instead of the knight. }
17. Bg5 Nc6 { Suddenly the d4-pawn also becomes a weakness. } 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19.
Nb5
{ 19.Rac1  Ra4!  followed by Na5-b3 was much better for Black. And here the game Krasenkow-Kanarek, Warsaw 2015 game could be improved. }
19... Qd7
{ Black is going to win material soon. Either the d4-pawn will be lost or Black will execute his threat with ...Nxe5, when the knight on b5 is hanging. }
