{ Threatening to win material, which forces White to go with his knight to the edge of the board. }
15. Na3 { The next exchanges are forced. } 15... Bxa3 16. bxa3 Nxc4 17. Qxc4
{ And now we calmly play castling. } 17... O-O
{ White is again a pawn up, but Black has full positional compensation. Black is threatening ...Bb5, therefore White is forced to make a move which just prevents it. }
18. Qc5
{ There are other options for White, but in general, Black's compensation is more than fine, having that great light squared bishop. }
18... Bxf3
{ 18...Bd5  followed by ...Qa4 and ...Nc6 is also perfectly safe and maybe from a practical point of view, easier to play, but I keep the other option as the main move because it leads to a nice finish. }
19. gxf3 Nc6 { We want to take on d4. } 20. Be3 Ne7
{ The knight is getting to a perfect square. } 21. a4 Nd5
{ And with such a knight Black will now aim at the white king. } 22. Ra1
{ Only Black can be better in the case of  22.a5  Qa4  . } 22... f6
{ The play on the kingside begins. } 23. a5 Qf7
{ Black's attack arrives in time before the promotion of the a-pawn. Or we can also say that the a-pawn arrives in time before Black can checkmate. }
24. a6 Qg6+ 25. Kh1 Qf5
{ And the game should end in a draw after good play by both sides.Conclusion: overall we saw many interesting positions with a balanced play on both sides. Some lines are hard to remember, and others are easier because of the logical follow-ups. I think the whole line can be played for 3 results, which makes the opening exciting, but on the other hand, complete concentration is needed. I would recommend memorizing at least the first 12 moves of the sharp lines. Positional lines can be played on the board - the moves are mostly natural and logical. }
