{ White has three serious options now, b4, Ke2 and Nd2. } 13. Nd2 Nxd2
{ Looks like the best way to get an equal play. } 14. Bxd2 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qxc5
{ This position was reached twice by Morozevich during the same tournament, in Wijk aan Zee 2009. }
16. Bc3
{ Played by Morozevich in his first 2009 game against Adams, but it was met by the strong and principled ...d4! }
16... d4
{ It would be very risky for White to allow  17.exd4  Rfe8+  18.Kf1  Qd5  , because of the poor bishop and the bad rooks. }
17. Bxd4 Nxd4 18. Qxd4
{ Here Adams continued with  18...Qb5  , but Black still had some problems to solve after  19.O-O-O!  Therefore I suggest an improvement. }
18... Qxd4 19. exd4 Rae8+
{ We are a pawn down, but the position is a forced draw. } 20. Kd2 Re4
{ A very important move! We are directly going for the d4-pawn. } 21. Kd3 Rf4
{ With the threats of ...Rd8 and ...Rxf2, Black is winning back the pawn and reaches equality.  22.Ke3  could be met by  22...g5!  and ...Re8 is coming. }
