{ Played in the game Ivanisevic-Lenic, Bled 2016. } 18... Nxd4
{ Obvioulsy once we have taken on d4, the position is just equal. } 19. Qxd4
Qxd4 20. exd4 Rfe8+
{ No more comments are needed for this drawish rook endgame. } 21. Kd2 Re7
{ and the players soon agreed to a draw. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2 and 5.a3"]
[Black "9.cxd5 with 10.e3 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3
{ One of the main moves and clearly a move that we need to pay close attention to. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3
{ Here and in the next move Black has a wide range of choices. I suggest one of the more dynamic approaches, which on the other hand requires in some lines a high level of exactness. }
6... Ne4 { There are many other continuations for Black here. } 7. Qc2 c5
{ We start, from the very early stage, a dynamic play against White's center. }
8. dxc5
{ Other moves are simply bad or have no meaning of their own, such as  8.cxd5  exd5  9.dxc5  Nc6  which is just a transposition to our main lines. }
8... Nc6
{ We develop the knight and at the same time create the threat of ...Qa5, which could be dangerous for White. }
9. cxd5
{ This is the only line where White tries to preserve the extra pawn, however, nowadays, it is considered to be a bit risky, because it opens the game and Black can get a very strong compensation by using the e-file and playing the bishop on f5 or g4. }
9... exd5
{ White has two wild options here. Both of them were very popular some years ago even at the highest level. We are going to see some really crazy lines. }
10. e3
{ Morozevich's favorite move. Black has a lot of options, but we only focus on what is currently considered to be the best. }
10... O-O 11. Nf3 { Alternatives are rather risky for White. } 11... Bf5
{ Black is almost fully developed. } 12. Bd3 Qa5+
{ White has three serious options now, b4, Ke2 and Nd2. } 13. Nd2 Nxd2
{ Looks like the best way to get an equal play. } 14. Bxd2 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qxc5
{ This position was reached twice by Morozevich during the same tournament, in Wijk aan Zee 2009. }
16. Rc1 Qb6 17. O-O Rad8 18. f4
{ Black was doing fine, when Morozevich came up with this interesting idea to push  f4  , his point was to have e4 in case Black pushes ...d4. The position remained balanced anyway. Carlsen continued with  18...Rfe8  which allowed  19.b4  with Rc5 plans. Probably it was a bit more careful to play ...a5. }
18... a5
{ Preventing the b4-Rc5 idea and only after that playing ...Rfe8 with equality. }
*

