{ Here and in the next move Black has a wide range of choices. I suggest one of the more dynamic approaches, which on the other hand requires in some lines a high level of exactness. }
6... Ne4 { There are many other continuations for Black here. } 7. Qc2 c5
{ We start, from the very early stage, a dynamic play against White's center. }
8. dxc5
{ Other moves are simply bad or have no meaning of their own, such as  8.cxd5  exd5  9.dxc5  Nc6  which is just a transposition to our main lines. }
8... Nc6
{ We develop the knight and at the same time create the threat of ...Qa5, which could be dangerous for White. }
9. cxd5
{ This is the only line where White tries to preserve the extra pawn, however, nowadays, it is considered to be a bit risky, because it opens the game and Black can get a very strong compensation by using the e-file and playing the bishop on f5 or g4. }
9... exd5
{ White has two wild options here. Both of them were very popular some years ago even at the highest level. We are going to see some really crazy lines. }
10. Nf3 Qf6
{ Here as well, following the latest trend seems to be the best decision. } 11.
e3 Bg4 12. Nd4
{ A move that was tried in a few games. Black can play  12...O-O  with a very good position, but how to resist making such a beautiful move... }
12... Bd1
{ Played for the first time in the game Eljanov-Balogh, Bosnia 2006. } 13. Kxd1
Nxf2+ { Black is winning the exchange but the position is not that simple... }
14. Ke1 Nxh1 15. Nxc6
{ Otherwise if White allows the opening of the e-file by ...Nxd4, the game will be quickly over. }
15... bxc6 16. g3 { Black's knight is stuck on h1. } 16... O-O
{ And here the critical move is Bg2. } 17. Bg2
{ The computer gives equality after both  17...Nxg3  or  17...d4  , but in my view, from a practical point of view, it is kind of impossible to play such a position from the White side without the computer's assistance. }
17... d4 { We are opening the position even more. } 18. e4
{ White must keep the e-file closed. } 18... d3 { A beautiful 'little' move. }
19. Qd2 { Now there are a lot of possible moves for Black... } 19... Rab8 20.
Bxh1 Rb3
{ With some mobility problems for White, in addition to the exposed king. Objectively the position is not so clear, but on the board I think Black is doing much better. }
