e3 Bg4 12. Be2 O-O
{ Two moves have been tried here. In almost all the cases, h3 just helps Black as the bishop retreats to f5 and stands more actively. }
13. Bd2 Rac8 14. O-O
{ If  14.h3  Bf5  as usual, while @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/pp3ppp/2n2q2/2Pp4/4n1b1/P3PN2/1PQBBPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 5 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Rc1  runs into the strong  14...Ne5  move! White could try mass simplification with @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/pp3ppp/2n2q2/2Pp4/4n1b1/P3PN2/1PQBBPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 5 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bc3  and after taking everything, Black wins back the pawn with Na5. }
14... Ne5 { Things are getting sharp. } 15. Nxe5 Bxe2 16. Nd7
{ With spectacular play Black obtained a better endgame. } 16... Qa6 17. Nxf8
Bd3
{ A very unpleasant intermediate move. The queen must protect the d2-bishop, but then White will not be able to take back on f1 with the rook. }
18. Qd1 Bxf1
{ The next moves also appear forced, and all this leads to a better position for Black. }
19. Qxf1 Qxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Nxd2 21. Rd1 Rxc5 { The best continuation. } 22. Nd7
Rc2
{ With a better endgame for Black because of the very active pieces. Lysyj-Sargissian, Rijeka 2010 }
