14. Bd2 d4 { When we can play the d4 move, we do it! } 15. Rad1 Nxd2 16. Qxd2
{ Happened in the game Bareev-Ivanchuk, Havana 2006. } 16... Rad8 17. Qc1
{ 17.exd4  is strongly met by  17...Nxd4! } 17... d3
{ Another very forced line. } 18. Rxd3 Rxd3 19. Bxd3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Ne5 21. Be4
Nxf3+ 22. Bxf3 Qxf3
{ After this massive simplification, Ivanchuk correctly assessed the position that has arisen, according to which, despite being one pawn down and having few pieces left on the board, only Black can be better off. The white king is still in great danger, once Black succeeds in bringing his rook to the attack. }
23. Qd1 Qf5 { Of course no endgame. } 24. b4 h6
{ Objectively the position was holdable, but in the game Bareev collapsed ten moves later. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2 and 5.a3"]
[Black "9.cxd5 with 10.Nf3 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3
{ One of the main moves and clearly a move that we need to pay close attention to. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3
{ Here and in the next move Black has a wide range of choices. I suggest one of the more dynamic approaches, which on the other hand requires in some lines a high level of exactness. }
6... Ne4 { There are many other continuations for Black here. } 7. Qc2 c5
{ We start, from the very early stage, a dynamic play against White's center. }
8. dxc5
{ Other moves are simply bad or have no meaning of their own, such as  8.cxd5  exd5  9.dxc5  Nc6  which is just a transposition to our main lines. }
8... Nc6
{ We develop the knight and at the same time create the threat of ...Qa5, which could be dangerous for White. }
9. cxd5
{ This is the only line where White tries to preserve the extra pawn, however, nowadays, it is considered to be a bit risky, because it opens the game and Black can get a very strong compensation by using the e-file and playing the bishop on f5 or g4. }
9... exd5
{ White has two wild options here. Both of them were very popular some years ago even at the highest level. We are going to see some really crazy lines. }
10. Nf3 Qf6
{ Here as well, following the latest trend seems to be the best decision. } 11.
e3 Bg4 12. Be2 O-O
{ Two moves have been tried here. In almost all the cases, h3 just helps Black as the bishop retreats to f5 and stands more actively. }
13. O-O Rfe8
{ This great move was introduced by Ivanchuk in 2006! It supports the ...d4 push in many important lines. White has tried five different moves here;  14.Rd1?  would lose due to  14...Ne5  as the f2-pawn cannot be protected. }
14. Bd2 d4 { When we can play the d4 move, we do it! } 15. Rad1 Nxd2 16. Rxd2
{ Mamedyarov's improvement over Bareev's Qxd2, but So Wesley was well prepared. }
16... dxe3
{ Black wins back the pawn and equalizes the position. If  17.fxe3  then  17...Rxe3  is equal. }
17. Rd6 Re6 { Everything is under control. } 18. fxe3 Rxd6 19. cxd6 Bxf3
{ Important, if  19...Qxd6?  then  20.Ng5!  and Black has problems on h7. } 20.
Bxf3 Qxd6 21. Qb3
{ The position is looking a bit worse for Black, but in fact it is just equal with precise play. }
21... Qe7 22. Bd5 Nd8
{ Holding everything together! Black is ready to activate the rook with ...Rc8. White's damaged pawn structure deprives the chance to hope for any advantage. }
23. Rc1 Qd7 24. Qc4 Ne6 { Black's pieces are out, so the position is equal. }
25. Bxe6 fxe6
{ And a few moves later the players agreed to a draw in the game Mamedyarov-So, Berlin 2018. }
*

