{ White is winning the c4-pawn faster than we could attack the one on c5, but the following forced continuations lead to a draw. Everything has already been played in many games, just remember the key ideas. }
13... b5 { The key move and a MUST to remember. } 14. cxb6 Bb7
{ and Black has enough initiative for the pawn. The analyses in the line lead to a draw, on practically an empty board. }
15. Nf3 Ke7
{ Black's king is taking a perfect position on e7, so the rook on h8 could can quickly join the game. }
16. bxa7 Bxf3 { The easiest way to equalize. } 17. gxf3 Rxa7
{ We want to play ... Rb8 next and there is nothing White can do about it. }
18. Rg1
{ This is White's best chance to bring h1-rook into play as quickly as possible. }
18... Rb8 19. Rc2 Rab7 { The b2-pawn is going to fall. } 20. Bxc4
{ 20.Rxg7  Rxb2  is also equal. } 20... Rxb2 21. Rxb2 Rxb2 22. Bd3 g6
{ The most precise way to secure the draw. } 23. Rg4
{ White's rook is finally out. } 23... Nc6
{ With the double threat of ...Ne5 and ...Rb3. } 24. Ra4 Ne5
{ White is ahead by a pawn, but Black's pieces are active enough to ensure a forced draw. After  25.Be2  Rb1+  26.Kd2  Rb2+  27.Kd1  Ra2=  with the idea of ...Ra1+, the position is just equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2 and 5.a3"]
[Black "9.Nf3 with 10.Nd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3
{ One of the main moves and clearly a move that we need to pay close attention to. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3
{ Here and in the next move Black has a wide range of choices. I suggest one of the more dynamic approaches, which on the other hand requires in some lines a high level of exactness. }
6... Ne4 { There are many other continuations for Black here. } 7. Qc2 c5
{ We start, from the very early stage, a dynamic play against White's center. }
8. dxc5
{ Other moves are simply bad or have no meaning of their own, such as  8.cxd5  exd5  9.dxc5  Nc6  which is just a transposition to our main lines. }
8... Nc6
{ We develop the knight and at the same time create the threat of ...Qa5, which could be dangerous for White. }
9. Nf3
{ Here we have three equally series major moves, although today the most popular is clearly  9.Nf3  . The options  9.e3  and  9.Nf3  lead to very similar positions, in which White tries to gain a small endgame advantage, which can be neutralized with a few accurate moves. }
9... Qa5+ { The usual queen's check. } 10. Nd2 Nd4
{ A very important move and it is more White who has to be careful in complications. }
11. Qd1 Nxc5 { 11...Bd7  is also possible. } 12. b4 Qa4 13. Ra2
{ And now we are entering the endgame. } 13... Qxd1+ 14. Kxd1 Na4
{ And once again, because of the direct tactical threats, White is unable to get any kind of advantage. }
15. Bb2 Nxb2+
{ Once the Bishop is taken the position is usually completely equal. } 16. Rxb2
dxc4 17. Nxc4 Ke7
{ With ...Bd7 and ...Rhd8 following. Granda Zuniga-Hou Yifan Zafra 2007. } *

