[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2 and 5.a3"]
[Black "9.Nf3 with 10.Bd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3
{ One of the main moves and clearly a move that we need to pay close attention to. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3
{ Here and in the next move Black has a wide range of choices. I suggest one of the more dynamic approaches, which on the other hand requires in some lines a high level of exactness. }
6... Ne4 { There are many other continuations for Black here. } 7. Qc2 c5
{ We start, from the very early stage, a dynamic play against White's center. }
8. dxc5
{ Other moves are simply bad or have no meaning of their own, such as  8.cxd5  exd5  9.dxc5  Nc6  which is just a transposition to our main lines. }
8... Nc6
{ We develop the knight and at the same time create the threat of ...Qa5, which could be dangerous for White. }
9. Nf3
{ Here we have three equally series major moves, although today the most popular is clearly  9.Nf3  . The options  9.e3  and  9.Nf3  lead to very similar positions, in which White tries to gain a small endgame advantage, which can be neutralized with a few accurate moves. }
9... Qa5+ { The usual queen's check. } 10. Bd2 Qxc5
{ We finally regained the pawn, and next ...Nxd2 is coming up. } 11. e3
{ The Bd2 can't escape. } 11... Nxd2 12. Nxd2
{ Here the two main moves are  12...dxc4  and  12...d4  .  12...O-O  also has some following, but I would like to suggest a fourth move, which has been tried in only 3 games so far. The greatest expert on this line is Karjakin, who has demonstrated in many games how to hold a slightly worse endgame in the case of  12...dxc4  . }
12... Bd7
{ Knowing Black's defensive arrangements in the variant  12...dxc4  ,  we know that Black's main resource is to develop pieces very quickly with ...Bd7, ...Rac8, ...Rfd8, and ...Be8.The idea of this move is to gain some very important time and to capture ...dxc4 later to avoid the critical variations. }
13. b4
{ Always the critical move.  13.Rc1  does not bring much benefit, Black can simply continue with  13...O-O }
13... Qe7
{ White tried different plans in all three games. One of the greatest experts on the whole line with White is GM Dreev, who played  14.Qb2  , so we keep it as the main move. }
14. Qc3
{ Is a well-known move in the ...dxc4 positions. The idea is to push ...b5 and the knight cannot go on the active squares of e5 or a5. }
14... O-O 15. b5 { 15.c5  e5  is also fine for Black. } 15... Nb8
{ This is our point, and regardless of what White does, Black will be able to undermine the pawns on the queenside with ...a6 and obtain an equal position. }
16. cxd5
{ I tried  16.Qb4  as an improvement for White, but Black can continue with  16...Re8!  and, again, ...a6 is going to be played on the next move. }
16... exd5 17. Be2 a6
{ Once we have played ...a6, the Nb8 is joining the game. } 18. bxa6 Nxa6 19.
O-O Nc5
{ After successfully undermining the pawn, Black had no problem in the game Stella-Sebenik, Radenci 2019. ...Rfc8 is coming with an even position. }
*

