[White "18) Nimzo Indian with 4.Qc2 and 5.cxd5, the sidelines"]
[Black "5.cxd5 exd5 6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5
{ We now have two main lines, which are  6.Bf4  and  6.Bg5  , but  6.Nf3  also deserves our attention because it is an often-played move with a logic of its own. }
6. a3
{ In my opinion, it makes no sense at all. White is forcing Black to take on c3, but the white queen is already in c2, which in many lines is a pure waste of time. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
{ 7.Qxc3  is completely wrong. Black gets the upper hand immediately by playing  7...Ne4! }
7... c5
{ We have several ways to continue, but I like the direct ...c5 approach. } 8.
Nf3 O-O 9. g3
{ This is the only chance for White to get something original. Otherwise,  9.e3  transposes to the structures we study in the Nimzo-Indian with 4. e3 and  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  is not at all dangerous for Black. }
9... cxd4 10. Nxd4
{ White can't take with the c-pawn because of the bad position of the queen. }
10... Nc6 11. Bg2
{ If White takes on c6 first, Black arrives very quickly with ...Re8 and ...Ba6. }
11... Nxd4
{ This move is not really necessary, but it offers an easy and direct play for Black. }
12. cxd4 Re8 13. O-O h6 { Prophylaxis against Bg5. } 14. Bf4 b6
{ Followed by ...Ba6 with a small edge for Black once Black completes his development with ...Rc8, ...Bc4 and ...Ne4. }
