[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5
{ We now have two main lines, which are  6.Bf4  and  6.Bg5  , but  6.Nf3  also deserves our attention because it is an often-played move with a logic of its own. }
6. a3
{ In my opinion, it makes no sense at all. White is forcing Black to take on c3, but the white queen is already in c2, which in many lines is a pure waste of time. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
{ 7.Qxc3  is completely wrong. Black gets the upper hand immediately by playing  7...Ne4! }
7... c5
{ We have several ways to continue, but I like the direct ...c5 approach. } 8.
Bg5 h6 { We are forcing White to take on f6. } 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. e3
{ Karpov and Korchnoi won a game with the white pieces in this line, but it did not happen because of an opening advantage. Actually, Black is already looking a bit better. }
10... O-O
{ I think we can already tell from here that Black has an excellent position. }
11. Nf3 c4
{ The black bishop approaches f5, and the white bishop does not have a chance to occupy the ideal b1-h7 diagonal. }
12. Be2 Bf5 { What a dream position! } 13. Qb2 Nd7
{ This is the cleanest way to play with the idea of making progress on the queenside, where Black has the pawn majority. The idea is to continue with ...Qc6, ...b5, ...Nb6-a4 and finally create a passed pawn with ...a5-b4. The b7 pawn is poisoned because taking it would open the b-file and allow the black rooks to invade White's camp. }
