[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5
{ We now have two main lines, which are  6.Bf4  and  6.Bg5  , but  6.Nf3  also deserves our attention because it is an often-played move with a logic of its own. }
6. Nf3 c5 7. Bg5
{ 7.a3  Bxc3  8.bxc3  O-O  leads to the 6. a3 line. This whole line with 6. Nf3 leads to Ragozin type of positions, arising after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  Bb4  and  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  ,  where the Qc2 move is not the most dangerous setup. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5
{ Black could transpose into a popular Ragozin line with  8...O-O  which is fine, but against this move order Black also has a more aggressive option. }
9. Bg3 Ne4 { The position is very dynamic. } 10. e3
{ The alternative to neutralize the upcoming ...Bf5 is to quickly bring the bishop to d3, but White still fails to equalize. }
10... Bf5 11. Bd3 c4 { We are asking the bishop what's next. } 12. Bxe4 Bxe4
13. Qa4+ Nc6
{ With an excellent version of the Ragozin-type structure. Black is already better with such a bishop on e4. Two games are continued with the more tempting but mistaken  14.Ne5?!  . However, even if White tries  14.h4  , Black can simply play  14...O-O  and enjoy an advantage, since his king is perfectly safe. }
14. Ne5 Bxg2 { Black can grab the pawn, using a known tactical idea... } 15.
Nxc6 Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 Qd7
{ This is the point behind 15... Bxg2. Black pins the queen and ends up with an extra pawn. }
17. Rg1 Be4 18. Be5 { Attacking the h8-rook. } 18... Rg8 19. f3 Bd3
{ And Black was clearly better in the game Malakhov-Ponomariov, Khanty-Mansiysk 2009. }
