[Black "5.cxd5 exd5 6.Nf3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5
{ We now have two main lines, which are  6.Bf4  and  6.Bg5  , but  6.Nf3  also deserves our attention because it is an often-played move with a logic of its own. }
6. Nf3 c5 7. Bg5
{ 7.a3  Bxc3  8.bxc3  O-O  leads to the 6. a3 line. This whole line with 6. Nf3 leads to Ragozin type of positions, arising after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  Bb4  and  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  ,  where the Qc2 move is not the most dangerous setup. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5
{ Black could transpose into a popular Ragozin line with  8...O-O  which is fine, but against this move order Black also has a more aggressive option. }
9. Bg3 Ne4 { The position is very dynamic. } 10. dxc5 Qa5
{ Black has many more moves at his disposal, but I suggest following the latest trend. }
11. Nd2
{ This is the only move and a known way to try to handle the e1-a5 diagonal. Now  11...Nxc3  also leads to interesting positions, but the following forced line is easier to play. }
11... Bf5 { The beginning of an extremly forced line. } 12. Nb3 Nxc5
{ As I have already explained, the following several moves are forced for both sides. }
13. Qxf5 { White has nothing else that makes sense. } 13... Bxc3+ 14. bxc3
Qxc3+ 15. Kd1 Nxb3
{ Everything is hanging and White has only one move, which leads to the endgame. }
16. Qe5+ Qxe5 17. Bxe5
{ After a series of 'only moves' the game continues with the 'stronger moves'. }
17... f6 18. Bxf6
{ And here I suggest a small improvement over the game Martinovic-Hracek, Sibenik 2016, which continued with  18...Rf8  after which White could have caused some minor problems. }
18... O-O { Looks very solid. } 19. axb3 Rxf6
{ We have a strange endgame, but it doesn't look any worse for Black. } 20. h4
{ 20.f3  Nc6  is also equal. } 20... Rxf2 { Simple and good. } 21. hxg5 hxg5
22. Ra5
{ White's rooks are active on both flanks, but it is more of a visual effect than anything really dangerous. }
22... Nc6 23. Rxd5 Rd8
{ Proposing a rook exchange, with a simple endgame that should end in a clear draw.Conclusion: The move 6. Nf3 is tricky because the opponent may want to trick us by playing the Ragozin, but if we remember the direct approach and the right order of moves, we do very well from the opening with a good chance of getting a better position. Personally, I would be happy to see 6. Nf3 in my games, knowing that actually in the 'main' lines, especially after 6. Bg5, I have to be extremely careful. }
