12. Be2
{ On  12.b4  ,  just like in the 12.Rc1 line, Black plays  12...a5!  and on both  13.b5  or  13.bxa5  he continues with  13...Rfc8  followed by c5! }
12... c5 { We finished the execution of our game plan with ...c5. } 13. O-O c4
{ Black has a perfect version of the Ragozin structure. Next we would like to play ...b5 and ...a5 with a big advantage. White's only plan could be to undermine the queenside with a4-b3. }
14. a4 a6 15. a5 { And anyway right now we play the move ...b5! } 15... b5 16.
axb6 Qxb6
{ Black's pawn on a6 might be weak, but White's b2-pawn is even weaker! } 17.
Ra5 Nf6
{ In the Martirosyan-Bluebaum game, Moscow 2016, Black played  17...Rfb8  with the interesting idea of exchanging the one on d5 for the b2-pawn, but he could have simply protected the d5-pawn first and had a small advantage after playing ...Rfb8. }
