1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
{ Probably the main move of our 4. Qc2 Nimzo-Indian. } 6... h6
{ It is very important not to forget to play instantly  6...h6  . } 7. Bh4 g5
{ The main theoretical lines begin with  7...c5  8.dxc5  g5  9.Bg3  Ne4  with thousands of games and extreme complications. I would like to suggest a rare alternative, which is gaining popularity today after several top GMs have used it successfully. }
8. Bg3 Nc6
{ We do not usually put the knight on c6 before playing the move c5, but in this line there is a concrete reason to do so. }
9. e3 h5
{ A very dynamic variation, where it is easy to play for a win from the opening stage of the game. We got right to the crossroads, White tried 7 different moves here. }
10. f3 Qe7
{ Black attacks the e3- and also the d4-pawn. The move ...Qe7 in general should be kept in the memory: it also support the idea of ...O-O-O at some point. }
11. O-O-O
{ The one critical move leads to a very interesting line.  11.Kd2  was played by Nakamura in a blitz game in 2021, but I doubt anyone will try this move in a longer time control. Black could have reached a better position after  11...h4  12.Bf2  and  12...Bd7  ,  followed by ... O-O-O. }
11... Qxe3+ 12. Kb1 Nxd4
{ A very forced line, but everything is under control. } 13. Rxd4
{ A forced sacrifice, otherwise  13.Qa4+  Bd7  14.Qxb4  Bf5+  is winning for Black. }
13... Qxd4 14. Nb5 Qd2 15. Nxc7+ Ke7
{ White cannot take the rook because of ...Bf5 and there's a checkmate on d1. }
16. Bd3 Qxc2+ 17. Kxc2 Be6 18. Nxa8 Rxa8
{ White did not have enough compensation to save the game in the Narciso Dublan-Vallejo Pons, Marbella 2019. }
