1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
{ Probably the main move of our 4. Qc2 Nimzo-Indian. } 6... h6
{ It is very important not to forget to play instantly  6...h6  . } 7. Bh4 g5
{ The main theoretical lines begin with  7...c5  8.dxc5  g5  9.Bg3  Ne4  with thousands of games and extreme complications. I would like to suggest a rare alternative, which is gaining popularity today after several top GMs have used it successfully. }
8. Bg3 Nc6
{ We do not usually put the knight on c6 before playing the move c5, but in this line there is a concrete reason to do so. }
9. e3 h5
{ A very dynamic variation, where it is easy to play for a win from the opening stage of the game. We got right to the crossroads, White tried 7 different moves here. }
10. h3
{ Trying to save the bishop is a natural reaction, but it gives Black a lot of tempi. }
10... Ne4 11. Bh2 Qe7 { Black's pieces are acting greatly together. } 12. Nf3
{ 12.Nge2  was also tried, but it makes no sense because of  12...Bf5  . }
12... Bf5 13. Bd3 { A beautiful model game was played by Black here. } 13... g4
{ White cannot open the h-file, otherwise Black takes h3. } 14. Ne5 gxh3 15.
gxh3 Rh6 { Once again the rook joins to the game with this typical motif. } 16.
Nxc6 Rxc6 { Involves an extremely powerful exchange sacrifice. } 17. Bb5 O-O-O
{ Fantastic play by Black. } 18. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Black's remaining pieces are too strong while White's ones are passive, and the king does not find its place on the board. White is already in trouble here. }
19. a3 Bxc3+ 20. bxc3 Rg8
{ The rook is ready to invade through g2, and Black correctly assesses that he need not worry about exchanging it because the queen would join the attack very effectively. }
21. Rg1 Rxg1+ 22. Bxg1 Qg5
{ What a beautiful positional play by Black. The game continued with  23.O-O-O  Qg2  White is running out of moves.  He is struggling to find any counterplay while Black is ready to take on h3 and promote the h-pawn.  24.h4  Nd6!  Bringing the knight to c4.  25.Qb3  Nc4  White is already in a kind of zugzwang. Only the queen can move, but it has limited squares.  26.Qb4  Kd7-+  Total domination of the black pieces. Black later went on to win the game in Veinberg-Donchenko, Barcelona 2019. }
