{ We do not usually put the knight on c6 before playing the move c5, but in this line there is a concrete reason to do so. }
9. e3 h5
{ A very dynamic variation, where it is easy to play for a win from the opening stage of the game. We got right to the crossroads, White tried 7 different moves here. }
10. Bb5
{ This is considered to be the main line and it is also the most frequently played move. }
10... h4 11. Be5 O-O { The alternative  11...Rh6  is also interesting. } 12.
Bxc6 bxc6 13. a3
{ There are three games in the database for this position, and in all of them Black withdrew with ... Bd6, after which Black's position could have been worse. Therefore I suggest a novelty... }
13... Bxc3+
{ Of course we take on c3, as we have seen in many previous variations. } 14.
Qxc3 Rb8
{ 14...Rb8 is a bit strange, but seems to be the strongest. The pressure on the b-file and the idea of playing ...Ne4 next remains; we do not care much about the c6-pawn. }
15. Qxc6 Ne8 { Threatening f6. } 16. h3 Rxb2
{ The position should still be around equal, but it looks dangerous for White from a practical point of view. }
*

