[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Bogo Indian, an introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ This is the starting position of the Bogo-Indian Defence. Let's start from the opening's very logical roots: The Bogo-Indian Defence is over 100 years old and is still being played on the highest level – which is obviously a good sign. The move  3...Bb4  is a very logical one: we develop a piece with a check, and what can be wrong with that!? Naturally, this is another good sign.   For instance, each time I play the King's Indian, I say to myself: 'This doesn't look right... I have no center. Yes, maybe I have some counterplay, but what happens if not?!' The global idea of the Bogo-Indian in 'our lines' is fairly simple: it is a very safe approach, and we are aiming to reach an equal position. For White, it is very hard to prove an advantage, and if White goes 'too far' in these attempts we get great counter chances. The downside is, of course, that if White is happy with a draw, it will be hard for us to complicate the position.   Another great point for Black is that most of the moves are very natural, so just knowing the main ideas enables us to find the right ones just over the board.   Conclusion: In case you are in a 'must win' situation with Black, it is probably not the best practical choice, but in most cases – when we are happy with achieving comfortable play – the lines you are going to see are suitable for every level of a chess player. I believe that the baseline could be played for at least the next 10 years without any major changes. Surely, some small adjustments will appear here and there, but it is nothing to be compared with, let's say, the 'Najdorf', where everything is changing monthly and not rehearsing and repeating the lines before the game might mean trouble in a forced line straight from the opening. }
4. Nbd2
{ To me, this is the most critical choice for White. I would advise you to to focus on 4. Nbd2 because it is strategically dangerous for Black – White is going to have a bishop pair.   A@@EndBracket@@  4.Bd2  This move is also very often played, but if we can remember the next 2 moves, we will reach a safe position. In addition, if we remember the major ideas, in my opinion, the whole line can be played on 'feeling'.  4...Bxd2+  5.Qxd2  d5  It is very important to remember the d5-push!  6.Nc3  O-O  7.e3  and here we are in the critical position. The next move again needs to be remembered:  7...Qe7  With the idea of playing ...c5 next. The rest of the lines should be checked, of course, and you can find them inside the course, but just for a shortcut: this is the key position. Pay the most attention to it, check the ideas, and please do not be too worried in case you might forget some lines. Most of the moves are natural and even after a small mistake the worst that can happen is a slightly inferior position.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.Nc3  This would lead us back into the Nimzo-Indian 4. Nf3 variation. }
4... b6
{ It is important to remember  4...b6  because we need to get our c8-bishop into the game as quickly as possible. }
5. a3
{ The most critical: White gains the bishop pair and aims for a theoretically long-term positional advantage. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7
{ The b7-square is often the perfect position for the c8-bishop. } 7. e3 O-O
{ Again, it is important to remember to castle first – please wait for White's next move as it is critical. }
8. Be2
{ And once  8.Be2  has been played – which is the most natural and most critical move – we can play... }
8... d5
{ And the rest can be found in the Bogo-Indian with 4. Nbd2 Chapter.   Conclusion: We are aiming for very safe positions with clear play for Black. It is a great opening that can provide us with a transparent plan for the next 10 years without ever working much on it.   Downside: In case White is not too ambitious, it is going to be a very hard task to get real chances of playing objectively for a win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) Bogo Indian with 4.Bd2 Bxd2+ 5.Nbxd2"]
[Black "5.Nbxd2 O-O 6.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ We will not focus on other continuations such as  4...Qe7  ,  4...c5  or  4...a5  , as they lead to slightly worse positions, but of course, they are playable options. I myself have played  4...Qe7  and  4...c5  many times, but each time I ask myself why, when I am very sure that I will end up in a somewhat worse position straight from the opening! }
5. Nbxd2
{ This recapture is not considered to be the most accurate in this and similar openings, as the ideal - and much more active - placement for the knight is on c3. In fact, in many cases, the knight is completely misplaced on d2, for example in structures such as white pawns on e4/d5 and black pawns on d6/e5.   White needs to choose between three setups @@StartBracket@@e4, e3 or g3@@EndBracket@@ and Black's main plan is connected to the pawn structure outlined above: in most cases, I suggest ...d6-e5, however, against the g3 systems, I believe the easiest setup involves ...b6. Therefore I recommend the most flexible move order, to see first what White is planning next. }
5... O-O 6. g3
{ I like the idea of opposing the bishop on the long diagonal with ...b6. }
6... b6 7. e4
{ This move has not been tried yet, but it is a known idea from the Queen's Indian Defence, with the plan that after ... Bb7 White would develop his bishop to Bd3 instead of g2, trying to control the center. It is important to react now with ...c5. }
7... c5
{ Using the idea that White is not yet prepared to push  8.d5?  in view of a quick  8...exd5  followed by ...Re8, after which the center collapses on White. }
8. e5 Ne8 9. d5
{ This move is an attempt to squeeze the black pieces, but the white pieces don't yet support such an aggressive approach. First of all,  9...Bb7  is completely fine, but Black can already play for an advantage by undermining the pawns with  ...d6  . }
9... d6 10. Bg2 exd5 { White's center is falling apart. } 11. cxd5 Nd7
{ Black has a slight advantage. } *

