[White "21) Bogo Indian with 4.Bd2 Bxd2+ 5.Nbxd2"]
[Black "5.Nbxd2 O-O 6.e3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ We will not focus on other continuations such as  4...Qe7  ,  4...c5  or  4...a5  , as they lead to slightly worse positions, but of course, they are playable options. I myself have played  4...Qe7  and  4...c5  many times, but each time I ask myself why, when I am very sure that I will end up in a somewhat worse position straight from the opening! }
5. Nbxd2
{ This recapture is not considered to be the most accurate in this and similar openings, as the ideal - and much more active - placement for the knight is on c3. In fact, in many cases, the knight is completely misplaced on d2, for example in structures such as white pawns on e4/d5 and black pawns on d6/e5.   White needs to choose between three setups @@StartBracket@@e4, e3 or g3@@EndBracket@@ and Black's main plan is connected to the pawn structure outlined above: in most cases, I suggest ...d6-e5, however, against the g3 systems, I believe the easiest setup involves ...b6. Therefore I recommend the most flexible move order, to see first what White is planning next. }
5... O-O 6. e3
{ A solid move, trying to avoid the e4 vs d6-e5 structure, but of course it is rather safe, than a dangerous strategy for Black. }
6... d6 7. Bd3 Qe7 { Black will still execute the e5-push. } 8. O-O e5
{ Black is threatening ...e4 and the structure would change favorably for him if White were to take on e5. Therefore the only logical continuation is ...e5. }
9. Qc2
{ And now most games have continued with the most natural continuation,  9...Re8  ,  refreshing the ...e4 threat. However, in this case, White can play  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  after which the h7-pawn is hanging. After  11...h6  or  11...g6  , White would aim to get a position with  12.dxe5  dxe5  and  13.c5  .  Therefore, I suggest a small prophylactical improvement with ...h6. }
9... h6
{ And next move we play ...Re8. If White tries some activity with  10.c5  , then  10...Bg4!  is strong, after which Black will develop his knight on c6! }
10. h3 Re8 11. dxe5
{ 11.Ne4  Nxe4  12.Bxe4  Nd7  with ...Nf6 next is also fine for Black. } 11...
dxe5 { Usually already now we can be quite sure that things are OK. } 12. Ne4
Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Nd7
{ And Black is completely fine. Black's knight is going to take a nice position on f6 or c5 and the Bc8 will join the game.   Conclusion: as we saw in the main line or in the sidelines, Black is gaining quickly by playing logical moves a comfortable play which makes the 5.Nbd2 line objectively not the best try for White. Even in the case you forgot the best answer in some lines, as Black there is nothing much to worry about, usually few options are very playable. The most critical point is to understand the position! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Bogo Indian with 4.Bd2 Bxd2+ 5.Qxd2"]
[Black "5.Qxd2 d5 6.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ We will not focus on other continuations such as  4...Qe7  ,  4...c5  or  4...a5  , as they lead to slightly worse positions, but of course, they are playable options. I myself have played  4...Qe7  and  4...c5  many times, but each time I ask myself why, when I am very sure that I will end up in a somewhat worse position straight from the opening! }
5. Qxd2
{ Why does White recapture with the queen? The answer is simple: White intends to develop the knight to c3, which is a much better position for the steed than on d2. }
5... d5
{ Here the ... d5-setup is considered to be the most solid for Black, but as we will see, White can cause us some headaches in both options. He must decide the character of the game now by choosing which direction to develop his f1-bishop.   6.e3  does not have its own significance because, after  6...O-O  , White should transpose to the main line with  7.Nc3  . }
6. g3
{ This is a very serious option for White, directing the game towards the Catalan opening - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.g3  . }
6... c6 7. Bg2 O-O
{ Black's main idea is to develop safely with ...Nbd7, ...b6, ...Bb7 and later push ...c5 with equality. However, against the main move  8.O-O  , we have a new direction in mind, therefore White must also consider some other options here. }
8. Qc2
{ In this case, White intends to develop his knight to d2 and play for e4 in the future. }
8... b6 9. Nbd2
{ If White wants to save on the O-O tempo to execute the e4-break, Black is well prepared with ...Bb7 followed by ...c5. }
9... Bb7 10. e4 c5 { The typical ...c5 push. } 11. exd5
{ 11.e5  Ne4  is also good for Black. } 11... exd5 12. O-O Nbd7
{ With equality. There will be exchanges of the central pawns in the next moves, which should lead to an equal position. }
*

