14. Rad1 { Leads to a forced line. } 14... cxd4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Nxd4
{ And we are in time to take the e5-pawn. } 16... Nxe5 17. Bxe4
{ There is nothing better for White: none of the tactical continuations seem to work. }
17... Bxe4 18. Qxe4
{ And here the game Gomez-Alvarez, Panama 2013, should be improved upon by playing ...Qf6. }
18... Qf6 19. Rfe1 Rfe8
{ Works, as Black can open his back rank next move with equality, and  20.f4  does not cause problems on the back rank because we have  20...Nf3+!  21.Qxf3  Rxe1+  22.Rxe1  Qxd4+  , always with check and equality. }
