{ Very concrete, and it works! If  13.f4  then  13...f6  is strong. The critical move is now  Qf4  . }
13. Qf4 h5
{ Threatening to play ...f6 or ...Qb8 winning the pawn and White has no time to send away the knight with h3. }
14. h3 g5 { Everything seems to work for Black. } 15. Qd4 c5
{ Wins the e5-pawn. } 16. Qc3 { This looks simply terrible for White. } 16...
d4 17. Qd2 Bxg2 18. hxg4 { White is winning a pawn... but losing the game! }
18... Bc6 19. gxh5 f6
{ Black is close to having a winning position, due to future actions on the kingside and having a fantastic c6-bishop vs a very passive a3-knight. }
