[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Bogo Indian with 4.Bd2 Bxd2+ 5.Qxd2"]
[Black "5.Qxd2 d5 6.g3 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ We will not focus on other continuations such as  4...Qe7  ,  4...c5  or  4...a5  , as they lead to slightly worse positions, but of course, they are playable options. I myself have played  4...Qe7  and  4...c5  many times, but each time I ask myself why, when I am very sure that I will end up in a somewhat worse position straight from the opening! }
5. Qxd2
{ Why does White recapture with the queen? The answer is simple: White intends to develop the knight to c3, which is a much better position for the steed than on d2. }
5... d5
{ Here the ... d5-setup is considered to be the most solid for Black, but as we will see, White can cause us some headaches in both options. He must decide the character of the game now by choosing which direction to develop his f1-bishop.   6.e3  does not have its own significance because, after  6...O-O  , White should transpose to the main line with  7.Nc3  . }
6. g3
{ This is a very serious option for White, directing the game towards the Catalan opening - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.g3  . }
6... c6 7. Bg2 O-O
{ Black's main idea is to develop safely with ...Nbd7, ...b6, ...Bb7 and later push ...c5 with equality. However, against the main move  8.O-O  , we have a new direction in mind, therefore White must also consider some other options here. }
8. Na3
{ This looks ugly at first sight, but it is a known move in similar positions. White protects his c4-pawn and wants to play Ne5 and Rc1 @@StartBracket@@against our aforementioned ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7 plan@@EndBracket@@ to exploit the c6-square and in some cases after taking on d5, the knight might also cause some trouble with Nb5. The drawback of the move is, as we will see in some lines, that Black sometimes takes back with the e-pawn on d5 and keeps the knight out of the game, as it cannot jump to b5. }
8... Nbd7
{ It is important to start with this move because  8...b6  9.Ne5  Bb7  10.Rc1  leads to a very unpleasant position. It is worth mentioning that Black has the option to enter into an endgame with @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/N4NP1/PP1QPPBP/R3K2R b KQ - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ne4  9.Qc2  Qa5+  10.Nd2  Nxd2  11.Qxd2  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  and here the position is very close to equal if Black plays ...Rd8 and ...a5. But, of course, the only side that can be better is White. }
9. O-O b6 10. Rfc1
{ Was the preferred rook to c1 by Ivanchuk and other grandmasters, but I am not sure where White can profit from having his rook on a1. }
10... Bb7 11. cxd5 exd5
{ Now we can see the drawback of @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP1QPPBP/RN2K2R w KQ - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Na3  .  White must try to give some function to it, but on c2 it still would not do anything and it is unclear where it is going from there. Therefore, the best is most probably to play Nb1. }
12. Nb1
{ On the other hand, to lose two tempi sounds a bit too much to continue fighting for an advantage! }
12... Ne4 { Not bad to have a knight on e4 with a tempo. } 13. Qd1 Re8 14. Nc3
Qe7
{ With an equal position. Depending on what White does next, we will react accordingly. Usually, the plan could be connected to ...Rad8 and ...c5. }
*

