{ A plan known from the Catalan opening. White often sacrifices a pawn like this, trying to get a dominating position where he is a pawn down, but the black pieces are very passive. }
10... cxb3 { There is nothing better for Black. } 11. Nxc6
{ This continuation wins back the pawn, but again it allows Black to get rid of his passive pieces and reach easy equality. }
11... Nxc6 12. Bxc6 b2
{ 12...Rb8  13.axb3  Bb7  is also OK, but it is cleverer to not allow the opening of the a-file. }
13. Qxb2 Rb8 { Black's position is looking very fine indeed. } 14. Rc1 Qb6 15.
Nd2 Bb7
{ With a totally easy to play and equal position, as in Markus-Grachev, Kragujevac 2013. }
