12. Nc3 Nbd7
{ An important motif! Black would like to give back his extra pawn to escape from the cramped position. }
13. Rfd1
{ The critical move, again trying to keep the tension. If Black takes on e5, then dxe5, followed by Ne4, could see the c5/d6 squares becoming really bad for Black. }
13... Qc7
{ It is important to get rid of the active knight, and not by taking it as mentioned before. }
14. Nxd7 Nxd7
{ Black is ready to activate his extra pawn on the queenside with ...a5, therefore White has to play b4. }
15. b4 Nf6
{ Black is still a pawn up, but White has full compensation. If Black has the chance to free his position with ...a5 or ...e5, he should definitely do so, but here for example  15...a5  does not work because of  16.bxa5  Rxa5  17.Nd5!  winning an exchange. }
16. Ne4 { 16.e4  e5!  frees Black's position. } 16... Nxe4 17. Bxe4 h6
{ And the position should objectively be equal as the black pieces are too passive to be able to realize the material advantage. On the other hand, though, White should not be dreaming about a full point here either! }
