{ Here the ... d5-setup is considered to be the most solid for Black, but as we will see, White can cause us some headaches in both options. He must decide the character of the game now by choosing which direction to develop his f1-bishop.   6.e3  does not have its own significance because, after  6...O-O  , White should transpose to the main line with  7.Nc3  . }
6. Nc3 O-O 7. Qf4
{ This alternative to the main move, which changes the character of the game, was introduced by Mamedyarov. White is planning to play e4, but such queen actions are rarely good in the early opening stage. }
7... c5 { We are not wasting any time! } 8. dxc5 Qa5
{ White has a choice here, but nothing seems to be too dangerous. } 9. a3 Nc6
{ Developing and preventing b4. } 10. e3 Re8
{ I like this idea of scaring White with ...e5/...d4 attacking plans. } 11. Be2
e5 12. Qh4 d4 { We are in the game ! } 13. exd4 exd4 14. Nxd4 Bg4
{ And it is White who needs to be careful, although objectively the game is still balanced. }
