[Round "?"]
[White "22) Bogo Indian with 4.Bd2 Bxd2+ 5.Qxd2"]
[Black "5.Qxd2 d5 6.Nc3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ We will not focus on other continuations such as  4...Qe7  ,  4...c5  or  4...a5  , as they lead to slightly worse positions, but of course, they are playable options. I myself have played  4...Qe7  and  4...c5  many times, but each time I ask myself why, when I am very sure that I will end up in a somewhat worse position straight from the opening! }
5. Qxd2
{ Why does White recapture with the queen? The answer is simple: White intends to develop the knight to c3, which is a much better position for the steed than on d2. }
5... d5
{ Here the ... d5-setup is considered to be the most solid for Black, but as we will see, White can cause us some headaches in both options. He must decide the character of the game now by choosing which direction to develop his f1-bishop.   6.e3  does not have its own significance because, after  6...O-O  , White should transpose to the main line with  7.Nc3  . }
6. Nc3 O-O 7. e3 Qe7
{ We reached a crossroads and White has a lot of plans. For Black, we want to play ...c5 at some point, but it all depends on our opponent's next move. }
8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bd3
{ It is possible to play a standard Cambridge Springs @@StartBracket@@Carlsbad@@EndBracket@@ structure by ...c6, ...Nbd7, ...Re8 as well, which is of course playable, but it is considered to be slightly inferior once White starts the minority attack on the queenside with b4-a4-b5. Bogo-Indian expert, Nikita Vitiugov, introduced a new plan here that has been followed by many strong grandmasters with good success lately. }
9... b6
{ Black would like to fight for the center with ...c5, using the fact that White cannot prevent it now with b4 @@StartBracket@@after which our structure might become a bit awkward@@EndBracket@@. }
10. O-O c5
{ The next few moves are important. If Black manages to develop the pieces, they will be perfectly fine, so White needs to act fast to have any hopes of an opening advantage. }
11. a3
{ This happened in a recent grandmaster encounter, Thybo-Sanal, Niksic 2021, but Black was completely fine. }
11... Bb7 12. Rfe1 Nbd7
{ Black's pieces are out which means that he stands fine. White decided to change the structure with dxc5. }
13. dxc5 bxc5 14. b4
{ Trying to create an isolated pawn on d5, and making use of the b7-bishop standing in the way of certain motifs. However, Black had great activity after ...Ne4. }
14... Ne4 15. Qb2 Rab8
{ We can say by now that maybe it is already Black who is trying to create complications. }
16. Bf1 Ba8
{ With a good position. We have analyzed similar structures in the main lines of the 4.e3 Nimzo-Indian, where Carlsen and other strong grandmasters had no issues with entering such isolated pawn structures, easily compensating with active piece play. }
