9... b6
{ Black would like to fight for the center with ...c5, using the fact that White cannot prevent it now with b4 @@StartBracket@@after which our structure might become a bit awkward@@EndBracket@@. }
10. O-O c5
{ The next few moves are important. If Black manages to develop the pieces, they will be perfectly fine, so White needs to act fast to have any hopes of an opening advantage. }
11. Rac1
{ This continuation has not been tried yet, but it needs to be checked whether White can quickly attack our hanging pawns or not. }
11... Nc6 { Tricky play, but it all seems to work. } 12. dxc5 bxc5
{ And now  13.Na4  is not dangerous because of  13...Ne4!  and the queen does not have a good place to go while taking the e4-knight causes problems after dxe4 as the knight this time has no decent place to go, but otherwise, the c5-pawn will be safe. }
13. Bb5 Bb7
{ Black needs ...Rfd8 and ...Rac8 to secure his pawns, therefore the critical test is going for the forced line... }
14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 { And now we have the beautiful... } 15... Nd4 16. Qxc5
{ Matters are forced. } 16... Nxf3+ 17. gxf3 Qf6 18. Be2 Rae8
{ Currently White is two pawns up, but his pawns are hanging and his king is weak. Black's compensation is sufficient to maintain the balance. }
19. Rfd1 Bxf3 { The f3-pawn is gone. } 20. Bxf3 Qxf3
{ White is still up a pawn, but because of his exposed king and the coming rook lift on the e-file, he does not have real hopes of standing better. }
