{ The break with ...c5 is of course the key. } 10. O-O cxd4 11. exd4
{ 11.Nxd4  is always met by  11...Bd7  ,  followed by ...Nc6 next move with an equal position.   And here, a very important move was played by GM Pavasovic. In case of normal development with ...Nc6 and ...Rd8, White could quickly create some dangerous threats with Rfe1 connected with the d5-break, using the misplacement of the black queen. }
11... Qc7
{ A huge tempo to get the queen out from under such motifs, after which natural development can continue. }
12. Qe2 Nc6
{ If Black has enough time to develop his pieces, Black is always fine in these isolated pawn structures. }
13. Rac1 Bd7
{ A novelty over the game Grachev-Pavasovic, Croatia 2009. Black quickly activates his rooks and  14.d5  just leads to simplifications. An active attempt could be Ne4. }
14. Ne4
{ With the idea of taking back with the queen followed by Bd3 or Ng5, but Black is not forced to take. }
14... Qf4 { And also  14...Nd5  provides equal chances. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Bogo Indian with 4.Bd2 Bxd2+ 5.Qxd2"]
[Black "5.Qxd2 d5 6.Nc3 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ We will not focus on other continuations such as  4...Qe7  ,  4...c5  or  4...a5  , as they lead to slightly worse positions, but of course, they are playable options. I myself have played  4...Qe7  and  4...c5  many times, but each time I ask myself why, when I am very sure that I will end up in a somewhat worse position straight from the opening! }
5. Qxd2
{ Why does White recapture with the queen? The answer is simple: White intends to develop the knight to c3, which is a much better position for the steed than on d2. }
5... d5
{ Here the ... d5-setup is considered to be the most solid for Black, but as we will see, White can cause us some headaches in both options. He must decide the character of the game now by choosing which direction to develop his f1-bishop.   6.e3  does not have its own significance because, after  6...O-O  , White should transpose to the main line with  7.Nc3  . }
6. Nc3 O-O 7. e3 Qe7
{ We reached a crossroads and White has a lot of plans. For Black, we want to play ...c5 at some point, but it all depends on our opponent's next move. }
8. Rc1
{ The most common move and I would say probably the most logical as well. It's a useful move whereby White holds the tension and prepares for the opening of the game, but does not want to lose a tempo with a bishop move in case Black takes on c4. }
8... dxc4
{ Most games continue with  8...Rd8  , but it is also very interesting to try the new and recently fashionable idea  8...b6  ,  while the safest decision to reach equality seems to be the standard simplification in the center. Despite having the extra and useful move Rc1 @@StartBracket@@compared to the 8.Bd3 lines@@EndBracket@@, White does not seem to be able to prove an advantage. }
9. Bxc4 c5
{ White needs to decide if he will enter an isolated pawn position or instead try to use his lead in development in the symmetrical structures after dxc5. }
10. dxc5 Rd8 { And now two plans can be tried... } 11. Qc2 Qxc5 12. Be2 Nc6
{ We are just making the typical moves. } 13. O-O Qe7
{ Removing the queen from the quick a3-b4 ideas and planning to develop his bishop next.  14.Ne4  Bd7  or  14.Rfd1  Bd7  are both equal. }
14. a3 { Now there is time to develop the bishop to a more active square. }
14... b6 { Followed by ...Bb7 and ...Rac8 with equality. } *

