9. Bxc4 c5
{ White needs to decide if he will enter an isolated pawn position or instead try to use his lead in development in the symmetrical structures after dxc5. }
10. dxc5 Rd8 { And now two plans can be tried... } 11. Qe2 Qxc5 12. O-O Nc6 13.
a3
{ This should be critical to try to gain some edge with b4, but Black has a reply known from similar positions.   13.Rfd1  just leads to semplifications and Black can equalize with  13...Rxd1+  14.Rxd1  Bd7= }
13... Ne5
{ Exchanging a pair of knights and getting out of all the tactical motifs at the same time. }
14. Nxe5 Qxe5
{ Black wants to play ...Bd7 with full equality. The only question is if there is some instant attack with f4. }
15. f4
{ But as we know, mostly such moves as f4 are not doing any harm to Black's position. }
15... Qa5 16. e4 { But counterplay arrives in time with ...Bd7/c6. } 16... Bd7
{ Moving the bishop to c6. } 17. e5 Ng4
{ Using the fact that the white king is vulnerable to a lot of motifs. } 18.
Kh1 { Or  18.Qxg4  Qc5+  winning back the piece. } 18... Nh6
{ Followed by ...Bc6 and ...Nf5 with an equal position. } *

