{ For players who like the Catalan and the 4.g3 Queen's Indian as White. } 5...
Ba6
{ The main line is  5...Bb7  , but this is a very interesting sideline that suddenly transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.g3  Ba6  5.Nbd2  Bb4+  line of the Queen's Indian Defense. Black is threatening to take on c4, which forces White to make an otherwise unnecessary decision. }
6. Qb3
{ The disadvantage of Qb3 is that after ...c5/...d5 pushes by Black it can easily come under unpleasant attacks. }
6... c5 7. Bg2 { The most natural move. } 7... Nc6
{ Developing the pieces to active squares and putting pressure on the white center. }
8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O O-O
{ The position is level and Black is ready to push ...d5 next. In these lines, one can see why provoking moves such as Nbd2 and Qb3 can prove useful, as they both block White from healthy development @@StartBracket@@Nc3 and b3@@EndBracket@@. }
