{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. g3
{ For players who like the Catalan and the 4.g3 Queen's Indian as White. } 5...
Ba6
{ The main line is  5...Bb7  , but this is a very interesting sideline that suddenly transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.g3  Ba6  5.Nbd2  Bb4+  line of the Queen's Indian Defense. Black is threatening to take on c4, which forces White to make an otherwise unnecessary decision. }
6. a3 { Very concrete play by White. } 6... Bxd2+ 7. Nxd2 Bb7
{ Just in time, before White plays Bg2 or e4 rendering the move 5...Ba6 senseless. Now, White needs to choose between two less attractive moves: f3 and Nf3. }
8. f3
{ With the idea of occupying the center with e4. Black must react accordingly. }
8... d5
{ Suddenly the White structure is slightly shaky; Black would like to play ...Nbd7 and ... c5. }
9. b4 O-O 10. Bb2 { And now I most like ...Qe7. } 10... Qe7
{ With the idea of preparing for the very quick opening of the game with ...c5, when Black does not decide yet if he will develop his knight on c6 or d7, and/or ...dxc4, after which the black rook can also join the game effectively from d8. }
