{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. g3
{ For players who like the Catalan and the 4.g3 Queen's Indian as White. } 5...
Ba6
{ The main line is  5...Bb7  , but this is a very interesting sideline that suddenly transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.g3  Ba6  5.Nbd2  Bb4+  line of the Queen's Indian Defense. Black is threatening to take on c4, which forces White to make an otherwise unnecessary decision. }
6. a3 { Very concrete play by White. } 6... Bxd2+ 7. Nxd2 Bb7
{ Just in time, before White plays Bg2 or e4 rendering the move 5...Ba6 senseless. Now, White needs to choose between two less attractive moves: f3 and Nf3. }
8. Nf3 O-O
{ Playing  8...Bxf3  is not the best: having 2 bishops vs 2 knights, White would likely enjoy a small but very stable advantage. }
9. Bg2
{ A well-known plan is coming from Black: for those who are familiar with the Queen's Indian Defense it should not come as a surprise... }
9... Be4
{ Black wants to play ...d5, ...Nbd7 and ...c5 without closing his bishop on b7. }
10. O-O
{ In similar positions, it is known idea for White to fight against the strong e4-bishop with Re1, Bf1 and Nd2 @@StartBracket@@White needs to preserve his two bishops to be able to fight for an advantage@@EndBracket@@ and when the bishop leaves from e4, either back with Bg2 or occupying the center with e4. However, in this version, it seems to be a bit slow, and Black arrives first with ...d5. }
10... d5 { 11.cxd5  Qxd5  followed by Nbd7 and c5 is also equal. } 11. b3
{ There are few ways to equalize here, the simplest being taking on c4. } 11...
dxc4 12. bxc4 Nbd7 { And ...c5 next, with an equal position. } *

