{ For players who like the Catalan and the 4.g3 Queen's Indian as White. } 5...
Ba6
{ The main line is  5...Bb7  , but this is a very interesting sideline that suddenly transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  b6  4.g3  Ba6  5.Nbd2  Bb4+  line of the Queen's Indian Defense. Black is threatening to take on c4, which forces White to make an otherwise unnecessary decision. }
6. Qc2 { The most logical, but  6.Qc2  also has its downside. } 6... Bb7 7. Bg2
{ The point of provoking Qc2 and then returning to b7 can be seen in two lines... One is to play ...Be4 now, with a big tempo and similar plans to those we saw in the 6. a3/8. Nf3 line.   The other is to challenge the center with  7...c5  , after which the typical Queen's Indian pawn sacrifice reaction with  8.d5  exd5  and then Nh4 is not supported by the queen from d1, which is important for White to win back the d5-pawn. }
7... c5 { We check the concrete moves. } 8. O-O { Leads to simplifications. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bxg2
{ Usually after the exchange of light-squared bishops, Black is doing fine. }
10. Kxg2 Qc8
{ A typical and flexible move. If White tries the aggressive  11.e4  , it can be met by  11...Nc6! }
11. b3 { Solid development. } 11... O-O 12. Bb2 Qb7+
{ Playing for a quick ...d5 break with equality. } *

