{ In almost all cases we will recapture with the bishop on c5. } 9. O-O O-O 10.
a3
{ Played by Tregubov and Ftacnik in a few games, but Black seems to have things under control in any event. }
10... a5 { We prevent White from playing b4. } 11. b3 Qe7
{ I like this principled move, which has positional and tactical ideas behind it. }
12. Bb2 d5
{ This is the point. Black would like to play ...Nbd7 with equality. } 13. cxd5
Rc8
{ A rather unpleasant intermediate move, as the queen does not have a good place to escape from the threats. }
14. Qb1 { This disconnects the white rooks and Black can already recapture. }
14... Nxd5
{ I see no reason for Black to be worse here.   Conclusion: 5.g3 is a very tricky line. We have to pay a lot of attention on the first moves of the line. As well, we get few different structures-which makes the things always complex. I would advice to pay serious attention how to act correctly against the 5.g3 but once you mastered the right set ups-I believe Black should be out of big dangerous of getting a nasty position.   In worse case a bit worse-which is objectively normal playing Black, in a good case we get equal play or even counter chances. }
