{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. e3
{ A solid move that often leads to structures known from the Queen's Indian Defense 4.e3 line, with a big difference - the knight is standing on d2 instead of the more active c3-square. Therefore, Black can choose to preserve his bishop. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3
{ 6.a3  Be7  should not make any difference, as White needs to complete development with Bd3 and O-O. }
6... d5
{ The most concrete way to fight for the center with the idea of following up with ...Bb7, ...Nbd7 and ...c5. }
7. O-O Bb7 8. a3 Be7 { Of course, we do not give away the bishop pair. } 9. b4
{ Is the other logical option to fight against ...c5 and at the same time trying to finish development with Bb2. White is also threatening positionally to push c5 himself, therefore Black needs to play ...c5. }
9... c5 10. bxc5 dxc4
{ Most games, including those by Karpov and Ivanchuk, have continued with  10...bxc5  11.Rb1  Ba6!  which also seems to be OK. But it is even easier to open the long diagonal first, in order to put the b7-bishop on a more active square. }
11. Nxc4 bxc5 12. Rb1 Bd5
{ This is the reason for including @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb2bppp/1p2pn2/2Pp4/2PP4/P2BPN2/3N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...dxc4  . }
13. Qe2
{ And now Black has a few good ways to play:  13...cxd4  and  13...Ne4  are possible, but I prefer ...Nc6. }
13... Nc6 14. dxc5 Ne4 { With equality, because the c5-pawn is going to fall. }
