[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Bogo Indian with 4.Nbd2 b6 5.e3 and 5.a3"]
[Black "5.e3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. e3
{ A solid move that often leads to structures known from the Queen's Indian Defense 4.e3 line, with a big difference - the knight is standing on d2 instead of the more active c3-square. Therefore, Black can choose to preserve his bishop. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3
{ 6.a3  Be7  should not make any difference, as White needs to complete development with Bd3 and O-O. }
6... d5
{ The most concrete way to fight for the center with the idea of following up with ...Bb7, ...Nbd7 and ...c5. }
7. O-O Bb7 8. a3 Be7 { Of course, we do not give away the bishop pair. } 9.
cxd5
{ This seems to be the right moment to change the structure, using the notion that Black should take back with the pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@since ...Nbd7 and ...c5 have not been played yet, after which taking back with a piece on d5 would also make sense@@EndBracket@@. }
9... exd5 10. b4
{ The only logical follow-up, otherwise Black plays ...Nbd7 and ... c5, or even immediately pushes ...c5 with the idea of ...Nc6, which is also possible. }
10... Nbd7
{ And now White needs to make a decision as Black is ready to push ...c5 again.  11.b5  is premature because Black can undermine it with  11...a6  and White cannot hold his structure with  12.a4  as the a1-rook is unprotected. Therefore, he must either allow Black to push ...c5 and try to get a small edge against the isolated pawn on d5, or instead try to fight against it with  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pbpnbppp/1p3n2/3p4/1P1P4/P2BPN2/3N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qb3  or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pbpnbppp/1p3n2/3p4/1P1P4/P2BPN2/3N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Rb1  ,  with an x-ray attack on the b7-bishop. }
11. Qb3
{ This move is a bit more natural than  11.Rb1  , and Black should play the same way against both. }
11... Bd6
{ Suddenly Black can switch his plan from playing ...c5, to ...Qe7 and ...Ne4. This is a known structure from the 4.e3 Nimzo and 4.e3 Queen's Indian lines, but in both cases, the white knight is on c3, which makes this whole idea of getting the knight to e4 much more difficult to execute, because Black always needs to deal with a hanging d5-pawn. This is a very key point, and the reason I suggest this line - with White's knight on d2, Black no longer faces that problem. }
12. Bb2 Qe7 { Black is ready to play ...Ne4. } 13. b5 a6 14. a4 axb5 15. axb5
Ne4
{ Black seems to be completely fine. The queen on e7 is nicely placed, connecting the rooks on the 8th rank and not allowing Ba3. }
*

