[Black "5.a3 with 6.Bxd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3
{ The main and most logical continuation: White immediately goes for the bishop pair, which should guarantee him a small but long-lasting edge. There are two alternatives as well: Bxd2 or Nxd2. }
5... Bxd2+
{ White has different set-ups depending on how he recaptures on d2. } 6. Bxd2
Bb7 { Simple development while awaiting White's next move. } 7. g3
{ The main alternative to  7.Bg5  after which Black also has a lot setups. Usually Black aims for ...O-O, ...Be4, ...a5, ...d6 in various move orders, with a slightly worse @@StartBracket@@because of White's bishop pair@@EndBracket@@, but very stable position. However, I propose instead a little-seen but very straightforward move... }
7... d5
{ This has been played only three times, and by weaker players. All three games continued with cxd5. }
8. cxd5
{ Looks like a small improvement for White, although Black's position remains fine. }
8... Bxd5 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O
{ And Black is ready to push ...c5 next. White has two plans now, either allow it and try to use the fact that the position is opening and the power of the two bishops might reveal itself, or instead try to fight against it with b4. }
11. b4 { Logical, but Black seems to be able to play his plan anyway. } 11...
c5 12. dxc5 bxc5
{ If White just ignores this, his minimal advantage should disappear. Usually, the critical move in similar positions is to try b5. }
13. b5 { But in this position it is a mistake. } 13... a6
{ Either the b5-pawn becomes very weak, or after  14.bxa6  Rxa6  - followed by ...Qa8 - the a-pawn might become a real target. The bishop on d5 is a real powerhouse in this position. }
