{ The main and most logical continuation: White immediately goes for the bishop pair, which should guarantee him a small but long-lasting edge. There are two alternatives as well: Bxd2 or Nxd2. }
5... Bxd2+
{ White has different set-ups depending on how he recaptures on d2. } 6. Bxd2
Bb7 { Simple development while awaiting White's next move. } 7. Bg5
{ The most consequent continuation after Bxd2 - White activates his bishop before playing e3. If White wants to play a  7.e3  setup instead, then it is much more logical to take back with the queen on d2 as the bishop should develop to b2 in that case. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 d6
{ Once again we are switching from the idea of playing ...d5, to ...d6 instead. }
9. e3
{ Here again, I basically suggest a novelty with only a few games in the database. Most games continue with  9...Nbd7  or  9...g5  ,  when Black often eliminates the g3-bishop but ends up in a slightly worse position because of the inferior pawn structure. }
9... Qe7 { A flexible move; Black does not show his cards just yet. } 10. Nd2
{ 10.Bd3  doesn't look right at this moment as it walks into  10...e5  . }
10... c5
{ This is another point of 9...Qe7. Now that the knight has left the f3 square, Black might put pressure on the center with ...Nc6. White also needs to solve his king issues but playing  11.Bd3  is premature as Black can simply collect the g2-pawn, after pushing ...g5. }
11. dxc5
{ And here Black also has a choice. It is possible to take back with  11...dxc5  after which the critical line is  12.Be2  Nc6  13.Qc2   13.O-O?  g5  14.Bg3  h5  is strong.  13...O-O  14.O-O  and now  14...Ne5  followed by ...Ng6. White might have a very minimal advantage, but it does not look like anything we need be afraid of. However, Black can also keep the position more dynamic and play instead ...bxc5. }
11... bxc5 12. b4
{ A typical move for such structures, but White delays his development a bit. }
12... cxb4 13. axb4 O-O
{ And Black might create some confusion by quickly attacking the b4-pawn, for example with ...Nc6, while White is trying to complete development. }
