{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3
{ The main and most logical continuation: White immediately goes for the bishop pair, which should guarantee him a small but long-lasting edge. There are two alternatives as well: Bxd2 or Nxd2. }
5... Bxd2+
{ White has different set-ups depending on how he recaptures on d2. } 6. Nxd2
{ A rare continuation. The only consequent idea behind this move would be to occupy the center with e4. }
6... Bb7 7. Qc2
{ Trying to get e4 without creating a weakness. In case of  7.f3  , we reach the kind of position that arises in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p1pp1ppp/1p2pn2/8/1bPP4/5N2/PP1NPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.g3  Ba6  6.a3  Bxd2+  7.Nxd2  Bb7  8.f3  line. }
7... O-O
{ A rare move, which has only been seen in a few games. It appears that Black is simply ignoring the idea of e4, but he actually prepares strong counterplay... }
8. e4 c5
{ This is already a novelty, but a very logical one to explode the white center while he is behind in development. }
9. d5
{ It looks logical to close the position with a big space advantage, but Black can create counterplay with ...exd5. }
9... exd5 10. cxd5 Re8
{ White is missing one tempo to claim a big advantage. Ideally, he should have his bishop on d3 and play O-O, but now the d5-pawn is hanging. The only sensible way to unpin the king on the e-file is with Be2. }
11. Be2 Qe7 { But still Black wins a pawn as both central pawns are hanging. }
