[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Bogo Indian with 4.Nbd2 b6 5.e3 and 5.a3"]
[Black "5.a3 with 6.Qxd2 #5"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3
{ The main and most logical continuation: White immediately goes for the bishop pair, which should guarantee him a small but long-lasting edge. There are two alternatives as well: Bxd2 or Nxd2. }
5... Bxd2+
{ White has different set-ups depending on how he recaptures on d2. } 6. Qxd2
{ This is the most common move, with the clear intention to develop the c1-bishop on the long diagonal. }
6... Bb7
{ White needs to decide where he wants to develop his f1-bishop. He has two options, but the main and most common move by far is e3. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3
{ Might look a bit more active than Be2, but for several reasons, it is better to choose the main line. The bishop from e2 protects the knight, so White never needs to worry about Bxf3, and after O-O, White plans to continue with b4, Bb2, and Rfd1, when the bishop on d3 is just blocking the d-file.   One of the main resources available to Black is ...Ne4 and ...f5, when a common reaction is Ne1 and f3 for White, but here as well the bishop on e2 fits better to the plan. After all this, it is understandable why 8.Be2 is the main move. }
8... c5
{ My suggestion, which is not the main move in the position, but very logical, especially, that the bishop is on d3. Black might also consider now changing the pawn structure with @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb1p1ppp/1p2pn2/2p5/2PP4/P2BPN2/1P1Q1PPP/R1B1K2R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  9...Bxf3  10.gxf3  cxd4  11.exd4  Nc6  , when the white pawns are shaky. }
9. b4
{ Played in Portisch-Timman, Montpellier 1985, but I can suggest an improvement on Black's play now. }
9... d5 10. dxc5 { If  10.cxd5  Qxd5  looks equal. } 10... bxc5 11. O-O
{ 11.Bb2  transposes to the 9.dxc5 line. } 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4
{ In this whole line, White is hoping to get a small edge with the bishop pair, but the black pieces will be very active. Also, the pawns are about to be eliminated on the queenside, making any White advantage symbolic, if there is any. }
12... Ne4 13. Qc2 cxb4 14. axb4 Nd7 15. Bb2 Qe7
{ Followed by ... Rfc8, and Black is very solid. } *

