8... c5
{ My suggestion, which is not the main move in the position, but very logical, especially, that the bishop is on d3. Black might also consider now changing the pawn structure with @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb1p1ppp/1p2pn2/2p5/2PP4/P2BPN2/1P1Q1PPP/R1B1K2R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  9...Bxf3  10.gxf3  cxd4  11.exd4  Nc6  , when the white pawns are shaky. }
9. dxc5 bxc5 10. b4
{ The consequent follow up, otherwise Black might play ...a5. } 10... d5
{ 11.O-O  would transpose to the 9.b4 d5 line. } 11. Bb2
{ We are following the game Kozul-Macieja, Portoroz 2001, where Black should have played ...dxc4. }
11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nbd7
{ The alternative  12...cxb4  13.axb4  a6  also looks equal, as Black quickly attacks the b4-pawn with ...Nc6. }
13. O-O { 13.b5  would be a mistake in view of  13...Ne4  with ...Qa5+ next. }
13... Nb6 14. Be2 Ne4
{ The black pieces are becoming very active again, securing enough compensation against the bishop pair. Also, the white queen cannot find a good place to go. Exchanging the queens should not cause Black any problems. }
15. Qe1 Rc8 16. Rd1 Qe7
{ And White can't prove the strength of the bishop pair; Black has become too active and equalized. }
