[Black "5.a3 with 6.Qxd2 #10"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3
{ The main and most logical continuation: White immediately goes for the bishop pair, which should guarantee him a small but long-lasting edge. There are two alternatives as well: Bxd2 or Nxd2. }
5... Bxd2+
{ White has different set-ups depending on how he recaptures on d2. } 6. Qxd2
{ This is the most common move, with the clear intention to develop the c1-bishop on the long diagonal. }
6... Bb7
{ White needs to decide where he wants to develop his f1-bishop. He has two options, but the main and most common move by far is e3. }
7. e3 O-O 8. b4
{ This move has been played by many strong grandmasters, including Carlsen against me in Germany 2015, but it does not look right after all, because it allows Black to create counterplay on the queenside with ...a5. }
8... a5 9. b5
{ This is the question, but having included the a5-b5 pair of moves seems to me like a clear achievment for Black. }
9... c5
{ Instead of the most common  9...d6  , I like the way Timman played against Shirov in Helsingor 2016. }
10. dxc5 { Is not good structurally as Black plays ...Ne4/c5. } 10... Ne4 11.
Qd4 Nxc5
{ The only question is if White manages to prevent us from completing development. }
12. Bb2 { White must act fast. } 12... f6 13. Rd1 e5 14. Qd2
{ 14.Qd6  is met by  14...Ne4  .  And now the engine suggests a very instructive pawn sacrifice with ...d6. }
14... d6
{ Having in mind to play ...Ne4 and ...Nd7-c5. White should accept the pawn. }
15. Qxd6 Qxd6 16. Rxd6 Nbd7
{ And here the black pieces are so much superior to the white ones, that despite the extra pawn it is White who needs to be careful not to get into trouble. }
17. Be2 Rfd8 18. Rd1 { 18.O-O  Ne4  19.Rdd1  Ndc5  is even better for Black. }
18... Na4 19. Ba1 Ndc5 { Black pieces are dominating the game. } 20. O-O Be4
{ We can clearly see the domination of the black pieces: the a1-bishop is kind of trapped and Black is also threatening ...Nb3. }
21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rd1 Rc8 { With full compensation for the pawn. } *

