{ The main and most logical continuation: White immediately goes for the bishop pair, which should guarantee him a small but long-lasting edge. There are two alternatives as well: Bxd2 or Nxd2. }
5... Bxd2+
{ White has different set-ups depending on how he recaptures on d2. } 6. Qxd2
{ This is the most common move, with the clear intention to develop the c1-bishop on the long diagonal. }
6... Bb7
{ White needs to decide where he wants to develop his f1-bishop. He has two options, but the main and most common move by far is e3. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Be2
{ This is the most common continuation by far, followed by developing the other bishop on b2. }
8... d5
{ Yet again, I would like to offer you this very rare line. The position is full of interesting and untried ideas that I would like to share with you. }
9. b4
{ Just as in the 8.b4 line, this allows Black to start his counterplay on the queenside with ...a5. }
9... a5 { This is already a novelty. } 10. b5 c5
{ Black always uses this plan, which is possible because the queen on d2 is standing in the line of ...Ne4.  11.O-O  can simply be met by  11...Nbd7  and then ...Rc8, ...Qe7, ...Rfd8. }
11. dxc5 Ne4 { Black maintains his good structure after this. } 12. Qc2 Nxc5
13. Bb2 Nbd7 14. O-O Rc8
{ We have reached a playable position with equal chances. } *

