[Black "5.a3 with 6.Qxd2 #21"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3
{ The main and most logical continuation: White immediately goes for the bishop pair, which should guarantee him a small but long-lasting edge. There are two alternatives as well: Bxd2 or Nxd2. }
5... Bxd2+
{ White has different set-ups depending on how he recaptures on d2. } 6. Qxd2
{ This is the most common move, with the clear intention to develop the c1-bishop on the long diagonal. }
6... Bb7
{ White needs to decide where he wants to develop his f1-bishop. He has two options, but the main and most common move by far is e3. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Be2
{ This is the most common continuation by far, followed by developing the other bishop on b2. }
8... d5
{ Yet again, I would like to offer you this very rare line. The position is full of interesting and untried ideas that I would like to share with you. }
9. b3
{ The most typical reaction to the ...d5 move - White would like to keep his center and develop his bishop on b2. }
9... c5
{ Of course, the most natural move is  9...Nbd7  which is what happened in most of the games, but this idea looks really interesting. There are no games with the upcoming variations, as in the two games in the database, Black just transposed with ...Nbd7 next move. As you will soon see, we have other ideas in mind! }
10. dxc5 Ne4 { A nice intermediate move. } 11. Qc2
{ So far we have seen this idea in different lines with the b4/...a5/b5 moves included when the black knight finds a very nice outpost on c5 at the end.   Now Black's idea is different, as after  11...Nxc5  12.b4  could be played.  Black should instead play ...dxc4. }
11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nd7
{ With the idea of developing first with ...Rc8 and only then ...Ndxc5.  13.cxb6  is always met by  13...Nxb6  ,  when ...Rc8 comes before White can complete development and consolidate his position. White cannot preserve his extra pawn. }
13. O-O
{ 13.c6  looks like a stylish move, but it just helps Black - he can simply take  13...Bxc6  . }
13... Rc8
{ 14.cxb6  Nxb6  is not enough for an advantage; White needs to hurry with development. }
14. Bb2 Ndxc5 15. b4
{ Black does not need to retreat, but instead can take the knight to a4. }
15... Na4 16. Qxa4 Rxc4 17. Qxa7 Nd6
{ 17...Bd5  with the idea of playing ...Ng5 next is also possible. Now, White needs to find the only move. }
18. Be5 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nf5
{ With a very dangerous position for White as his king is exposed and Bg3 will not secure its safety because of ...h5,...h4. }
